<HEADLINE>Drive         to boost food and drink earnings</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241217</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN initiative has been launched which could boost the earnings of the region's
food and drink industry by up to #110m by 1998. The aim of Scottish Enterprise
Tayside's Food and Drink Strategy is to increase the industry's annual turnover
by 33% to #445m, with exports rising by 60%, from their 1994 level of #25m up
to #40m in 1998.
Central to the strategy will be a scheme to assist selected companies to enter
new markets, and the successful Meet the Buyer programme will continue to
introduce Tayside companies to top retailers.
The focus will be on structured initiatives, progressed and funded in distinct
stages, while ensuring companies gain improved access to vital market
information.
The Perth Food Festival in 1994 and 1995 helped to promote Perth and
Perthshire's food producers and traders and enhance the area's reputation as
home to some of Scotland's finest hotels, pubs and restaurants.
It is also a festival for local people, all of whom are invited to take part in
the series of events which this year took place over nine days in May. The
Perth Partnership stepped in to support the Festivals' promotional activities,
and the Perth City Hotel Managers' Association organised the programme of
events.
Highlight of the festival was the Gala Dinner in May, which brought together 12
Perthshire chefs and their teams to produce a seven-course banquet.
As the association's chairman, Douglas Stanfield, of the Station Hotel, said:
``It is unusual in that it brings together different hotels which would
normally be competing with each other.''
Since it was established in 1979 Highland Spring Ltd has invested more than
#30m establishing one of the most modern natural mineral water plants in Europe
at Blackford in Perthshire.
Today it is the largest producer of natural mineral water in the UK, and
exports to more than 30 countries world-wide. The company is the largest
employer in Blackford, with some 130 staff.
The 1995 figures from the British Market Research Bureau show that Highland
Spring retained its No.1 slot for the third year running as Britain's favourite
bottled water.
A light, fresh water with a clean taste and low mineral content, it is
available as still, light sparkling or sparkling.
The water is sourced from the Ochil Hills in Perthshire, and its catchment area
of 2000 acres is protected so that the source is completely free from any kind
of farming, industry or building. This prevents pesticides, fertilisers or
animals from polluting the rainfall as it slowly filters through the rich
mineral-bearing rock strata.
Rainwater takes some 30 years to reach the source hundreds of feet below the
Ochil Hills. The rainfall absorbs the natural minerals as it passes through
thousands of fissures in the layers of rock.
To qualify as a ``natural mineral water'', strict EU and UK regulations must be
met. The water must undergo tests which can take up to two years and be bottled
at source, receiving no treatment other than filtering.
A Perth company which has more than doubled its workforce in the past 18 months
has had its plans for continued growth boosted by a major grant from the
European Union.
Perth Fresh Meat Ltd, which has more than 350 employees at two sites on the
Inveralmond Industrial Estate, has been awarded #275,000 under an EU initiative
to assist firms which process and market agricultural products.
The grant, which was won with the aid of Scottish Enterprise Tayside, will help
to spur on the firm's plans to increase the Perth workforce by up to a further
150 employees over the next two years.
A key supplier of packaged beef, lamb, and game to leading UK supermarket
chains and the export market, the company will use the funding to invest in
leading-edge packaging technology.
Morris Bond, chairman and chief executive of the Beck Food Group, parent
company of Perth Fresh Meat Ltd, said: ``Last year we succeeded in winning
significant new business with some of the UK's top retailers.
``I am delighted that we have been successful in obtaining this grant from the
EU which will help our company to continue its expansion into these markets.''
Alastair Byres, responsible for the food and drink sector with Scottish
Enterprise Tayside, said: ``This award will enable one of Perth's major
employers to win new orders in an intensely competitive market.''
</TEXT>
