<HEADLINE>India tries to deal for release of sick hostage.Kashmiri militant offered fast trial</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SHEIKH MUSHTAQ</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241219</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INDIAN negotiators have offered guerrilla abductors a deal to free a Western
hostage in Kashmir, a senior official said today.
The official, who declined to be named, told foreign correspondents in Srinagar
that India could offer a guarantee to Al-Faran militants through independent
diplomats that jailed militant Masood Azhar would be tried speedily, possibly
leading to his freedom.
The negotiators are trying to secure the release of American Don Hutchings,
said to be critically ill. Hutchings is known to be suffering from frostbite.
A senior official said today that Briton Paul Wells, who was suffering from
viral fever, had now recovered.
Fellow Briton Keith Mangan and German Dirk Hasert are the other hostages,
kidnapped while trekking in the Himalayan region. A fifth captive, Norwegian
Hans Christian Ostroe, was found beheaded on August 13.
The latest approach over Hutchings signalled an easing of procedures linked to
tough anti-terrorist laws, under which suspected terrorists can be held in
custody for long periods without trial.
Officials in Srinagar, the summer capital of the troubled Jammu and Kashmir
state, confirmed Al-Faran's offer for the exchange of a sick hostage earlier
this week.
India has officially refused to exchange prisoners for hostages, but says it is
willing to release Kashmiri prisoners as part of a routine review. It has ruled
out a rescue raid, saying it could endanger the lives of the hostages.
A senior official in Srinagar, who declined to be named, had said earlier this
week that Al-Faran wanted India to free Azhar, a leader of the Pakistan-based
Muslim group Harkat-ul-Ansar.
Indian officials say Harkat-ul-Ansar has a large number of Afghan war
activists, helping a five-year-old rebellion in the province - the only state
in India with a majority of Muslims - where some 20,000 have been killed since
1990.
After Al-Faran captured the tourists in July, it demanded the release of 22
jailed separatists, including three members of Harkat-ul-Ansar, in exchange for
the hostages.
It later softened its demand, asking for the release of 15 separatists
including Harkat-ul-Ansar members.
India claims Al-Faran, which was unknown before the kidnappings, is a front for
Harkat-ul-Ansar, and accuses Pakistan of arming and training guerrillas
spearheading the separatist revolt in the disputed region.
Pakistan, which rules over one third of Kashmir, says it provides only
diplomatic and moral support to the rebels.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
