<HEADLINE>Employers who have found Perth and Kinross the perfect location for expanding businesses Small towns with big appeal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241220</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR many people one of the great appeals of working in Perth and Kinross
District is the chance to live in one of the area's attractive small towns and
villages, such as Crieff.
Today the town's residents and its visitors are a far cry from the bandits,
horse thieves and drovers who congregated in this frontier town on the fringe
of the Highlands in the years up to the '45 uprising.
Set on a steep hill facing south over the valley of the River Earn at the hub
of old drove roads, Crieff was once a thriving cattle market. In Victorian
times it became a spa town, and the Crieff Hydro is nowadays an institution
among families who enjoy healthy, traditional holidays.
Many of the town's 6000 residents commute the 17 miles to Perth for work at at
Gloags, Bells or General Accident, however, this population is swelled by
visitors in the summer. There is no rail station but new roads and the Dunblane
by-pass mean that the town is only about an hour's drive from Glasgow and
Edinburgh.
Surrounding Crieff are visitor attractions such as Buchan Pottery, Innerpeffray
Library and the Glenturret distillery. Tourism provides the main employment in
the town, with some 250 staff working at the recently reopened Crieff Hydro.
The Hydro and its many facilities, include tennis, swimming, yoga, riding and a
golf centre, attracts 110,000 visitors a year. Residents can also enjoy the
leisure facilities at the hotel's Lagoon Club.
Many of the shops in Crieff set out their stalls for tourists and between a
mixture of craft shops and national stores are a host of cafes and eating
places. The Athena Greek restaurant currently enjoys preference among many.
Crieff primary, St Dominics and Crieff High School provide schooling in the
public sector and, Ardvreck preparatory school and Morrisons Academy for day
pupils and boarders, in the independent.
Golf, hunting, shooting, fishing and watersports are all on the doorstep. And
in Macrosty Park tennis, putting, and picnic spots can be enjoyed amid acres of
pleasant walks.
There are many traditional Victorian and Edwardian residential properties in
Crieff, especially around the Hydro on the north side of town, as well as some
older flats and new build.
Tay Homes has a development on the eastern edge of town. On the western edge,
Bett is building four-bedroom family homes, and in the town Thomas Mitchell is
building bungalows. Other streets have been developed on a small scale by local
builders such as Shaws, Dodds and George McOmish. New development was limited
until recently by the town's sewage capacity.
Kate Beattie, a resident for eight years and property manager at Drysdale
Anderson, said: ``We are minutes from the countryside and I go hillwalking to
Aberfeldy on a Sunday. Countryside properties are always popular. Everyone is
looking for an idyllic cottage set in a few acres with a stream and roses by
the door.''
The property market in Crieff tends to be locally based, using local estate
agents. Nik Mayall, of Clark Thomson in Crieff, said: ``Houses are considerably
cheaper here than in Dunblane and Perth. Stone-built semis costing #85,000 to
#90,000 in Crieff would cost #120,000 in Perth, and the differential in
stone-built detached is even greater.''
The holiday home market is small but busy. Helen Tocher, at General Accident
Property in Perth, said: ``We are often asked about Crieff. In some months we
have up to a dozen houses, and then none for a month or two.''
</TEXT>
