<HEADLINE>Patten rules out Beijing shadow</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975241221</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HONG KONG: Governor Chris Patten has vowed to veto any attempt by China to set
up a rival government-in-waiting well ahead of the 1997 handover.
He was responding to predictions by an influential Hong Kong adviser to
Beijing, who set alarm bells ringing in the colony when he said China would
establish a shadow government about six months before the deadline.
Talks offered
ABUJA: Nigeria's military government said it was willing to hold talks with the
Commonwealth to resolve the row over the hanging of nine minority rights
activists. ``We resolved to educate our friends, who were hoodwinked into
taking their positions,'' said junta member Commodore Victor Ombu.
Graf: `no deal'
BONN: The Finance Minister of Steffi Graf's home state of Baden-Wuerttemberg
yesterday denied striking any preferential financial deals with the German
tennis star, who is under investigation for suspected tax evasion. Gerhard
Mayer-Vorfelder was being questioned by a parliamentary committee investigating
the case. Graf's imprisoned father Peter is expected to appear before it next
month.
Bible found
BONN: The Latin Bible used by Protestant reformer Martin Luther to translate
Christianity's holy book into German has been found after being lost for over
200 years. The volume, signed by Luther and covered with notes he made in its
margins, was among thousands of Bibles stored at the Wuerttemberg State Library
in Stuttgart, its librarian claimed.
Iraqi blast
NICOSIA: An opposition broadcast claimed a local headquarters of the country's
ruling Baath party was blown up in northern Iraq last week, killing 12 security
guards and wounding more than 20.
Rapists lose
STRASBOURG: The European Court of Human Rights has upheld decisions by British
courts to send two men to jail for raping their wives despite their protests
that 17th-century rulings effectively said this was not a crime. The two men
were sentenced to three and five years in prison in 1990 and 1991.
Polio drive
NEW DELHI: Some 75 million Indian children under four will be vaccinated
against polio next month in one of the most ambitious chapters of a worldwide
drive to eradicate the crippling disease by the end of the century. Rotary
International is helping to fund and organise the drive.
It's just bull
CANBERRA: Australia's sex industry is attempting to stop the export of tons of
bull's penises to Asia, claiming they do not work as a male aphrodisiac. ``The
libido-enhancing claims are fraudulent in the extreme,'' said Robbie Swan, a
spokesman for the Eros Foundation. ``They are about as much use as a bull's
tongue.''
Skyscraper fire
NEW YORK: Fifteen people were slightly injured and the Empire State Building
was evacuated on Tuesday night when an electrical fire sent smoke spiralling
from the basement up through the famous Manhattan skyscraper.
Landmine plea
GENEVA: The Red Cross is launching its first global advertising campaign, to
swing public opinion in a battle against landmines, which kill 2000 people per
month.
Clancy duped
WASHINGTON: Thriller writer Tom Clancy, author of The Hunt for Red October, was
reportedly the biggest loser in an alleged #4m shares fraud. He told the
Washington Post he invested almost #1m of his own money and #350,000 on behalf
of others in what authorities said was an illegal, unregistered mutual fund
after striking up a friendship with Virginian Richard Scott during a baseball
game.
</TEXT>
