<HEADLINE>Daughter pleads to let mother die</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241222</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN will tonight publicly plead for a court to let her mother die, in a
case which will make legal history.
In Scotland's first ``right to die'' case, the Court of Session in Edinburgh
will decide next week if Mrs Janet Johnson, 53, should have her feeding tube
withdrawn.
She has been in a ``persistent vegetative state'' for three years with no
evident hope of recovery.
Her daughter, Ms Linda Bryce, will tell TV viewers tonight: ``I just hope the
court give us the sanction and let her go, because it'll be the kindest thing
they ever do, kinder to my mother and kinder to the family.
``She definitely died three and a half years ago. It's definitely not my mother
in that bed,'' she tells BBC Scotland's Frontline Scotland TV programme.
In a landmark ruling in England, the House of Lords ruled that Hillsborough
football stadium victim Tony Bland could have his artificial feeding tube
withdrawn, but Mrs Johnston's is the first case in Scottish law.
Law Hospital in Lanarkshire and Mrs Johnston's family are agreed that she
should be allowed to die with dignity, but the case is going to the Court of
Session as the legal position in Scotland is unclear.
</TEXT>
