<HEADLINE>Suicide girl may have seen murder</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241224</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TEENAGER Kelly Holland - found hanged in her cell in Cornton Vale Prison near
Stirling in June - could have taken crucial evidence about the unsolved death
of Hamilton student Amanda Duffy to her grave.
The fatal accident inquiry that opened yesterday into the deaths of Kelly and
fellow inmate Arlene Elliot, both 17, heard evidence from Kelly's father and
Arlene's mother of the changes in their daughters from confident schoolgirls to
suicidal teenagers.
Arlene's mother, Roseanne McKay, 40, of Caledonian Crescent, Edinburgh, said
drink and drugs had ruined her daughter's life. She said that until she was 14,
Arlene was a quiet girl. ``She used to play the cello and go to church. The
drugs changed her,'' she said.
But the most dramatic evidence came from Kelly's father, Mr Edward Holland, 44.
He said Kelly, of Hillhouse Road, Hamilton, changed overnight from cheerful
schoolgirl to suicidal teenager when she went missing in May, 1992.
Mr Holland told the inquiry: ``She was missing at the same time that Amanda
Duffy was found murdered in Hamilton. She was found 100 yards from where
Amanda's body was found.
``Whether she saw anything, we don't know, but I thought there was a dramatic
change in Kelly since then. She had been so bright in school it made you happy
inside to talk about her.''
Mr Holland said his daughter immediately began to exhibit signs of self-harm.
She was found wandering the streets of Newcastle with a bottle of 100
paracetamol tablets in her pocket.
She was sent to Kerelaw Assessment Centre in Ayrshire, where she was found cut
and bleeding, apparently after falling through a window.
She was sent to a psychiatric hospital in Livingston, where she cut her hands
and face. She continued to try to harm herself - throwing herself out of a
second-floor window just a few weeks before she died.
He said: ``We asked all sorts of people for help - social workers,
psychiatrists, key workers. Nobody gave us any answers.''
Mr Holland said his daughter's behaviour became increasingly bizarre. She would
go missing for days at a time, always leaving the house by the window, never
the door. When she was found again, she did not seem to realise where she was.
He said a noose had been found in her cell at Cornton Vale during previous
remands, and he and his wife had tried repeatedly to warn the prison
authorities she was suicidal.
The inquiry heard that Kelly was remanded in custody by a sheriff at Hamilton
on June 23 after being arrested for being disorderly.
Police who picked her up in a Hamilton park found her hiding a piece of broken
glass up her sleeve.
A deputy prosecutor in the procurator-fiscal's office in Hamilton was so
concerned that she telephoned police at the court to ask them to warn Cornton
Vale that Kelly might try to kill herself.
But Constable Adam Angus, whom the depute fiscal had said she had telephoned,
claimed he never received any such call.
Mr Holland, who was in court the day his daughter was remanded in custody, said
she was very distressed as she was led to the cells, and he had intended to
phone the prison the next day to warn staff she could be suicidal.
He never got the chance. She was found hanged in her cell at 1.30am.
Arlene, of Dumbarton Road, Glasgow, was found hanged in her cell four days
later.
Both parents criticised the prison system for not taking better care of their
daughters.
The inquiry continues.
Amanda Duffy's father, Mr Joe Duffy, said yesterday it would be tragic if Kelly
had kept quiet about information about his daughter's death and taken it to the
grave.
He said he wanted to talk to Kelly's father about his suspicions.
</TEXT>
