<HEADLINE>Children face health worries</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241225</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHILDREN as young as 11 are already worrying about their weight, their health,
and their job prospects, a major survey of schoolchildren in the West of
Scotland revealed yesterday.
The Medical Research Council, which published the findings, said most of the
3000 children in the study were healthy, happy, and optimistic about the future.
Nevertheless Drs Patrick West and Helen Sweeting, from the council's Medical
Sociology Unit at Glasgow University, were taken aback at the number who had
been suffering symptoms of physical or psychological problems.
More than half said they had had headaches, stomach aches, and colds or flu
during the previous month, and one in three said they had been unhappy or had
difficulty sleeping.
Other complaints included loneliness outside school (19%), in school (9%),
being teased (14%), and being bullied (5%). All of these experiences were
associated with poorer psychological health and lower self-esteem.
The researchers found that 11% of girls and 7% of boys were on diets of one
sort or another.
``We don't know how many were on diets prescribed by their doctors for medical
reasons,'' Dr West said yesterday.
The findings are the first to be released from a research project that will
track the 3000 through from their final year at primary school until the age of
16 and possibly beyond, with the aim of mapping out the factors that influence
teenage lifestyles.
Dr West said the findings called into question the traditional idea that this
particular age was the healthiest time in people's lives.
</TEXT>
