<HEADLINE>Lockerbie curbs on Libya to stay UNITED NATIONS: The UN</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975241226</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Security Council reviewed but made no change in sanctions imposed on Libya
since 1992 after it failed to surrender two suspects in the 1988 Lockerbie
bombing.
British UN representative Sir John Weston told reporters after closed-door
consultations that the sanctions, which include an air embargo, a ban on the
sale of weapons to Libya, and the downgrading of diplomatic links, will remain.
