<HEADLINE>Waverley's #15m lifeline will safeguard future of Monktonhall but end worker control Miners face  up to the end of their dream</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER, LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241227</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE 200 miners of Monktonhall colliery in Midlothian, who each invested #10,000
to re-open it three years ago as a co-operative, have been offered a #15m
lifeline which would cost them their dream.
Waverley Mining Finance, which helped save the pit, has offered 10,000 ordinary
company shares in exchange for the miners' 51% holding which would mean the
miners losing control. The Waverley shares are currently trading on the stock
market at 100p.
Waverley director Anthony Johnston warned the pit would close if the offer was
rejected.
``We couldn't go on supporting it. The board of Monktonhall would have to take
the decision to just shut it down,'' he said.
Yesterday, miners forecast the offer would be accepted.
Waverley stated that, if the share offer was given the go-ahead, it would
result in #15m being put into the pit, allowing re-investment in machinery, and
the opening of a new coal face which could extend the life of Monktonhall for
at least 16 years.
Ironically, the offer of a financial lifeline from Waverley comes as the 240
miner owners of Tower Colliery in Mid Glamorgan announced profits of #2m,
having invested #8000 each.
Monktonhall has been losing money but Mr Johnston said an investment of #15m
could see production in the opening of a new coal face rising from 275,000
tonnes a year to 540,000, also providing an additional 80 jobs, including
apprenticeships in the industry.
He said the proposed issue of shares would be subscribed by institutions and
current shareholders, amounting to #5.5m, with a similar amount ploughed in by
the company. An additional #4.1m would be received by the Department of Trade
and Industry's coal subsidy scheme.
Should the miners - who have three weeks to decide - accept the share offer,
they would not be allowed to cash them in, or trade them, for three years.
When Waverley stepped in with cash aid, it had 49% of the shares, with the
miners' consortium holding the balance.
Mr Johnston added: ``Yes, it is a buy-out proposal, but we want to protect the
interests of the miners.''
The man who led the battle to reopen Monktonhall, former miner Jackie Aitchison
- now personnel manager at the pit - described the offer as ``fantastic''.
``Not only is it safeguarding jobs and allowing continuity of employment, it is
going to create 80 jobs, which will include trainee miner apprenticeships.''
Shareholder Edward Kimain, 59, of Penicuik, a miner for 30 years - the last
three at Monktonhall - summed up pitmen's feelings.
``It's not too bad really. We have not actually got much choice. If we don't
accept it, we'll lose the pit. This way we'll get something out of it.''
Colleague Paul Davidson, 27, of Edinburgh, said: ``It secures the mine's
future. It is basically good for the company.''
Later yesterday, Midlothian MP Eric Clarke, former general secretary of the
National Union of Mineworkers in Scotland, said: ``I hope the company puts its
money where its mouth is, protecting the jobs of the Monktonhall men, and
providing extra jobs, which I would certainly welcome.''
Mr George Bolton, president of the NUM in Scotland, added: ``There are massive
coal reserves able to be worked from Monktonhall, but it does require
investment in new machinery to reach them.
``It is capable of providing quality coal for the domestic and industrial
market, and if more jobs are available, I am delighted.''
</TEXT>
