<HEADLINE>Doubt cast on Chirac reason for tests amid fresh nuclear outrage</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241228</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FRANCE'S fourth nuclear test in the South Pacific provoked outrage today while
a French expert expressed doubts that computer simulation could viably replace
actual testing as intended by authorities.
President Jacques Chirac has said France will probably stage six tests rather
than the eight he originally announced in June. But he denied the series has
been cut short because of the protests.
Chirac has promised to sign a treaty banning all tests forever once the series
is completed, by May 31 at the latest. He claims France needs the tests to
validate a new warhead for its submarine-based missiles and acquire simulation
capacity.
However a critic of Chirac with close ties to nuclear-test experts released a
report expressing doubts that France could develop new nuclear weapons in the
future without more live tests.
Jacques Baumel, an MP of Chirac's own Rally for the Republic party but who is
estranged from him, said he was ``sorry the president had excluded the
possibility that France could in the future carry out a further small number of
tests''.
Baumel said the computer simulation programme would cost F16bn (#1980m) instead
of the F10.5bn (#1350m) initially estimated. He further claimed it was unclear
where F2.5bn (#320m) of the total would come from.
He added that the programme would depend on delivery by the United States of
advanced giant computers of a type France had been effectively barred from
purchasing in the past.
Specialists said Baumel's statement was seen as part of a running campaign by
backers of defeated presidential candidate Edouard Balladur to snipe at Chirac
rather than an attempt to change policies.
Meanwhile in Wellington, Greenpeace staged a rooftop protest at the British
High Commission against the ``UK-French entente nucleaire''.
Eight protesters wearing masks of Prime Minister John Major and French
President Jacques Chirac climbed on to the roof unfurling ``Union Jacques''
flags and blowing hooters and whistles.
The demonstration lasted about an an hour and ended after a Greenpeace
spokesman met with a commission representative.
Asian nations unequivocally condemned the latest test. Japan's Foreign Minister
Yohei Kono summoned French Ambassador Jean-Bernard Ouvrieu to lodge a formal
protest.
Australian Prime Minister Paul Keating, who has announced a campaign to rid the
world of nuclear weapons, said he was appalled.
``(France) has further isolated itself from international thinking on nuclear
issues and significantly devalued its international credentials,'' Keating
said.
In Seoul, South Korean protesters tossed scores of eggs at the premises of the
French embassy over its main gate. ``Stop nuclear testing'', they wrote with
paint on the road.
A small group of Greenpeace activists also set up road signs at the
Franco-German border today, warning motorists heading into France that they
were entering a country which carries out nuclear tests.
``Warnung, Atomteststaat'' (Warning, State Carrying Out Nuclear Tests''), read
the signs erected east of the French city of Strasbourg. There were
demonstrations at other border crossings.
The first test in the current series took place on September 5, the second on
October 2 and the third on October 27.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
