<HEADLINE>Sri Lankan troop-carrier plane feared shot down by guerrillas</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241229</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Colombo, Wednesday
A PLANE belonging to the Sri Lankan Air Force was feared to have crashed into
the sea today with 62 people on board, air force sources said.
They said the Antonov aircrafttook off from the Ratamalana air base near
Colombo at 1150 GMT headed for the northern Palaly base.
It got in touch with the northern Jaffna control tower before disappearing
without trace off the Karinagar naval base.
The sources said the Russian-built AN-32 plane had 54 troops, six air force
personnel and two crew members on board.
There was speculation that the plane had suffered a technical problem or come
under a guerrilla attack, they added.
The air force lost a Chinese-built Y-8 cargo plane on Saturday when it was shot
down over the sea off the Palaly airbase. Only one of five officers on board
survived.
Another AN-32 crashed mysteriously into the sea near Colombo last month killing
more than 70 troops.
The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam shot down two British-made Avro transport
planes at Palaly in April killing 90 servicemen and showing the world that the
rebels, fighting for a homeland in the north and east, possessed surface-to-air
missiles.
On October 17, Sri Lanka's military launched a massive advance on Jaffna town
from Palaly and the troops are now surrounding the town, which is believed to
be largely deserted.
Any final push is expected to be painstakingly slow as the troops pick their
way through mines and other booby-traps.
Army commandos today cut off a key supply route for up to 2000 rebels believed
to be holed up in the northern town.
The army also banned travel on the Jaffna Lagoon, tightening control over the
main waterway used by civilians and Tiger rebels to reach the mainland from the
northern peninsula.
A military statement said the capture of the Jaffna-Kandy highway, the main
supply route for the town, followed a fierce battle on Tuesday afternoon in
which 45 rebels were killed and more than 100 wounded in the Ariyalai area, in
the eastern suburbs of Jaffna.
The battle for Jaffna is now being waged by the army's elite reserve strike
force of commandos, better trained for fighting in urban areas, who took over
from regular soldiers on Monday.-Reuter
</TEXT>
