<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pope tells Irish to say no to divorce</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241230</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POPE John Paul yesterday urged Irish electors to block the introduction of
divorce in a referendum tomorrow.
Speaking to Irish pilgrims in Rome, the Pope called for reflection before
voting on ``the unbreakable bond of marriage''.
The papal comment came with opinion polls pointing to a tight finish in the
nationwide divorce poll.
Though a ``yes'' vote has been backed by all government and parliamentary
opposition parties, surveys have highlighted a steady drift away from the
referendum recommendation to scrap Ireland's constitutional ban on divorce.
Two months ago, around 60% of the electorate were behind divorce. The most
recent poll this week showed 45% for the reform, 42% against, and 13% still
undecided.
Irish Prime Minister John Bruton and his deputy, Mr Dick Spring, were launching
final appeals for support yesterday.
But anti-divorce campaigners reported increasing confidence that the law change
would be turned down.
In what could prove to be an important intervention, the Pope said Irish people
should pray more intensely for ``the welfare of marriage and family in
Ireland''.
</TEXT>
