<DOCNO>GH951123-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Damages for QE2 passengers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241231</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CUNARD last night said passengers who sued after enduring a Christmas ``cruise
from hell'' on the QE2 last year were getting full fare refunds and
compensation at a cost to the company of #7.5m.
Hundreds were left behind when it sailed from Southampton in December after
workers were unable to complete a refit in time.
Safety milestone
A MAJOR milestone in offshore safety has been reached with every offshore
installation in UK waters now having an approved safety management system in
place, the Health and Safety Executive announced yesterday.
Strike notice
VAUXHALL was yesterday given seven days' notice of industrial action by its
9000 manual workers in protest at a 3.5% pay offer.
Fishing blow
PRESIDENT of the European Commission Jacques Santer last night confirmed that
new costs would be imposed on the Scottish fishing fleet. He said the
Commission would not withdraw its proposed levy for hygiene checks.
Virgin appeal
VIRGIN Television yesterday won permission to challenge the legality of the
Independent Television Commission's decision to award the licence for Channel 5
to a rival bidder.
Jailed for life
A 68-YEAR-OLD man was jailed for life yesterday after he was convicted of
murdering his 80-year-old love rival. Edward Martin stabbed Mr Warwick
Batchelor who he believed was winning over the affections of Ms June Cuxson, 52.
QC challenge
PROMINENT Scottish Nationalist lawyer Ian Hamilton, QC, confirmed last night
that he will challenge Sir William Fraser for the post of Chancellor of Glasgow
University.
Accidents fall
ROAD accidents in Strathclyde between July and September fell compared to last
year, according to Strathclyde Regional Council. Just over 5900 accidents were
recorded, a drop of 55 on 1994.
Pass protest
STRATHCLYDE Elderly Forum will stage a whistlestop demonstration around
Strathclyde tomorrow to deliver petitions, signed by 40,000 people, on the
price of bus passes to the 12 new single-tier authorities which will adopt
responsibility for concessionary travel.
</TEXT>
