<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>War of words over   nursery vouchers plan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241232</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE controversial scheme to give parents a #1100 voucher for the purchase of
nursery and other pre-school places for their three or four-year-olds became
the focus of a row between the Scottish Office Education Minister and Labour
spokeswoman Helen Liddell yesterday.
Mrs Liddell said it was time for Mr Raymond Robertson to ``grow up'' after he
dismissed Opposition criticisms of the scheme as no more than ``the tired
jargon of political abuse''.
The Minister's comments are contained in a letter to Mrs Liddell which was
released yesterday.
Mrs Liddell had written to Mr Robertson about the scheme after a survey showed
that only 16% of respondents to the Scottish Office consultation exercise on
vouchers supported the creation of a marketplace for nursery education.
She wondered how he could justify such a ``flawed and unworkable'' proposal
which was being rushed through for political gain - amounting to a pre-election
bribe damaging to pre-five education.
Mrs Liddell added that more stringent inspection methods than the
``light-touch'', self-monitoring proposals put forward by the Government were
essential, and expressed concern about appointing a private company to
administer what looked like being a costly bureaucratic nightmare.
Bids have been invited for the year-long pilot scheme beginning in August which
the Government has earmarked for testing vouchers, and Mrs Liddell said the
strictest of conditions should apply to it.
In his reply, Mr Robertson said the Scottish Office planned to learn as much as
possible from the pilot.
He continued: ``You say that `light-touch' inspection is not acceptable, yet at
the same time you suggest that our proposals are bureaucratic. You must make up
your mind.
``What we intend is a system which has firm and robust quality guarantees, but
not one which is tangled heavy-handedly in red tape.''
The appointment of a business services company to handle the voucher pilots
throughout the UK would bring economies of scale, he predicted.
Mr Robertson reminded Mrs Liddell that the Educational Institute of Scotland
had recently accused Ministers of delaying nursery education in a ploy to save
money.
``I am left feeling that if we are attacked both for going too fast and for
going too slowly, we have probably got things about right,'' he said.
Mrs Liddell said last night that she had hoped for a ``more mature response''
to what were crucial, unanswered questions about vouchers.
</TEXT>
