<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241239</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MASSIVE disruption of postal services throughout the UK was threatened last
night after peace talsk collapsed. They had been an attempt to resolve a
dispute which was originally triggered by unofficial action by workers at a
local office in Edinburgh.
Thousands of Scottish postal staff had earlier yesterday come out in support of
their Portobello colleagues.
Talks had got under way last night in Edinburgh after more than 1000 workers in
Glasgow had voted unanimously to continue their unofficial strike action.
Following the failure of the talks to resolve the dispute, which will leave
most of central Scotland without any deliveries today, divisional officer for
the Communication Workers Union, Mr George Robertson, said last night: ``We
tried to put something to Royal Mail that would have been a way forward to
settle the original dispute at Portobello but they rejected it.'' He added:
``We will continue to tell our members to go back to work but it looks as
though the dispute goes on.''
A Royal Mail spokesman said he hoped talks would resume today.
The spread of the unofficial action is like a domino effect. As one sorting
office takes action, management steps in and delivers mail to another office,
where the postal workers walk out in protest at the management's
strike-breaking tactics.
One senior trade union official called for an end to the ``madness'' and a
leading Scots businessmen forecast a ``devastating'' impact on the country's
business community.
The workers attending meetings in Glasgow and Edinburgh were given letters
saying their action was repudiated by the CWU, an attempt to stop Royal Mail
management from taking it to court where it could face punitive fines for
unofficial action.
Union officials had planned to hold a ballot for official industrial action but
ballot papers had been held up in the post by the dispute.
Mr John Keggie, CWU divisional officer, said the situation was becoming
``crazier by the day'' and there were fears of huge delays for Christmas.
Around 4000 staff throughout Scotland are involved in the action which has
resulted in a huge backlog of mail. Postal and processing staff are involved in
the row over staffing changes.
Mr Peter Dunn, acting director general of the Scottish Chambers of Commerce,
said it was a sad reflection on modern management and employee relationships.
He warned: ``This strike could cost the business community millions. It must be
fairly obvious the business community will not tolerate this too long before it
seeks alternative methods of doing its work.''
Mr Geoff Runcie, chief executive of Glasgow Chamber of Commerce, also warned
customers might use alternative services and not return to the Royal Mail.
There is a strong belief among workers that management is deliberately loading
as much mail as possible into the first delivery so that in time second
deliveries will be eliminated, jobs will be lost, and costs reduced.
Mr Keggie said: ``We are heading into the Christmas period where we want to
operate properly and effectively. At the moment the public are being denied a
service because of management's refusal to negotiate a compromise and a
sensible back-to-work agreement.''
Mr Robertson said members were finding it difficult to work under a
``heavy-handed, bullying, and threatening regime'' imposing unnecessary
changes. He said it had not happened yet but it appeared the dispute was set to
spread over the Border.
The Royal Mail said it was ``bitterly disappointed'' the union had failed to
get staff to give up their illegal strike action.
Delivery director Alex Gibb said: ``This illegal action is taking place because
some members do not want to make changes to improve the service for customers
who want to get their mail as early as possible.
``Claims that Royal Mail is trying to get rid of the second delivery are total
rubbish.''
The Royal Mail said any changes were not new, had been fully worked through
with active staff involvement at Portobello, and agreement had been reached.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The 20-year killing spree. Murder mystery of how they kept their secret</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES McKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241240</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS the cell doors closed behind mass murderess Rosemary West, attention
immediately shifted to how she and her husband Fred had managed to carry out
their killing spree undetected for at least 20 years.
There are also fears that the final tally of deaths may never be known.
Sentencing her yesterday to 10 life terms, trial judge Mr Justice Mantell
wasted few words: ``If any attention is paid to what I think, you will never be
released. Take her down.''
It had taken the jury of seven men and four women only two hours to return the
last seven guilty verdicts, unanimously convicting her of murdering 10 young
women and girls.
The jury had decided on the previous day that Rosemary West was a triple
killer, having murdered her Scots-born step-daughter Charmaine, her own
daughter, Heather, and lodger Shirley Ann Robinson, who had been made pregnant
by Frederick West.
Within two hours of the final verdicts being delivered, police admitted they
fear the Wests killed many more than the 12 highlighted during the horrendous
trial at Winchester Crown Court.
Locally people were talking of a figure in excess of 60. There is a good deal
of gossip over killing fields. The police say they just do not know.
In Gloucester alone officers believe nine girls associated with 25 Cromwell
Street could well have been murdered by the Wests.
Yesterday they announced a fresh investigation into the movements of these
girls. They hoped the inquiry might reveal they are still alive. However,
police stressed there would be no digging or searching for possible further
victims in the immediate future.
Other forces, especially Strathclyde Police, are anxious to interview Rosemary
West in a bid to determine if her husband killed while living in Scotland and
if so how many.
The truth is the police do know more young girls have died, but they do not
know where to continue their diggings. It is unlikely for the moment that
Rosemary West will point them in the right direction.
Circumstances surrounding the victims would appear to have made it relatively
simple for the Wests to cover their tracks:
q Only five of the 12 victims discovered during the inquiry were ever
officially reported as missing.
q  Most of them were adult.
q  The victims vanished in different places.
q  Nothing marked most of the disappearances as being out of the ordinary.
Serious questions will also be raised over the social services' involvement
with the West family.
q Medical staff saw some of the West children a total of 16 times over a
period of 14 years.
q Social services were not told of a court case in 1973 in which Fred and
Rosemary West were fined for assaulting a teenage lodger.
q Two of the West children, including the murdered Charmaine, went into social
work care five times.
q Social services had only five contacts over a five-year period, and only one
contact in the 18 years before Fred and Rosemary West were arrested, in 1992.
Still maintaining her innocence, Rosemary West is to appeal. Her lawyer, Mr Leo
Goatley, says she has the support of her family. He said she was devastated by
the verdicts.
Five of her seven living children are in care and their names have been
changed. The press is forbidden from publishing anything that might identify
them in their new lives.
Yesterday Rosemary West had recovered some composure when she returned to the
dock to hear the jury deliver their final verdicts which ensure she goes down
in criminal history as perhaps one of the most evil killers known.
After being detained for some days in the cell specially built for her at
Winchester Prison, it is likely Rosemary West will be transferred to Durham.
There she could meet Moors Murderer Myra Hindley. They are the only two women
in the country who now know they have no chance of ever being released from
prison.
Rosemary West knows that from now on she will not be able to come into contact
with people other than those whose duty it is to guard her. ``She would not
last more than five minutes if she ever tried to mix,'' said one recently
released prisoner who met her in jail.
She was reconciled to her fate when the jury delivered their final verdicts.
Their final decisions came just a little more than 20 minutes after the judge
responsed to two questions put to him in a note.
``Yes,'' was his answer, telling them they could convict in the absence of
direct evidence if they accepted ``similar fact'' evidence that Frederick and
Rosemary West had cruised the streets to pick up young girls to take them back
to Cromwell Street, where they were sexually assaulted.
Immediately the jury retired on this direction from the judge, defence counsel
Mr Richard Ferguson QC objected by declaring Mr Justice Mantell had not given
the jury the defence claim that it was a huge chasm to leap by assuming such
activities made Rosemary West a murderess,
Mr Mantell abruptly dismissed the application by declaring he would not change
his direction to the jury.
In less than half-an-hour the jury returned with unanimous verdicts on seven
counts of murder.
They had been left in no doubt about the horror which must have followed the
abduction by the Wests of these seven girls and young women. They had been
bound, gagged, and taped.
Most horrific of all was the taped mask which covered the head of 15-year-old
Shirley Hubbard, who disappeared in 1974.
Inserted between the tape bindings were plastic breathing tubes. That alone
indicated that these girls were sexually tortured for hours if not days before
they were killed.
The judge told the jury they, like him, might like to believe that their bodies
were dismembered after, rather than before, death.
Immediately the final verdicts were delivered, Mr Justice Mantell did not waste
many words in sentencing Rosemary West to life imprisonment on each one of the
10 murder charges.
At that stage there was a cry of ``hooray'' from the public gallery and someone
else shouted: ``Quite right.''
It was the first and only suggestion of any kind of outburst throughout the
trial, which has lasted almost eight weeks.
Throughout yesterday's proceedings Rosemary West stood impassive before the
judge, her hands folded in front of her.
Upstairs in the public gallery her step-daughter, Mrs Anne Marie Davis, a key
witness for the prosecution, and whose evidence had played a major role in
determining the verdicts, asked a minder next to her to hold on to her arm. She
still slumped to the floor.
Outside the court there was a crowd of about 150. They watched the white prison
van, accompanied by police motorcycle outriders, carry Rosemary West for the
last time on the short journey between court and prison.
It was the nearest Winchester has shown an interest in what has been happening
in their town. ``We only came on this one occasion to make sure that she is
leaving here for ever,'' said one local.
Inside the court the jury was being offered counselling services. The judge had
told them that they would never have a more important job to do in their lives.
Meanwhile it was revealed that the ashes of Rena West and her daughter
Charmaine are to be brought home to Scotland. Mrs Davis hopes that returning
the ashes of her murdered mother and sister to their native Scotland will help
ease the pain.
While Mrs Davis, now aged 31, left Scotland as little more than a toddler, she
considers herself very much Scottish.
She thought her half-sister Charmaine had returned to Scotland to live with
their mother. It was only when the police began to excavate at 25 Midland Road,
Gloucester and at Letterbox Field that she learned the truth.
``As Charmaine and Rena's closest relative, Anne Marie had the remains cremated
together,'' said a friend. ``Now the trial is over she is determined that their
ashes be taken back home to Scotland.''
Fred West maintained until the end that he did not kill his Scottish nannie Ann
McFall, who was carrying his child.
The police discovered her body in a field near the burial ground of Rena West,
his first wife. ``The exception out of the 12 victims found was Ann McFall,''
police said yesterday. ``Frederick West never admitted involvement in the
murder of that young girl.''
Nevertheless he did indicate the field where he thought she might be buried. He
was right. Her remains were recovered.
Meanwhile, the Lord Chancellor commissioned a report into the way key witnesses
in the trial were paid money by the media for their stories.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Report stresses need to share information</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241241</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE author of an inquiry into the West murders last night demanded a national
shake-up in information networks between child protection agencies as he
published a report showing action could have been taken earlier to protect
youngsters in the family.
Mr John Fitzgerald, director of the independent Bridge Childcare Agency, said
``much more sophisticated'' ways of sharing information between police, health,
social services, and education officials must be found. The Bridge report,
commissioned by Gloucestershire area child protection committee, reveals how
files were opened and closed on different members of the family by various
agencies over a period of more than 30 years.
But no-one made a link or established a connection between events that might
have set alarm bells ringing about possible abuse.
Communication between agencies was rare. Unlike today, there was no requirement
to share information with one another. The report makes a number of
recommendations and claims proper health information is critical to detecting
possible abuse.
Last night, Mr Jeff James, chief executive of Gloucestershire Health, said
there were lessons to be learned in the light of the case.
He added that all the health organisations were reviewing their arrangements
for protecting children and would draw on external advice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nine reasons behind a catalogue of evil</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241242</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN internal inquiry by Gloucester Police has identified nine reasons why the
murders went undetected.
q Only five of the 12 victims were reported as ``missing persons''. The
disappearances of Heather and her half-sister, Charmaine, eight, Catherine
Costello - Fred West's first wife - nanny Anne McFall, and lodger Shirley Anne
Robinson went unreported. The victims who were reported missing - Lynda Gough,
Carole Cooper, Lucy Partington, Therese Siegenthaler, Shirley Hubbard, Alison
Chambers, and Juanita Mott - had no known connection with each other.
q The victims vanished in different places, ranging from London and Worcester
to Cheltenham and Gloucester.
q Most were adult ``missing persons''. During the seventies, thousands of
people were reported missing each year - most of whom turned up alive in due
course.
q There was nothing remarkable about the disappearances, except for Lucy
Partington. Her disappearance on the night of December 27, 1973, was given
considerable local and national publicity.
q There was no apparent link to Cromwell Street. Some of the victims were
abducted, or were on the run from local authority care, or had lodged at 25
Cromwell Street, or were members of the West family. There was no apparent
pattern of kidnappings. Victims vanished on weekdays, at weekends, and at
differing times of day and night. No-one saw anything.
q Some victims had been in care. Shirley Hubbard was fostered in Droitwich when
she was six, Alison Chambers often absconded from local authority care in
Gloucester, Carole Cooper was staying at a children's home in Worcester when
she disappeared, while Shirley Robinson was in care for petty offences. Their
backgrounds perhaps only became significant after police discovered 25 Cromwell
Street was a haven for the runaways.
q Gloucestershire had only a small police force. With just over 1000 officers
to cover the whole county in the early seventies, missing persons inquiries
were noted by constables and sergeants, with an inspector reviewing progress
later, and officers generally acted on information from relatives. Limited
resources meant few in-depth investigations.
q The time scale. The Cromwell Street killings went undetected for more than 20
years. The victims had to be seen against a background of thousands of adults
who went missing over that period.
q The secrecy of the murdererers. Frederick and Rosemary West wanted their
activities to remain secret and were prepared to kill to ensure this.
One senior officer on the inquiry said: ``Those who died were to some extent
victims of their time . . . just missing persons in a foot-loose society. Even
given today's sophisticated detection and publicity methods, it is perhaps
unlikely that their deaths would have been detected earlier.''
</TEXT>
