<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The victims: Ten young lives lost at the hands of partners in crime</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241243</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Charmaine
West
SPRING 71: Fred West's step-daughter from his marriage to his first wife,
Catherine.
West was living with Rose, though they were not yet married, when Charmaine
disappeared, aged eight. During the trial the court heard of Rose's dislike for
Charmaine which was often directed at the girl through violence.
After spending periods in care, Charmaine went to live with Fred and Rose at 25
Midland Road, Gloucester and disappeared in the spring of 1971.
Charmaine had gone to live with her mother. However her mother, Catherine had
already been murdered by Fred.
Charmaine's remains were discovered buried under the kitchen window at 25
Midland Road on the tenth day of the search. Fragments of coal were found with
the bones, evidence that Charmaine's body had been stowed in the coal cellar
before her burial.
Lynda
Gough
APRIL 73: The eldest of three children, Lynda left school to become a
seamstress in Gloucester. She was known to have been friendly with lodgers at
25 Cromwell Street.
Shortly before her 20th birthday she moved out of her parents' home to a flat
in Gloucester, and then vanished. Her parents reported her missing, but there
was no trace of her.
Lynda's mother visited 25 Cromwell Street in search of her daughter. The woman
who answered the door was wearing Lynda's slippers, and some of her clothes
were hanging on the clothes line. Mrs Gough was told that her daughter had
moved away.
Her remains were found in a former car inspection pit in a garage, which had
been converted into a bathroom, at 25 Cromwell Street. With the remains was two
separate pieces of tape, a bootlace and fragments of fabric.
Carol Ann
Cooper
NOVEMBER 73: The first victim buried in the cellar at 25 Cromwell Street,
Carole Ann was just 15.
Her parents separated in 1962, and she went to live with her mother. After her
mother's death she lived with her father, who had remarried, but was placed in
care in 1971.
Known as Cass, she was in the care of Worcestershire County Council and living
in a council home in Worcester. She was last seen getting on a bus to return
there after a night out.
She was not known to have had any connections with the Wests, and detectives
concluded that they picked her up while she was hitch-hiking.
Her remains, decapitated and dismembered, were found under the cellar floor. It
is believed she had been bound and suffered sexual abuse before being killed.
Around her skull was the remnant of an elasticated gag.
Lucy
Partington
DECEMBER 73: A Medieval English student at Exeter University, Lucy, 21,
disappeared two days after Christmas, 1973, while on the way home from a visit
to a friend.
It is thought that the Wests picked her up as she waited for a bus to her home
at Gretton, near Winchcombe.
The trial was told that Lucy, a gentle and chaste girl, was not the sort of
person who would have any social contact with Fred and Rose West, and she would
never have gone to the house voluntarily.
Her remains, decapitated and dismembered, were found under the floor of the
cellar at 25 Cromwell Street. There were pieces of cord tied around the skull.
Seven days after Lucy disappeared, Fred West went to hospital with a cut on his
hand which, the prosecution said, indicated that Lucy may have been held alive
in the cellar, the victim of sexual abuse, for a week.
Therese
Siegenthaler
APRIL 74: Swiss-born Therese, 21, a sociology student at Woolwich Polytechnic
in London, set out to hitch-hike to Ireland to visit a friend who was a priest.
She had no known connection with Fred and Rosemary West.
An experienced hitch-hiker, she had planned to make her way from London to
Holyhead to catch a ferry to Ireland, and was due to return to friends in north
London on April 21. She was reported missing two days later.
Her remains, decapitated and dismembered, were found under the floor of the
cellar at 25 Cromwell Street, where they had been forced into a small area.
Near her skull were the remains of sticky tape, which appeared to have been
used as some form of gag.
Prosecution counsel Brian Leveson told the court: ``How she got to Cromwell
Street, the Crown cannot say. She must have been abducted.''
Juanita
Mott
APRIL 75: The second of three sisters, Juanita was 18, and had left her family
home in Gloucester soon after leaving school. Her parents had split up.
She lived in various bedsits in the Gloucester area, including 25 Cromwell
Street, and worked as a bottler with a local soft drinks firm.
Juanita had promised to take care of her landlady's children while she attended
a wedding, but she disappeared the night before.
Her decapitated and dismembered remains were found in the cellar of 25 Cromwell
Street. Lengths of looped and knotted rope were found with the bones, and
material, apparently from her own clothes, was wrapped around her head.
Soon after Juanita's death, the floor of the cellar - the bodies beneath
arranged neatly - was concreted over, and the room was turned into a bedroom
for the Wests' children.
Shirley Anne
Robinson
MAY 78: The Wests' lodger and Fred's lover, to whom she became pregnant, she
flaunted the pregnancy early on, but later attempted to distance herself from
the family, apparently to avoid Rose West's mounting jealousy.
From a broken home and under the supervision of Gloucester Social Services,
Shirley Anne typified the Wests' victims, drawn by their apparent friendliness
and the offer of a home.
Last seen when eight months pregnant, staff at the benefits office tried to
contact her and were told that she had moved away from Cromwell Street, leaving
no forwarding address.
The Wests told people she was in Germany and had given birth to a son, Barry.
Shirley Anne's body, and her unborn child, had been buried in the garden of 25
Cromwell street. Her right leg had been amputated.
Alison
Chambers
AUGUST 79: Born in Germany, where her father was in the Army, Alison, 16, was
taken into care after her parents split up, and later moved to a children's
home in Gloucester, from where she went missing on a number of occasions.
Described as ``a bit of a rebel'', she was a frequent visitor at 25 Cromwell
Street, and was known to have lesbian tendencies. Rosemary West, who was also
keen on lesbian sex, began to lure her into her confidence.
Alison wrote to her mother saying she had left the children's home and was
living with a ``homely'' family, doing the housework and caring for their
children. She had left her job in a solicitor's office.
Her remains were found in the garden at 25 Cromwell Street. She had been
dismembered. Around her skull was fastened a buckled belt, which was intended
to silence her screams as she was abused.
Heather
West
1987: The first body discovered at 25 Cromwell Street, Heather, 16, was the
last known victim of the Wests' serial of murders.
Fred and Rosemary's first child, born prior to their marriage while they lived
at 25 Midland Road, she was never reported missing by her parents, though they
pretended to several people that they had.
The Wests concocted several stories to explain her disappearance - gone to
Wales with a lesbian, run away from home, or was living in Gloucester or
Brockworth and was regularly in contact.
Rosemary West claimed she had given Heather #600, but could not explain where
she drew the money from.
The truth was simple and grisly, Heather had been murdered and dismembered, and
buried under the garden patio.
Before any of the other bodies were found, Fred West had told police he alone
was responsible for her murder, the final lie to be laid to rest.
Heather's former headmaster remembered her as a ``very pleasant'' girl.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
