<HEADLINE>Ayr today looking for a better tomorrow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN BEATTIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975241244</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STEVE Munro, the former Scotland winger, has told the Diary that his club, Ayr,
is to hold a crisis meeting on Wednesday at which the future of the club is to
be discussed.
I gather that there is deep unrest at the club, and suspicion about the funding
of three New Zealanders who are at Millbrae but do not have jobs.
Munro, and fellow club member Malcolm Wilkinson, are to make presentations on
the evening.
``We have to define what being a member of the first XV at Ayr means, and I
think we have to define it as a largely amateur role. But, for clarity's sake,
it has to be spelt out and everyone has to be aware of what we are about,''
said Munro.
``There will be a standard package, perhaps, which includes blazer, boots, and
a tour every two years. I see two or three areas to progress. We need someone
as director of coaching, perhaps one full-time professional as an employee of
the club, and we need to add a multi-sport role, and a multi-sex outlook, to
Ayr rugby club.
``There may be 10 quid given to the players after a match for beer money, but
that would have to be spent at the club.''
Munro has consulted with SRU director of rugby, Jim Telfer, and Keith
Robertson, to examine the club structure at Melrose. ``We are in the fourth
division, and we want to be challenging at the top,'' says Munro.
``I think if we clearly define ourselves in this way, players will be
attracted. I think that many clubs will follow Ayr and Melrose as they try to
define what it means, for players and clubs in Scotland, to enter the
professional era. If you don't spell it out you're whistling in the dark.''
Out of tune
IT was good to bump into Alex Moore, the former Scotland winger, on Saturday.
Alex, who won six caps as an Edinburgh Accies player in the early nineties, was
on police duty at Murrayfield and I saw him deep in the bowels of the stadium
in the players' tunnel.
We exchanged greetings. ``I tell you what,'' said Alex. ``If the team plays
like that at Murrayfield for the Five Nations' then at least we have something
to look forward to . . . the Tina Turner concert.'' Ouch.
Sick joke
THESE North and Midlands boys are tough. No wonder they beat the Samoans. After
the game Martin Waite was sick over Brian Ireland, and the lads stole Rowen
Shepherd's rear wipers and let down the tyres of his car. Not a sheep in sight,
honest.
Just joking
I AM intrigued at the lengths many of our clubs are going to in order to
entertain precious spectators by making match programmes that little bit
different.
Allan Glen's have a picture of Mike Gibson, the famous Irish centre of the
seventies, on their cover. A dangerous liaison surely.
Pride of place in the Diary's collection goes to an offering from referee Eddie
Crozier, who sent along the Whitecraigs match programme. Under the proud
legend, ``Lochaber RFC'' where there should have been a team list, there was,
instead, the following: ``Sorry boys, could not manage to get your names.'' On
the facing page is a racy message of welcome from the club president, who
wishes everyone an enjoyable afternoon's rugby.
Beneath that is a cartoon depicting one player leaving a scene of quite obvious
injury to another. The downtrodden player, lying flat on his back and in great
pain, is seen to be saying: ``An enjoyable day's rugby, you've got to be
f*****g joking.'' No letters are blanked out in the Whitecraigs programme. See
South siders? Any more out there?
Time check
THE Diary understands that the Western Samoan manager let slip at the
post-match dinner on Saturday that Bill Hogg, the SRU chief executive, has very
little grasp of time. When rumours of Western Samoa cancelling their tour were
rife, Hogg phoned the Southern Hemisphere to check, but at two o'clock our
time. Which raised our friend from the middle of his slumbers. Sounds likely to
me.
</TEXT>
