<HEADLINE>Back on the Bond wagon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241245</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WATCHING the new Bond film, Goldeneye, I was irresistibly reminded of those
lines allegedly written by the Poet Laureate, Alfred Austin, about the illness
of the Prince of Wales, later Edward VII - ``Across the wires the electric
message came, He is no better, He is much the same.''
Forget the hype, all that stuff about this being a Bond for the nineties. The
seventeenth in the series is the same old nonsense, albeit with slightly higher
production values, one outstanding stunt, and a new, sexier, although slightly
lightweight Bond, Pierce Brosnan. It should delight fans of the series because
it represents a return to form.
I am not one to knock Timothy Dalton's Bond films. His two outings as 007 were
competent enough adventures and he had both the looks and the weight for the
role, although he was a bit short on charm. The films were an attempt to
redefine the series after it had, in Roger Moore's latter years, gone off the
rails a bit, becoming too tongue in the cheek, too full of irrelevant glamour
girls. As for Moore, he had become a shade too old for the role.
That the attempt did not work was not Dalton's fault. But it meant there was a
six-year hiatus between his last film, Licence to Kill, and the present one. In
that time the world's political climate had changed: the Cold War, the basic
requirement for a Bond adventure, had ended and political correctness had
arrived. Changes in the name of PC are minimal. The heroine, Izabella Scorupco,
is allowed to give 007 a dressing down for being a callous brute about all the
women he has loved and killed, which sticks out like a sore thumb amid the
carnage.
Dame Judi Dench makes the most of her two short scenes as M, although to tell
the truth any old English character actress could have done as well, and
certainly any of the other Dames. She delivers the coup de grace with relish,
telling Bond he is a misogynistic chauvinist male dinosaur, but being a woman
she really thinks he is pretty terrific underneath the frost, you can tell.
Directed by Martin Campbell, the film's pace seldom slackens, and he has
created that stunt. It takes place within the first ten minutes, during the
obligatory pre-credits mini adventure, and is never improved upon when the film
proper begins. The tank chase through the streets of St Petersburg is
excitingly shot, and the studio street fits in with the real locations
brilliantly, a tribute to the skills of Peter Lamont, the production designer.
But they do drive the tank up and down it once too often because one starts to
recognise the buildings. As for that stunt, I don't want to spoil things, but
it involves a pilotless bi-plane, a precipice, a runaway motorbike and Bond and
is breathtaking in its audacity.
The plot is pretty hopeless, but plot was never among the series' strengths,
and occasionally a little too familiar. We have been here before. At the
climax, looking for the site of the radar telescope which controls Goldeneye,
Bond flies over a lake deep in the mountains of Cuba and professes himself
stumped as to where it is. One is tempted to shout look at the lake, you fool,
because he has romped over a similar lake in the past.
A renegade agent, 006 (Sean Bean, like Brosnan an alumnus of the Citz) and an
ambitious Russian General (Gottfried John, impressively nasty), are out to
acquire the Goldeneye, a device which will allow them to hold the world to
ransom and do terrible things to the international computer networks. Robbie
Coltrane appears as a Russian arms dealer, and Alan Cumming hams it up madly as
a bent Russian computer expert working on the Goldeneye project, both making a
decent impression in underwritten roles. Famke Janssen slinks around as Xenia
Onatopp, a Russian sadist who kills her victims by strangling them between her
thighs. Miss Scorupco, the obligatory love interest, is terrific as another
computer operator. She displays spirit, and may, if she is lucky, escape the
curse of Bond. Few, if any, of the other 16 leading ladies went on to better
things.
Brosnan looks good enough to eat, wears his clothes with style, manages the
fights well enough, and should have a career ahead of him as 007, if he wants
it. He has, however, been ill served by the script. The obligatory double
entendres are crude and unfunny. Given that disaster was forecast by the
Cassandras of the film world, the result is a triumph.
Demi Moore may be the highest paid actress in Hollywood history, but she is
also one of the worst. Her performance as Hester Prynne in Roland Joffe's
lavish, handsomely photographed, but incredibly dull version of Nathaniel
Hawthorne's novel, The Scarlet Letter, is wooden and lacklustre, and one of the
reasons why this expensive affair is a disaster. The other is they ditched the
book.
Free spirit Hester, furnished with an amazing wardrobe and lots of make-up,
arrives in a Puritan colony in seventeenth century Massachusetts, to set up
home for her husband (Robert Duvall) and in no time is upsetting the locals
with her willful ways. One day, walking the woods, she spies a young man
bathing, and one flash of his buttocks is all that is needed to make her fall
in love. He turns out to be the local preacher, Reverend Dimmesdale (Gary
Oldman), who reciprocates the passion.
Meanwhile, her husband is apparently killed when the Indians attack the ship
bringing him to the colony. But Hester's pregnancy is a problem, because she
must wait seven years for his death to be confirmed before consorting with
another man. When she refuses to say who the father is, the elders condemn her
to life as an outcast, branded by the scarlet letter A for adultery pinned to
her dress. Then her husband returns from the dead.
Joan Plowright, as a randy old biddy, doing her celebrated impersonation of
Beryl Reid, is one of the few good things in the film, although it does seem a
pity that she is not burnt at the stake for heresy. It would have cheered
things up enormously. All is solved when the Indians attack the settlement in
the final reel. Would that they had done so two hours earlier and we could all
have gone home sooner.
Patricia Rozema's When Night is Falling is a glum tale about an affair between
two Canadian lesbians, Camille (Pascale Bussieres), an academic at a theology
college, and Petra (Rachel Ward), a circus performer. Camille is forced to
chose between Petra and her dreary boyfriend, but it is hard to care. Night
does not fall quickly enough.
</TEXT>
