<HEADLINE>From a cause to a crusade</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SUSAN ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241246</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN A small room in a Dundee clinic mothers discuss what was once the
unimaginable - turning carer for your terminally ill child. But many of these
women have also been forced to think of their grandchildren's future.
This is the double trauma of carers whose children are HIV positive.
There is little evidence of bitterness or self-pity among members of the
Tayside Carers' HIV Support Group, and this is their strength. The prime
function has been to act as a channel to release emotions, and provide a
sanctuary where carers can meet and talk freely.
One, Elizabeth, whose daughter was in her thirties when she died, explains:
``To begin with I couldn't speak to my husband about our daughter. I was a bit
apprehensive about coming to the group, but you need someone to talk to and
this gave me the confidence to talk to my husband.''
Talk is therapeutic, but Marion had other reservations about opening up:``I
went to my first meeting three weeks after my daughter had died, and sat and
cried throughout the meeting, it was the first time I had really spoken about
her death.''
``But I was kind of frightened, because there were others there whose sons and
daughters were still alive, and I didn't want to mention that my daughter had
died.''
Being a parent of someone who is HIV means entry to a closed society, Marion
goes on: ``At home people can get fed up of listening to you, but everyone here
understands my fears.'' These fears include imagined inadequacies as mothers,
not being protective enough, and Marion summed up a universal view: ``It's the
only time in your life where you are powerless to do something for them.''
For Marion now the HIV cause has become a crusade, a complete turnaround of her
previous views: ``Before my daughter's illness I would not have shaken hands
with someone who was HIV.''
Absorbing the news is then followed by thinking through the implications,
Margaret explains: ``You are very selective about who you tell because of the
fear of prejudice.''
And then the anxiety spreads to the grandchildren and the effect of the
parent's illness on their school pals, leaving primary age youngsters open to
being marked as modern day lepers. For Marion continuing education is the
answer, because she argues infection is still happening, and stressed: ``We
can't really be getting the message through because young people are still
getting HIV because they don't think it will happen to them.''
The Tayside group celebrates its third year on Monday, and any suggestion that
meetings are depressing is brushed aside, instead there is joking about the
fictitious names which will be used in this article.
n.Information about the group meetings from Hazel Robertson, Tayside Regional
Council Social Work Department, Dundee Royal Infirmary (01382 346648).
</TEXT>
