<HEADLINE>Mother dismissed for not working at night Sacked lawyer's job claim</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241247</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FEMALE lawyer yesterday claimed she was unfairly sacked and sexually
discriminated against by a leading Scottish legal firm.
Mr Cameron Fyfe, managing partner for Ross Harper &amp; Co, yesterday admitted to
an industrial tribunal that he had sacked Mrs Eileen Paterson, 36, of
Pollokshields, without asking about her personal circumstances after she
refused to work at night.
The tribunal also heard that another lawyer in Ross Harper &amp; Co was excused
from working nights because he became medically unfit at the prospect of
cross-examining police officers in court.
Mrs Paterson, who is married to advocate Robert Skinner and has two chilren
aged nine and four, worked in Ross Harper &amp; Co's offices in Ingram Street,
Glasgow, for nine years before being sacked earlier this year after refusing to
take part in the night call-out rota covering weekdays and weekends.
Prior to the introduction of the rota, Mrs Paterson had been excused from night
call-outs because of her family commitments.
Asked by Mr Jack Quar, representing Mrs Paterson, whether he had looked into
her family circumstances, Mr Fyfe said: ``I knew she had two children. I knew
she was married and my assumption was that her husband could look after the
children or someone else.''
Mr Quar: Don't you know her husband is frequently away at night?
Mr Fyfe: I know from my own knowledge how busy a junior counsel is but I don't
believe a junior counsel is busy every night of the week.
You made no investigation into how often he was away from home and the nature
of his practice? - I cannot see what further investigation I could have made. I
know enough about an advocate's life from my own experience. He could be the
top QC in the country and I don't think they would be busy every night.
So you proceeded on the assumption that daddy could look after them? - I
understood her husband, a neighbour, or whoever could look after the children.
So you thought it reasonable for Mrs Paterson to give her children up to the
care and custody of whoever? You don't think it would have been incumbent to
make investigations about her domestic situation? - No I didn't.
Earlier, Mr Fyfe had told the industrial tribunal in Glasgow that the
management of the criminal office in Ingram Street, previously done by himself,
had been transferred to Mr John Caruthers who had produced a policy document
late last year which called for all qualified solicitors to go on the night
call-out rota.
He agreed that the partners in the Ingram Street office, prior to Mr Caruther's
arrival, had allowed Mrs Paterson to be excluded from the rota.
Asked why it was essential for Mrs Paterson to go on the rota, Mr Fyfe said it
was necessary to create a bond between clients and lawyers by having the
solicitor who spoke to them while in custody also represent them next day in
court.
He said also that another criminal lawyer, who worked in Ingram Street, was
excused from going on the rota.
The tribunal continues.
</TEXT>
