<HEADLINE>Clinton works on Congress</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241248</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
From Our Correspondent
THE first few hundred Nato troops will go to Bosnia next week, and the main
movement of what will be an army 60,000-strong will begin before Christmas.
Meanwhile, President Clinton will try to persuade Congress of the wisdom of the
move.
Both Houses expressed continued scepticism of the need to send US troops into
the Balkans, but were less openly critical than before the Dayton agreement.
Last Friday Congress passed a resolution that would forbid the president to
spend money on a Bosnian peacekeeping operation. Congress appears less obdurate
now.
His spokesmen, starting with the vice-president, today repeated the claim that
there could be no peace without a large Nato force, which the United States
must lead. They argue that the alternative is a resumption of the war.
Critics say the appearance of peace has come because of the winter. All sides
must go into winter quarters and are preparing to resume the battle next spring.
The weather is a serious concern for the Americans and their allies, who will
have to house the troops in inclement conditions.
The Americans are to patrol the central front. The French are to take Sarajevo
and the British, western Bosnia. Other contingents will add to the total,
including a a small number of Russians.
</TEXT>
