<HEADLINE>smokers increase cot-death risk</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANN SHAW</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241249</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n BABIES of smokers may be up to nine times more at risk of cot deaths than
those of non-smokers, suggests new scientific research carried out at the Royal
Hospital for Sick Children in Glasgow.
Cot death is still the single biggest killer of babies over one week old in
Scotland. The Scottish Cot Death Trust has launched a campaign to raise
awareness of the issue with a series of posters asking the public to ``Donate
money to an unknown cause'' featuring a hard-hitting image.
Information from the Scottish Cot Death Trust, Royal Hospital for Sick
Children, Yorkhill, Glasgow (0141-357 3946).
n After The Herald coffee mornings come the afternoon cup of tea. Jane Asher is
launching an appeal in aid of arthritis research and asking people to invite
friends in for a cuppa and a piece of cake.
Although Tea Week does not take place until March 10-16, 1996, to celebrate the
Arthritis and Rheumatism Council's diamond jubilee, volunteers are needed now
to help organise the event.
Write to Jane Asher, Arthritis and Rheumatism Council, PO Box 177,
Chesterfield, Derbys S41 7TQ.
n A FREE Winter Warmth helpline has been set up to give advice to the elderly.
Sponsored by three charities and the DoH, the line is open between 10am and 4pm
on weekdays on 0800 289404.
n SYNTHETIC pillows may account for more than half of severe asthma in
youngsters. A study of more than 1500 children between the ages of 11 and 16
found they were almost three times as likely to have a wheezing attack at least
once a month if they used non-feather bedding.
According to the British Medical Journal, researchers at St George's Hospital,
London, believe it may be due to the compounds given off in the foam.
n ABUSE of the elderly is slowly gaining recognition as a major social problem.
Now a pilot helpline, funded by the Department of Health, has been set up for
victims. The Elder Abuse Response Line provides advice on 0181-679 7074.
n HIGH intakes of Vitamin C could reduce the risk of osteoarthritis, says a
recent report in GP magazine. It also points out that if sufferers switch to a
high intake of Vitamin C they are less likely to experience so much pain. The
American study involved 640 people. The researchers told a recent American
College of Rheumatology meeting that they also noted the disease progression
could be reduced by high intake of beta-carotene and Vitamin E.
n A WORLDWIDE competition, ``Paint Your Asthma'', invites young people and
carers to put their feelings on the problem into art. Organised by the National
Asthma Campaign, it aims to bring to public attention what it feels like to be
one of the three million people in the UK, over a million of whom are children,
who suffer from asthma.
There are four categories: up to 11 years, 12-17 years, 18 years and over, and
carers (all ages). Closing date is January 31, 1996.
Entry forms are available from Nicole Bettelley, Burson-Marsteller, 24-28
Bloomsbury Way, London WC1A 2PX.
An asthma helpline, run by the NAC, is open from 9am-9pm Monday-Friday, and
staffed by specialists on 0345 01 0203.
n THRUSH is a common complaint affecting four out of five women in their
lifetime. The most common symptoms include vaginal itching, soreness, and a
discharge.
Often it can be treated simply but women are reluctant to seek medical advice.
Now a new Thrush Advisory Service, with a free telephone helpline, has been
launched. By calling 0800 132649 women will be able to find out more about the
symptoms of thrush as well as the best way to treat it.
For a free leaflet write (enclosing sae) to the Canesten Thrush Advisory
Service, 12C Hillreach, Woolwich, London SE18 4AW.
</TEXT>
