<HEADLINE>Policeman denies assaulting women</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241250</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COURT was told yesterday how a young receptionist was grabbed round the neck
as she left a nightclub and had her head banged three times against a police
car. A policeman denies five charges of assault and four of breach of the peace.
Constable Graham Howie, 31, of the Tayside force, is alleged to have committed
the offences in Perth between July and October of last year.
He is accused, at Perth Sheriff Court, of assaulting two women in separate
street incidents. He is also alleged to have frightened and alarmed women by
shouting at them while they were in police cells, and trying to induce one of
them to drop a complaint against him.
Further charges accused him of assaulting two men, one of them twice, and
committing breaches of the peace by shouting and swearing in the street.
One of the alleged assault victims, Miss Sarah-Jayne Devlin, 24, of Glenartney
Terrace, Perth, said that she was approaching a taxi rank after leaving a
nightclub at 2.30am when another woman pushed her for no reason.
She said that as she fended off the woman she was grabbed round the neck from
behind and dragged backwards on her heels to a police car.
She said she was then knocked to the ground and had her head banged three times
on the side of the car before a foot or a knee was used to pin her head against
her chest with such force that she could hardly breathe. The witness said that
she eventually saw that it was a policeman - she identified him as the accused
- who was involved.
Miss Devlin said that she could not remember biting Mr Howie while she was on
the ground but might well have done so.
She said that when taken to the police station she was charged with police
assault, resisting arrest, and breach of the peace.
She was later prosecuted for breach of the peace only and found not guilty.
Miss Devlin said that while in the police station she told Mr Howie she wanted
him charged with assault. ``He replied: `Your type cannot afford that' and
called me a bitch. I couldn't believe it. He was shouting, more or less
spitting it out.''
she denied that she was involved in a drunken full-scale fight with another
woman when she was arrested.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
