<HEADLINE>Dogged deterrent to drug dealers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241251</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STRATHCLYDE Police have come up with a new drugs deterrent to help clean
Glasgow's streets of dealers - Taz the retriever.
He looks just like any other family pet but the alert three-year-old has a
finely tuned nose which can sniff out an illegal substance in seconds.
Taz is the only police sniffer dog in Britain with the skills to detect drugs
on the human body. The black short-haired hound has already pounced on a number
of drugs carriers and suppliers in the past four months - many from queues of
people waiting to enter the city's clubs and pubs.
Yesterday, he demonstrated his skills in Glasgow's busy Central Station by
screening the crowds and detecting three separate decoys carrying ecstasy,
cannabis, and heroin.
On detecting the drugs carrier, Taz sits beside his target until an officer
arrives. He is then given a ball to play with as a reward for his work.
Taz took six weeks to train at a cost of #3000. He will be joined by two more
dogs, one of which will be used on city streets.
Taz's handler, PC Jardine Smith, said: ``Taz is taller than other sniffer dogs,
which means he has good access to places where people carry drugs such as
pockets, waistbands, and underpants.''
</TEXT>
