<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Muslims and refugees remain victims in carve-up of Bosnia</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241252</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN THE Middle East, Palestinians and Israelis proclaimed a ``peace of the
brave''. In Dayton, Ohio, the warring factions in the Balkans finally conceded
a peace of the exhausted, defeated, resentful, and bitterly disappointed.
Resolving the fate of the West Bank and Jerusalem is simplicity itself compared
with sorting out Bosnia in the wake of its horrible civil war, and the fate of
Yitzhak Rabin is no doubt a reminder to Slobodan Milosevic and Alija
Izetbegovic of the dangers they face.
There would have been no peace in either conflict without relentless American
pressure, and the agreement on Bosnia will certainly fail without continuing
American leadership of a great international effort to make it work. Tens of
thousands are dead and hundreds of thousands of refugees have lost their homes
because leaders vacillated for years, while Bosnia burned.
The bottom line is that Franjo Tudjman of Croatia, who played a large part in
igniting the first Yugoslav war in 1991, has got most of what he wanted while
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia has renounced, at least for now, his hopes of
creating a Greater Serbia. The Muslims of Bosnia, history's victims, ground
down between those unforgiving tyrants, have been forced to accept the
partition of their country under a fig-leaf central government.
The agreements have to be ratified by the people on the ground, starting with
the Bosnian Serbs whose first reaction was to reject the Dayton agreement out
of hand. Their representatives refused to attend Tuesday's ceremony when the
three presidents initialled the document.
They will have to allow their two most popular leaders, General Ratko Mladic
and their titular president, Radovan Karadzic, to leave office (there is not
much hope that they will ever be prosecuted for their crimes). They must give
up their control of western Sarajevo and admit that the city will be reunited
under the control of the Bosnian Government.
Furthermore, they must give up territory along the front lines in the east and
open a wide corridor to the Goradze pocket, which will be enlarged.
They must pull their troops back from the confrontation lines, to allow the
Nato peace-keepers to interpose themselves between the two sides. Lastly,
within two years, the last pocket of Serb-controlled Croatia must be handed
over. Its leaders have already denounced the agreement.
It will require all Mr Milosevic's authority to bend the Serbs to the
inevitable.
They have also had to renounce their hopes of enlarging the Brcko, or Posavina,
corridor in the north. That heavily-fortified pass will be taken over by the
Americans, who will this way control the movement of Serbian forces and
supplies between eastern and western Bosnia, with all the dangers that implies.
In exchange for these concessions, the Serbs will recover a swathe of territory
in the west that they lost in the last Croatian-Muslim offensive. This will be
a bitter pill for the Muslims to accept, because they must abandon hope of
controlling a direct road between central Bosnia and Bihac in the east. The
British will have the task of separating the two armies there.
Furthermore, thousands of Croatian and Muslim refugees who were summarily
resettled in the area, around Mrkonjik Grad, will have to move again. The
Muslims have no choice: the territory is controlled by the Croatian army.
There are 500,000 to one million Muslim refugees, driven from their homes in
eastern Bosnia, from Prijedor and Banja Luka in the west; and the victims of
Croat ethnic cleansing in south-central Bosnia, still camped on the hillsides
and public spaces of central Bosnia.
The Dayton agreement specifies that all refugees will be allowed to return
home, but no-one seriously believes that the people of Srebrenica will return.
President Izetbegovic said on Tuesday: ``This is not a just peace, but it is
more just than a continuation of the war.'' The refugees who have nothing to
hope for may not agree.
Winter has come early this year and the first task of international relief will
be to provide for them: there are hundreds of thousands of Serb refugees, too,
in Banja Luka and eastern Bosnia, and in Serbia itself, who were driven out of
Krajina.
The people who have come out best from the war and the peace are the Croats.
They have recovered almost all their national territory and are promised the
rest, Eastern Slavonia, within two years. They have driven almost all the Serbs
out of Croatia, at least 150,000 people, to form a nearly homogeneous state.
Bosnia has been partitioned into three. The Serbs have the lion's share, 49% of
the territory for a third of the population. The Croats, too, have done well.
They had 20% of the population and now control at least a quarter of the
country.
The only victory the Muslims can claim, besides the bare fact of their
survival, is Sarajevo. The future central government, which will supervise both
the Bosnian-Croatian Federation and the Serb Republic of Bosnia, has what the
Serbs call ``a paper roof''.
It has no army and no arrangements yet for a police force. But it will control
the capital, and if Sarajevo can recover its pre-war cosmopolitan, democratic,
and liberal ways, that oasis of civilisation may eventually spread to the rest
of the country.
</TEXT>
