<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A sick society</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241254</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHRIS HOLME argues that increases in NHS patients treated is not necessarily a
healthy sign
EXTRAPOLATION is a new disease afflicting Cabinet ministers and health analysts
alike. Triggered by a diet of too much raw data, it often leads to chronic
verbal diarrhoea.
The Government boasts how increases in funding and patients treated show the
health service in good shape. Opposition politicans and unions fall into the
same trap, seeing mere bed numbers as totems of the welfare state's vitality.
But their mistake is not to see the NHS for what it is, an illness rather than
a health service. Society's sense of well-being is usually in inverse
proportion to how busy its hospitals are.
Lothian's director of public health, Dr Helen Zealley, has developed this theme
in her annual report. It chronicles a variety of increases in self-injury,
self-poisoning, divorce rates, hospital emergencies for unspecified complaints,
and higher rates of mental ill-health and distress.
``All of these appear to be symptoms of a society which seems to be in danger
of losing the vital feature of neighbourliness,'' she says.
This also shows itself with Lothian now having the highest rates of abortion
and unwanted pregnancies in Scotland.
Abortion rates in the region have risen two-thirds over the last decade among
women under 20, to the extent that more than 40% of healthy teenage pregnancies
now result in termination. So much for the extrapolated myth of young women
using childbirth as a passport to housing and benefits.
The overall abortion figure increased by 10% last year to 2281, leaving
Edinburgh with a rate 50% higher than the rest of Scotland.
``These are matters of concern which need to be addressed,'' Zealley says.
``I am pleased at the reduction in births but I am sorry to see that it is
being achieved through termination. What is needed is better education about
sexual relationships and use of contraception, including the morning-after
pill.''
Education, she argues, should start with reinforcing young women's confidence
to say no to sex in a relationship.
There are other familiar home truths of a changing society. Use of recreational
drugs like ecstasy was increasingly common among teenagers.
``Importantly, for those seeking to address the dilemmas, illegal drug use was
seen to be the norm, even among those who did not use drugs themselves,''
Zealley says.
Her report reveals that heart disease continues to decline and is no longer the
biggest single killer in Lothian, a position it has held every year since 1959.
It has been overtaken by cancer, where rates among women are still rising due
to increased smoking.
Those searching for the feel-good factor in reams of NHS statistics are more
likely to find a sick society instead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Anger blazes behind the smokescreen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALLAN LAING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241255</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is still happening. In the sleepy Middle American town of Wenatchee
(population 24,000) well-intentioned state prosecutors claimed two weeks ago
that dozens of children had been systematically raped and molested over a
seven-year period by as many as 80 adults, including the local pastor and his
wife. The devil, it seems, continues to make work for idle hands.
But whose hands? The accused or the accusers? There is little doubt where the
sympathies of television dramatist Michael Eaton lie. There is, he declares, a
social phenomenon around. It centres, not just on accusations of child abuse.
Not even on accusations of ritual child abuse. It centres on bizarre claims of
the organised international satanic-inspired abuse of children.
It started in the States during the eighties, moved to Australia, and
eventually raised its rather ugly and sordid head in Britain just a few years
ago. In Scotland it manifested itself in two celebrated cases, in Ayrshire and
Orkney. Children were removed from their mothers' arms - sometimes for years -
in a frenzy of institutional hysteria.
Eaton, who graduated with a degree in social anthropology, does not believe a
word of it. Which is why he has attempted to redress the balance by writing a
controversial fictional drama on the subject. Flowers of the Forest, a powerful
and harrowing film starring Pauline Collins, Lia Williams, Clive Russell, and
Annette Crosbie, has just completed shooting in Scotland. It was commissioned
by BBC Scotland and will be shown as a Screen Two movie next year.
To Eaton controversy is a familiar friend. He wrote the script for ITV's Shoot
To Kill drama-documentary about Northern Ireland which was accused of being
pro-IRA. More recently, he wrote the acclaimed religious drama series, Signs
and Wonders.
It is a brave move, perhaps even a foolhardy one, on Eaton's part to tackle the
ritual child abuse issue as a television drama. He may well be on a hiding to
nothing; a no-win situation. Indeed, before he even put pen to paper he was the
target of strong criticism. For research purposes he visited Orkney and, along
with BBC Scotland, was immediately accused of making a tasteless bid to grab
the ratings. Fears were expressed that, by setting the film in an un-named
Highland village, viewers would immediately think that the events portrayed
were what really happened in Orkney or Ayr.
Eaton is quick to stress that nothing could be further from the truth. He is
also anxious to make the point that Flowers of the Forest is an entirely
fictional account and not based on any particular case.
``These accusations of systematic child abuse are incredibly disturbing to me.
Social workers seem to have an agenda and believe only the answers that confirm
their hypothesis. They put words in the children's mouths. And yet there is
still the perception around - and not just in social work departments - that
there is no smoke without fire. I wanted to write a drama that says that it is
perfectly possible for there to be smoke without fire. I have tried to look at
the subject dramatically in order to get behind the headlines,'' he explains.
The film centres on the fictional Mid West Highland Social Work Department. Two
young children from a local village are brought in because they have been
running wild. Senior social worker Janet Hinton (Williams) suspects that they
have been abused. When Aileen Matthews (Collins), an expert from the Christian
fundamentalist New Morning Trust, is brought in, they become convinced of the
existence of a widespread network of ritual abuse.
The drama then explores the devastating effects which the allegations have upon
the tight-knit community. Why did Eaton choose Scotland? England, after all,
has had more than its fair share of such cases - in Rochdale, Cleveland, and
Nottingham. One reason for setting the drama North of the Border was the simple
fact that BBC Scotland had expressed an interest in commissioning the piece.
But, more importantly, Eaton believes that the absurdity of the child abuse
phenomenon is magnified in Scotland because, unlike England, our legal system
offers an extra layer of protection in the form of the Children's Panel system.
``People I know in the social work profession in England told me that they were
particularly surprised when the Orkney and Ayrshire cases came up because they
thought the Scottish system was so much better. In England social workers seem
to be able to do what they want.
``It is also the case that Lord Clyde's Report on the Orkney case was the first
to say publicly that the children were being interviewed in disclosure sessions
by people who were not trained child psychologists. They didn't know how to ask
the questions or how to deal with the information they had,'' adds Eaton.
Of his research trip to Orkney, he says: ``I went there and spoke to quite a
few people and there was this press speculation that I was writing a
drama-documentary about the Orkney case. That is not the case.
``It would have been not only morally wrong to do a drama-documentary about one
case in particular, but also legally impossible because the information that
one needed in order to make the points, was not available.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The tell-tale signs of these stressful times</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANN SHAW</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Illustrattion</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241256</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DO you skip meals because you haven't time to eat properly, drink too much
coffee, take work home with you, find you haven't time for exercise or
relaxation, and work long hours because you are worried about losing your job?
Have you cut back on your social life and has your marriage suffered? Are you
worried that you don't have enough money for the things you need? If you can
answer yes to even half of those questions then you are part of today's
stressed workforce.
Six years ago stress in the workplace was an unknown phenomenon. Today it's on
everyone's lips. The major cause is the restructuring of the workforce,
bringing with it job losses and uncertainty.
Some companies are beginning to tackle it, though many are afraid - regarding
it as a huge can of worms which, once opened, they will have neither the skill
nor the resources to handle.
But the problem has to be tackled if long-term damage to people's health is not
to happen. Lothian Health Trust, with its 25,000 employees, have taken a
positive step forward with their Healthy Workplace Strategy. They sent a
questionnaire to employees, analysed the results, produced a report, then held
a one-day seminar on Stress in the Workplace in Edinburgh.
They invited top organisational psychologist, Professor Tom Cox of Nottingham
University, to give the keynote speech as part of their plan towards developing
the strategy.
Cox quickly dismissed the idea that the solution lay in bringing in outside
stress consultants with their armoury of alternative therapy. Sending a nurse
for aromatherapy may temporarily alleviate her stress problems but it would not
tackle the root cause. ``You have to ask yourself why your employees need these
things in the first place,'' he said. ``The key lies in good management. Find
out what causes the stress then devise ways of coping with it.''
He used the analogy with fighter pilots. They are under tremendous stress, but
they handle it. Why? Because they are highly trained for the job. They get
tremendous support and they have control over what they do.
Only by introducing similar systems with the emphasis on training support and
giving people more control over their work will we see stress levels reduced.
Workplace stress must now be taken seriously following the landmark court case
involving social work manager John Walker who sued Northumberland County
Council in November 1994 for #200,000.
If people say they are ill they are ill, said Cox, and they are likely to die
sooner than those who are unstressed.
So, how do you define stress? Cox said quite simply it's placing more demands
on a person than they have the ability to cope with. The effects of
work-related stress include poor timekeeping, increased sickness, and a high
staff turnover.
He added that the most effective method of reducing stress is to train people
to do the job properly. Managers had a variety of tools to help them reduce
stress in the workplace ranging from redesigning jobs, restructuring work,
better training, and more effective management systems, to counselling, health
screening, group discussions and even helplines.
But we also have to rethink what we mean by work, he said. Just back from
Helsinki where he had taken part in an international conference on
tele-working, he added: ``The issues raised by tele-working touch fundamentally
on the structure of future workplaces. A significant portion of people will be
involved in tele-working and an even greater number will work from home.''
He said the process of moving us all back into the home, which is similar to
that prior to the industrial revolution, is already under way and it poses all
kinds of problems: do we design homes differently in the future to take care of
this? Do we have to recreate a new set of health and safety regulations and do
we have to go around and inspect homes?
Already the European Commission is investigating how some quality of working
life for people can be maintained when they are no longer gathered together in
traditional workplaces.
He said: ``In one sense we are going back and in another sense we are going
forward by exploiting telecommunication technology. People will be able to do
their jobs wherever they are, whether at home or on a park bench.''
The ``virtual company'' of the future can be one or two people with a bunch of
contracts and those people need not even be in the same country. Already some
of our major companies have their clerical work carried out on the other side
of the world and as a user of that company's services you would never know, eg,
an airline ticket booked in Manchester is processed in Delhi where a vast
source of skilled cheap labour exists on the Indian sub-continent.
Cox says these major social changes are both exciting and also potentially
stressful, especially for the individual whose job is changing rapidly.
He offers the following advice:
If you are worried about your job then try to seek more information so that you
are better informed about the changes taking place within your company. You
should try to become part of that process otherwise there is a danger of
finding yourself pushed aside.
Often people worried about their jobs withdraw so they don't know as much as
they could about what is going on. Secondly, seek support from colleagues. If
you have a medical or psychological problem then go and consult your GP.
But these issues have to be tackled at an organisational level too. Managers
need to be asked if they are managing the process of change in the best
possible way. There's evidence that the uncertainty of job changes damages the
staff who remain, as well as the staff who leave. A good manager will not want
to damage the survivors because it is on them that the company is going to rely
heavily in years to come.
The Edinburgh seminar received a mixed response from workers within Lothian
Health Trust because the trust is in the process of negotiating more staff
cuts. Des Loughney, a member of Edinburgh Trades Council, said: ``Stress in the
workplace is a political problem as well as an educational one. There are some
managers using stress as a disciplinary weapon to get rid of people they don't
want.''
Stress, added Cox, is like the old song: It Ain't What You Do, It's The Way
That You Do It. ``At the end of the day it comes back to good management.''
</TEXT>
