<HEADLINE>Settlement rests on thin ice</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241257</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Settlement rests on thin ice
THE Dayton peace treaty is likely to push Bosnia off the front pages in coming
months and bring relief to civilians tormented by three winters of savage
warfare. However it is a peace of exhaustion, not of reason.
No meeting of minds has occurred between the protagonists during their 20 days
closeted together in middle America. The chief war party, the Bosnian Serbs of
Radovan Karadzic, were not even there, but were quick to denounce a sell-out by
President Milosevic, acting on their behalf. The unpalatable terms of the deal
have also opened up divisions within the Sarajevo government and between Bosnia
and Croatia, locked in a loveless marriage known as the Muslim-Croat federation
of Bosnia.
Only Croatia and Serbia seem to have turned over a new leaf. Zagreb is ready to
normalise relations with Belgrade now that it has recovered its lost territory.
But this may only fuel the territorial ambitions in Bosnia of Croat leader
Franjo Tudjman.
It was territorial disputes that produced the nail-biting finale to Dayton and
may yet give rise to a still-born peace.
The main concern of the Bosnian Serbs has been to safeguard the narrow corridor
of land across northern Bosnia through which most of their supplies come. It is
vulnerable to a Muslim-Croat attack following the losses suffered in the
autumn. President Milosevic's insistence on security guarantees for the
Posavina corridor made the talks run beyond Monday's US deadline but he got
little thanks from the militants of the self-styled Republic of Srpska, who
view him as a traitor to the Serb cause.
The final loss of the Muslim enclaves of Zepa and Srebrenica has produced
similar ill-will within the Muslim camp. One remaining enclave, Goradze, will
remain linked to Sarajevo by a corridor, presumably defended by Nato forces.
Meanwhile, in northern Bosnia where Muslim forces made big gains in the autumn,
the peace deal is likely to be treated with contempt by the army. It prevents
further advances on what were once mainly Muslim towns like Prijedor, the scene
of brutal ethnic cleansing in 1992, which Bosnian troops are now virtually in
sight of. They are convinced they could capture this land and they may press
forward regardless of any orders not to do so.
The danger is that populist politicians will try to exploit both the unrest of
the military and the refugees from which the Bosnian army is now largely
staffed. Muhamed Sacirbey, the foreign minister, offered his resignation at the
weekend perhaps to distance himself from a deal which amounts to partition by
any other name and is likely to divide his government.
The status of Sarajevo itself remains in doubt after Dayton. The Serbs still
hope to partition it while their opponents hope it will be the seat of a
unified Bosnia.
Constitutionally, Sarajevo will be the capital of a two-state country. A single
government and parliament are envisaged after internationally-supervised
elections. But how it can work in a Bosnia where Serb nationalists retain
institutions like a separate police force and security service is not clear.
Public figures found guilty of war crimes by the Hague Tribunal under Judge
Goldstone are barred from political life. But even if Karadzic and General
Milosevic retire to the shadows, it is hard to see how co-operation can grow
among the bitterest of foes to make a rickety constitution last for more than a
few weeks or months.
How citizens traumatised by war can be expected to trust a new government
composed of former enemies is hard to imagine. Most Bosnians (the highest
estimate being 2.7 million) are now refugees. They have the right to return and
vote in their own localities according to Dayton. But how can they be expected
to return to areas controlled by those who expelled them?
The fate of Muslims driven from their homes in Mostar during the 1993
Croat-Muslim civil war, suggests that no return will be possible for most
refugees: despite the federation uniting former enemies, the Croats running
most of Mostar simply thumb their noses when the European Union official
supervising the reconstruction of the city asks for the right of return.
It is likely that the Nato forces enforcing the Dayton agreement will be unable
to guarantee safe passage to refugees who wish to occupy their own homes again.
Tuesday's agreement does not require the demilitarisation of Bosnia which will
probably make a mockery of the promise of freedom of movement through the new
state. Weapons will flow to the Muslims but the US appears likely to block the
arrival of heavy weapons which is what they mainly lack. The beleaguered Serbs
in their stronghold of Pale are already receiving military assistance from
Belgrade despite the bad blood between them. So an enduring peace seems a
chimera if it is accompanied by an arms build-up.
Dayton holds out little comfort for the large numbers of ethnically-mixed
Bosnian citizens, even less for millions of refugees who enjoy little prospect
of rebuilding shattered lives. Despite the brilliant solo effort of Richard
Holbrooke, ``the Balkan Kissinger'', the initiative could be blown away by
another rogue missile attack on Sarajevo or a Muslim attack on a Serb area.
Tom Gallagher lectures in peace studies at the University of Bradford.
</TEXT>
