<HEADLINE>Toll protests prompt delay</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241258</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEFORE campaigners gathered in Portree last night to consider future strategy
against the Skye bridge tolls, it emerged that none of the protesters who have
refused to pay the tolls since the bridge opened on October 16, will appear in
court this year.
One of the organisers of the Skye and Kyle Against the Tolls (Skat) campaign,
Skye councillor Gavin Scott-Moncrieff, claimed this was evidence of the
strength of public feeling on the issue.
``By our calculations there must be some 400 reports sent to the
procurator-fiscal in Dingwall since the bridge opened and obviously that has
delayed the process. We are pleased to have demonstrated by force of numbers
how strongly people feel about having such unjust tolls imposed on the people
of Skye, but our aim remains to get into court so we can challenge the legality
of the tolls,'' he said.
Procurator-fiscal David Hingston confirmed yesterday that there would be no
court case in 1995 but said he couldn't say how many reports of non-payment he
had now received.
Last night's meeting in Portree was called in order to show the strength of
local feeling in advance of tomorrow's meeting in Inverness of the new Highland
Council to maximise support for a motion tabled by all six Skye and Lochalsh
councillors urging measures to persuade the Scottish Office to change its
policy on skye Bridge tolls.
</TEXT>
