<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Court told 14-year-old   addict `out of control'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241260</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SHERIFF heard how a ``completely out of control'' teenager became addicted to
Temazepam at the age of 14.
At Paisley Sheriff Court yesterday, John Logan, 17, was sentenced to two years
in a young offenders' institution after admitting 11 separate charges.
The court was told he stole from his mother, a church, and social workers who
were trying to help him.
Procurator-fiscal David Green said the youth abducted two schoolboys, aged 15
and 12, and took them to a close in Paisley where he threatened to slit one
boy's throat.
The youngsters had been given money by their parents to buy school clothes and
Logan robbed each of them of #25.
Defence agent Paul Lynch said Logan's crime spree had coincided with his period
of addiction which was totally out of control and cost his client over #100 a
week.
The court was told that he stole from his stepfather and aunt and even robbed
his friends' families to get items to sell for cash.
Defence agent Paul Lynch asked with the sheriff to impose a sentence which
would allow his client to receive specialist counselling for his drug taking
and revealed that no such facility was available to inmates detained in Polmont
Young Offenders' Institution. He said that Logan had a chronic dependency on
Temazepam.
He added: ``Temazepam is synonymous with crime in the Paisley area.''
The solicitor urged Sheriff Dunlop not to sentence Logan to a further period of
detention, claiming that drugs were freely available to prisoners, and asked
for a disposal which would enable the teenager to put his wrecked life back
together again.
</TEXT>
