<HEADLINE>Ballot on Dounreay begins</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSSHighland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241261</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BALLOT papers were posted out yesterday to 20,632 voters in Caithness asking
them if they supported Dounreay's proposal to reprocess spent nuclear fuel from
33 research reactors worldwide.
The referendum has been organised by the Caithness Against Nuclear Dumping
group, which has raised #10,000 to pay for the independently conducted poll.
The referendum begins as the Government was accused of endangering jobs and
safety in the nuclear industry by pressing ahead with its privatisation plans.
Mr Tony Cooper, general secretary of the Engineers and Managers Association,
giving evidence before the Trades and Industry Select Committee yesterday, said
nuclear privatisation would also accelerate the so-called ``dash for gas''.
Mr Cooper added: ``There is pressure to bring forward the planned date for
privatisation from next summer because the Government needs to fund tax cuts.''
.q.A reactor at the Hartlepool nuclear power station in Cleveland has been out
of action for 10 days after a leak of mildly radioactive carbon dioxide gas, it
was revealed yesterday.
The plant's other reactor had not been operating following a fire in a nearby
transformer last month. The station is expected to be operating again by
tomorrow.
</TEXT>
