<HEADLINE>Warning over bogus workmen</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241262</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE have warned elderly people to be on their guard after a spate of
incidents involving two bogus workmen in Edinburgh and East Lothian.
The pair, said to have Irish accents, are believed to have stolen money from a
house in Royal Park Terrace where they had gained entry by saying they had to
check the electricity supply.
Judge installed
FORMER Lord Advocate, Lord Rodger of Earlsferry, 51, was installed as a judge
yesterday at a ceremony at Parliament House in Edinburgh. He replaces Lord
Allanbridge who retired earlier this month.
Clean-up squad
A NEW hit squad armed with a high-powered hose on a specially adapted vehicle
has been launched in Edinburgh to combat the dual problems of illegal
flyposting and dropped chewing gum. Armed with a high-power hose in a specially
adapted vehicle, the council-run team will patrol the city cleaning up property
hit by flyposters free of charge.
Road victim plea
POLICE are appealing for witnesses after pensioner Ms Sarah Naylor, 66, was
killed when struck by a car in Carntyne Road, Glasgow, on Sunday.
Fire death
A MAN died after a house fire in Ayr early yesterday. Firefighters found Mr Ian
Baillie, 35, unconscious in his bedsit at Bath Place, Ayr. He died on his way
to hospital.
Homes decline
PLACES for elderly people in residental care homes in Scotland fell last year
by 500 to 17,471, according to Scottish Office figures, reflecting moves
towards community care.
SNP holiday
STAFF of SNP-controlled West Lothian District Council are to be given a holiday
on St Andrew's day.
</TEXT>
