<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cup experience can turn boys into men</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN LORIMER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241263</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HUTCHESONS' Grammar School face an exacting test on Saturday against Irish
opponents Presentation College from Bray at Auldhouse, a fixture which,
according to Magnus Brown, a former Watsonians' back-row forward and the master
in charge of rugby, will provide his young charges with a different kind of
experience.
``Irish schools rugby is more like our club rugby. They play a really hard game
and are not inclined to take prisoners,'' says Brown, who reasons that the type
of uncompromising rugby played is a result of their participation in the Irish
Schools Cup.
``The cup is a high-profile competition which, in the later stages, attracts
huge crowds and involves big money. Teams like Presentation College train five
or six days a week, such is the pressure on them,'' says Brown.
Very few leading rugby schools have opted to take part in the equivalent
Scottish competition but Brown believes that situation could soon change.
He said: ``Schools are becoming more professional about rugby. More than one
school offers sports bursaries.''
As to Hutchesons' following the example of St Aloysius' by going into the cup,
Brown has mixed feelings. ``We have a good fixture list now. It is balanced and
well-structured round the district scene. We could fall into the trap of
playing too much rugby, dropping good fixtures to play less meaningful cup
games.
``But if a sufficient number of the leading rugby schools came into the
competition, we would need to allocate certain Saturdays for cup games.
Perhaps, too, some measure of seeding would be necessary.''
A week after the match against Presentation College, Hutchesons' will play
Strathallan in what Brown expects could be his side's hardest domestic fixture
this season. Fortunately for the Glasgow school, they will be back to nearly
full strength.
``We have been badly hit by injuries, particularly to sixth-year boys,''
explains Brown. But he added: ``We were forced to play a number of younger
players, including some fourth-year boys. That, however, should be good for the
future.'' And perhaps, too, for a strong Hutchesons' team in the Scottish
Schools Cup?
SCHOOLS RESULT
Fettes College 27, Glasgow HS 0.
</TEXT>
