<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Princess of Wales heads for a nation with a passion for powerful women Argentinians await the new Evita</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241264</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Princess of Wales last night headed out for Argentina and prepared to face
the renewed attentions of the world's media following her extraordinary
Panorama interview, which the BBC has so far licensed to be shown in 37
countries.
With the furore over her revelations continuing at home, 7000 miles away she
was set to be feted by macho Latins as an icon of womanhood.
The Princess may not want to be cast in the mould of former Argentine
President's wife Evita Peron, but to a tango-loving nation with a passion for
powerful, beautiful women, the temptation is too great.
The hard-hitting significance of the Princess's Monday night interview, in
which she admitted adultery and cast doubt on the suitability of her estranged
husband to be king, will be lost on her hosts.
Argentina's President Carlos Menem, a self-confessed ``seducer'' who is
separated from his wife, is more interested in being seen with the world's most
famous woman. Officially, the Princess is in Argentina on a semi-private
working visit at the invitation of a charity. Unofficially, however, the
four-day visit, beginning today, is official, laid on for the benefit of
President Menem.
She flew out as Argentine television broadcast the Panorama interview on
Channel 13 at lunchtime yesterday.
The princess was smiling as she boarded British Airways flight 267 from London
Heathrow airport bound for Buenos Aires at 9.15pm.
Wearing a knee-length black dress under a waist-length red jacket with a black
collar, she looked relaxed as she embarked on what is being seen as her new
career as ``ambassador'' for Britain.
In the TV interview, the princess marked out a future role as an ambassador for
Britain abroad, a role the visit to the Argentine will help develop.
On arrival she will visit a number of hospitals and an old people's home,
showing the caring side of her nature, and will meet President Menem in person.
Meanwhile senior Tories were claiming a divorce between the Waleses was
inevitable. Mr James Hill, secretary of the Tory back-bench constitutional
affairs committee, said MPs were now virtually unanimous in the view that a
divorce was the only option - in which case the princess could not become Queen.
Downing Street insisted there had been no Ministerial discussions about the
prospects for a divorce.
q.The Queen last night paid her first visit to the Queen Mother since her hip
replacement operation last week. Accompanied by the Duke of Edinburgh, the
Queen spent 40 minutes at the King Edward VII Hospital for Officers in London's
Marylebone.
q.Betting is being invited on who will be the next Queen - and the Princess of
Wales has started as even-money favourite. Mrs Camilla Parker Bowles is quoted
as 5-2 second favourite by bookmaker William Hill.
</TEXT>
