<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Farmer  ignored collapse of road bridge</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241265</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FARMER continued feeding his cattle after being told a bridge had collapsed
into a river, a fatal accident inquiry was told yesterday at Glasgow Sheriff
Court.
Mr William Stark, 51, said that the bridge where two teenagers drowned was
``not my responsibility''.
Lawyer Mr Andrew Pollock said: ``Is feeding cattle more important than saving
lives?''
Mr Stark: ``Are you trying to say that I should have had the road coned off and
it was my responsibility?''
Mr Pollock: ``Yes, I am.''
The lawyer then said that Mr Stark had not bothered to telephone the police or
done anything to stop a vehicle going into the river. ``You had washed your
hands of the whole thing,'' said Mr Pollock.
Mr Stark: ``I didn't wash my hands of it. I didn't expect anyone to go down the
road to the bridge.''
Mr Stark, of Twechar Farm, Twechar, said he was busy and carried on with his
work.
He was giving evidence during the inquiry into the deaths of John Furay, 17,
and James McClement, 17, both of Twechar, who drowned when a VW Polo driven by
John Furay plunged into the rain-swollen River Kelvin when Gavell Bridge near
their homes collapsed last December 11.
A third youth, James Gibson, 18, also of Twechar, escaped by kicking the car
door open and raised the alarm.
Mr Stark told Mrs Margaret Porter, leading the evidence, he had decided to
check his fields earlier that morning and drove a tractor over the bridge. He
said the water was higher than the arch.
That afternoon he was working in his farm when a youth stopped his car and told
him the bridge had collapsed. He carried on working and went in to feed his
cattle.
Questioned by Mr Pollock, for John Furay's family, he said the four fields
surrounding the bridge were his but added: ``The bridge is not my
responsibility.''
The inquiry continues.
</TEXT>
