<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>American football</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975241267</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DEFENSIVE back Dave Wilson will stop playing Cupid to keep a date with the
Scottish Claymores for next season.
There were fears that Wilson, who runs a dating agency with his girlfriend
Jodie in his hometown of Los Angeles, would stand the Claymores up. But Wilson,
who signed halfway through last season, will close his dating agency down for a
couple of months next summer to re-join the Claymores - and leave some
Californian romantics with broken hearts.
``Jodie knows how much it means to me to come to Scotland to play and she is
fully supportive,'' he said. ``I'm really looking forward to the new season.''
Head coach Jim Criner also announced that 6ft 7in defensive lineman James
Spencer will re-join the team. He was signed from Barcelona Dragons with just
three games left last season but made an instant impact.
Hockey
BRITAIN yesterday stayed on course for a place in the Atlanta Olympics at the
qualifying tournament in Cape Town, where they secured a 2-2 draw with European
champions Holland, thanks to the influence of the Scottish players on the
scoreboard.
Twice in arrears through scores by Suzan van der Wielen and Jeanette Lewin,
Great Britain fought back each time to level the score thanks to Rhona Simpson
and Susan Fraser. Results:
Argentina 1, Canada 0; Korea 3, China 1; Germany 1, South Africa 0; Holland 2,
Great Britain 2.
Latest placings - 1, Germany (8 points); 2, Korea (7); 3, Argentina (7); 4,
Great Britain (6); 5, Holland (5); 6, China (3); 7 South Africa (3); 8, Canada
(1).
Today's games: South Africa v China, Holland v Canada.
Golf
DEFENDING champions Kilmarnock Barassie got off to a good start in the European
Club Cup in Portugal yesterday with ann aggregate of 148 over the Vilamoura
course. Gordon Sherry posted a three-over-par 75 and Alan Reid went two better
on 73, while Jim Milligan's 83 was the non-counter.
They left Scottish club champions Kelso far behind, with he Border boys
managing only 169, 25 over par. Scores were counted from Ian Ford and Ian
Lauder.
Weightlifting
GREECE'S Pirros Dimas set a new clean and jerk record in the men's 83kg
category at the World championships in China yesterday. Dimas lifted 212.5kg,
beating his own mark of 211kg set at the European championships in May.
Earlier, China's Tang Weifang set a world record in the women's 70kg category
when she lifted 129.0kg in the clean and jerk. The previous record of 128.5kg
was set by compatriot Zhou Meihong in Istanbul last year.
