<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241268</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE brother of Rosemary West said yesterday: ``I fear she will hang herself
like Fred.''
Graham Letts said: ``I don't think she will be able to cope. I sure she will
try and do the same as Fred did and hang herself.
``I think she will be in tremendous shock. I know she thought she was going to
get off.
``She was really convinced she was going to walk away from this.
``She is a tough person but the thought of being in prison will be more than
she can cope with.
``I really fear she will try and kill herself.
On the verdict, he added: ``We were prepared for it, but it has still come as a
tremendous shock.
``I tried to prepare the children for the worst - but how on earth can you
prepare for something like this.
``There was always a fear that she would be found guilty and now it has
happened we will have to try and go away and rebuild or lives.''
The magistrate who fined Rosemary and Fred West for a brutal sex attack on a
teenager 22 years ago said yesterday: ``My conscience is clear.''
Mr John Smith, 86, was chairman of the bench when the Wests appeared before
Gloucester Magistrates charged with stripping, gagging, and indecently
assaulting lodger Carol Raine in 1973.
Just minutes after yesterday's conviction, he said: ``I certainly don't think I
was too lenient.
``I have nothing on my conscience whatsoever. I have nothing further to say.''
A witness in trial called for the death sentence for serial murderers and said
she would happily act as executioner of the woman who tormented her.
Kathryn Halliday, 37, who told the Winchester trial jury she was subjected to
``violent and aggressive'' lesbian sex by West, said: ``I would personally
volunteer to press the button on the electric chair or flick the switch to hang
her.
``That is what she deserves, that is what would give me most pleasure.''
Ms Halliday said she was ``absolutely delighted'' with Rosemary West's fate.
``At one stage we began to fear that she may get off on some of the murders,
but she has got what she deserves.
``I have always said there was a pact between Frederick and Rose West and I
believe there are still many more bodies to be found.''
Tory MP Barry Porter called on Home Secretary Michael Howard to give a pledge
that he would never contemplate the release of Rosemary West from prison.
Mr Porter, MP for South Wirral, said: ``It is simply beyond belief that any
Home Secretary, present or future, could even contemplate the possibility of
ever freeing her.''
Mr David Shaw, Conservative MP for Dover, said: ``The Home Secretary must now
give an undertaking that, within the powers he possesses, he would never allow
her to be released.
``Her crimes were so appalling that this is certainly a case where capital
punishment would be appropriate. However, we need to be assured that she will
remain in prison for the rest of her natural life, never to savour freedom
again.''
Wests' neighbours spoke of their relief at the verdicts.
Ernest and Olive Miles are the longest remaining residents at Cromwell Street
where number 25 stands derelict and boarded up.
Mrs Miles, 76, who has lived with her husband at number 45 for 48 years, said
the guilty verdicts were the right ones.
``What happened there within the walls of number 25 was the work of the devil -
the work of Satan,'' said Olive.
``No-one will ever know whether she was forced into it by her husband or not,
but guilty was the only verdict that the jury could have reached.''
Husband Ernest, 79, called for Rosemary West to be hanged.
``Prison's not good enough for her. She deserves all she gets for what she put
those innocent young women and girls through. How could any woman be party to
the murder of her own daughter and her little step-daughter?
``They should hang her in the centre of Gloucester - most local people would
agree with me and probably enjoy the spectacle,'' he said.
Dave Limbrick, 31, who lives at number 57, said: ``She must have known what was
going on under her own roof.
``I had met Fred West on the street a number of times. He seemed a bit thick
and was always grinning with a stupid smile on his face.
``We just thought he was happy about life in general, but we all know now it
was probably something far more sinister.''
He added: ``No-one noticed anything out of the ordinary. There were no real
clues to what was going on. Fred was always doing jobs for other people so it
didn't seem strange that he was always digging or doing jobs on the house.''
Cathy Barry, 20, is a relative newcomer to Cromwell Street.
The media studies student who lives at number 19 was well aware she was moving
to an infamous road but later found out that her bedroom was built by Fred West.
She said: ``My mother told me not to read the papers during the trial as she
thought it would frighten me, but I'm not really bothered. The bodies are all
gone now and life has to go on.
``You hear a lot about what the Wests were like. They seem to be weird but
no-one picked up on any clues.''
Miss Barry added that she and around a dozen other residents of Cromwell Street
had been paid to appear on ITV's The Time The Place discussion programme today
to describe what life is like living on Cromwell Street.
She said: ``Some people say they are tired of all the attention, but most love
it really.''
Last night, the wilting remains of bouquets of flowers laid in tribute to the
victims were on display outside number 25.
The doors and windows of semi-detached house were boarded up and the gate to
the back garden was locked to deter sightseers.
As darkness fell and people returned to their cars, television crews lit up the
neighbourhood with powerful lights.
Locals jeered at camera crews as they filmed the empty house - complete with a
freshly painted stripe of whitewash to cover obscene graffiti that has appeared
during the trial.
The infamous ``25 Cromwell Street'' iron sign that became synonymous with the
killings had been seized during the course of the police investigation.
Police have tried to ward off souvenir hunters.
Meanwhile, councillors and Gloucester's city mayor spoke of the notoriety that
the Wests' depravity had brought on the cathedral city.
Mayor Rose Workman said: ``We are all shocked and the people of Gloucester will
try their best now to get themselves back to what they were doing before.''
Continuing speculation over the presence of more bodies in the area would no
doubt continue to keep the city in the limelight, but Mrs Workman said: ``All
over the country parents who have had children leave home and who haven't heard
from them since must be wondering whether their children are still alive.
``I urge them if they are still alive, please ring home to let them know
they're OK.''
Despite the ghoulish reputation the city may have acquired during the West
chapter, tourist boss Philip Cooke said there had been no change in the number
of visitors.
One lesson for the future might be learned. A children's charity said adults
must learn to listen to children when they give out signals that there is
something wrong within their family.
Valerie Howarth, executive director of Childline, said it should not be
forgotten that the West murders only came to light after a remark by a child to
a Gloucestershire social worker who took it seriously and alerted police.
``The lesson for us all is that, no matter how fantastic a child's story may
seem, children should be listened to when they give out signals that there is
something very wrong in their families,'' said Mrs Howarth.
</TEXT>
