<HEADLINE>EU holidays `would help millions'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241269</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOUR million British workers would gain additional holiday entitlements under
the EU working-time directive due to come into force in November 1996, a TUC
report claims today.
Britain, alone, is challenging the directive in the European Court of Justice.
Launching the report, Give Us A Break, TUC general secretary John Monks called
on the Government to end its ``workhouse mentality'' and endorse the directive.
Due to be introduced on November 23, 1996, the directive will provide an
immediate right to a minimum of three weeks paid annual leave, rising to four
weeks by 1999.
British workers stand to gain most from the directive as Britain is the only EU
member state with no legal right to paid leave. According to the TUC, over two
million British workers - eight out of 10 of them part-timers - get no paid
holiday leave at all while over four million - nearly one in five of all
employees - currently get less than four weeks paid leave per year.
Britain and the Netherlands share bottom place in the EU public holidays league
with just eight a year.
</TEXT>
