<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The banality of evil: the gruesome secrets of a `naff' home In the House of Horror</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DUNCAN CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241270</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE bones have long since been removed, but everyone walks around the white
ribbon marking the site where each of the the nine victims was unearthed, as if
it was a grave in a cemetery.
A white ribbon in the shape of a square and a card inscribed with the words
``Heather May West'' identifies the spot in the back garden where the Wests'
eldest daughter was found.
The patio under which she was buried has been dug up now, and the surface of
the Wests' back garden, where they used to hold their family barbecues, is now
one of uneven dirt and gravel.
The place where the bodies of Alison Chambers, Shirley Robinson, and Lynda
Gough were found were also marked with white ribbon and their names marked by
police for benefit of the jury, who walked around in pairs and in silence.
The extension built by Frederick West has largely been torn down, its dividing
walls marked by white and yellow painted stones.
The front door, through which so many victims were hustled, is jungle green
with 15 panels of gold, white, and blue glass.
On the back of an interior ground-floor door is a slightly old-fashioned,
almost life-size poster of a smiling young woman in a black nightdress, with an
unmade bed behind her.
The green door to the ground-floor front room - Rose's Room, as it was for some
time - has a peephole covered by a wooden cap. It is above waist level for
someone of average height, but at a height that would require a very short man,
like West, to stoop only slightly to see what was going on inside.
Inside the room, the peephole is obscured by a lucky white horseshoe. The floor
is covered by cut-up squares of carpet material in garish purple, green,
orange, and blue. Above the place where the bed would have been are two lights
fixed at an angle on the wall and pointing down.
The wallpaper is pink and blue, and there is a painting on a piece of hardboard
of a yellow vase with flowers in one corner. The most striking thing about the
room is how tiny it is, even without furniture.
The other ground-floor room, which was the Wests' bedroom, has a floral
wallpaper with cornflowers and pink stripes. A basin and sink unit with louvred
doors is in the corner, and there is an white artexed ceiling with fake black
beams.
In her statement, witness Miss X, described West's taste as ``naff''. There is
nothing in this room, or anywhere else in the house, to suggest she was being
unkind.
The 15 brown-carpeted stairs and dull green bannister lead to the first floor,
with its green weeping willow tree-pattern wallpaper, peeling as is most of the
wallpaper in the house.
On the first floor at the back, the wallpaper is a pattern of Chianti bottles,
wine glasses, corkscrews, tongs, carriage clocks, old-fashioned lamps, floral
plates, coffee pots, and vases of flowers.
On the same floor is the bathroom, ``the office'' as the Wests used to call it,
with its matching avocado bath and basin.
Nearby is the old bar-room, one wall of which is covered by a Caribbean scene,
of the kind seen in suburban travel agents in the seventies.
On the left in the picture are Bird of Paradise flowers familiar to tourists to
the Canaries and a rocky cliff runs down to the beach and the clear blue sea: a
scene from a tacky rum commercial.
The rest of the room is papered in floral flock, and there are two lamps with
cream shades beside what was once a fireplace.
Up a further flight of 15 steps is the top back room, the mirrors room, which
is papered with a silvery grey tree design. There is a mirror at ground level
as you enter, and mirrors on the fitted, louvred wardroobe. There is a vanity
unit and artexed ceiling with the same fake beams as below.
The doors in both the top-floor rooms have latch-handles and are wooden in an
arched, ranch style.
On the landing a small trapdoor leads to the roof.
In the front room there is a boarded-up fireplace, red floral wallpaper, and a
white skirting board.
Back on the ground floor, two steps, then a turn, then a further six steps lead
into the cellar, where the bodies of other victims were found. Again the places
their bones were unearthed are marked with a simple name card and either a
small circle or square of white ribbon. Anyone of average height has to stoop.
Black beams run through the cellar, and one section has been cut out by the
police. That section contained four holes and it is assumed that bound, taped,
and gagged victims were suspended from here as the West's carried out their
horrific, sadistic, and depraved attacks.
On one wall is a childlike drawing of a couple of cowboys, one with a black hat
and Zapata moustache, the other with a cigar and a pistol in a holster on his
hip. What looks like a squaw, with a feather in her hair, is almost obliterated
by wear.
The phrase ``Tar 4 Ian'' followed by a heart is still visible on one wall and
there are children's scribbling marks in crayon.
Latterly, this was used as the children's bedroom. They slept above the remains
of victims.
The cellar is lit by builders' lights now, and one brick has been removed. You
can hear the sound of music from outside.
The most striking aspect of the house is how tiny it is, how small the rooms
are, and how close together. It would have been impossible for people within it
not to know the business of others.
The bodies were unearthed from tiny spaces. The low-ceilinged cellar is dark
and claustrophic. It is impossible to imagine how terrifying it must have been
for the victims to have been taken in there against their will.
</TEXT>
