<HEADLINE>Charlie Chester ill</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph </GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241271</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VETERAN entertainer Charlie Chester was seriously ill yesterday after suffering
a stroke at home.
Chester, 82, was taken unconscious to the Kent and Canterbury Hospital in
Canterbury on Tuesday night. His wife, Joan, was at his bedside yesterday.
``There has been some improvement overnight and he is now conscious but he is
to have a brain scan,'' said a BBC Pebble Mill spokesman yesterday.
Charlie Chester's Sunday Soapbox show on Radio 2 has been running since 1969.
The original idea was to have a radio letters page with listeners writing in
with their news and views.
Since then it has become a huge self-help show where people offer goods which
they would otherwise throw out and exchange them over the air. Chester, awarded
an MBE in 1991, is a former King Rat of the Grand Order of Water Rats - the
showbiz charity organisation.
</TEXT>
