<HEADLINE>Abusive student may go to jail</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241272</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POST-GRADUATE student, who has conducted a long-running campaign of abuse
against Aberdeen University and its Principal, Professor Maxwell Irvine, now
faces the prospect of imprisonment.
A judge has found Peter Dow in contempt of court and breach of interdict for
continuing his campaign.
Mr Dow, 29, has disrupted university meetings and issued thousands of leaflets.
He has likened Professor Irvine to Hitler and Stalin and described him ``and
his criminal gang'' as potential killers.
In a written judgment issued at the Court of Session yesterday, Lord Kirkwood
said that, in 1991, Dow, of Hollybank Place, Aberdeen, had his dissertation on
the subject of magnetic resonance imaging - a medical scanner technology -
failed by the university and he lost a series of appeals.
Mr Dow started a campaign against the university and in particular against the
Principal. He claimed that lives were being put at risk because his expertise
would not be available to the public.
In court, Mr Dow, who conducted his own case, admitted that he had continued to
publish and distribute thousands of leaflets. His position was that everything
in them was true and that the university was trying to stop him from telling
the truth.
The judge said Mr Dow had demonstrated quite clearly that he was incapable of
accepting any decision that went against him. His allegations were totally
without substance.
Another court hearing has been fixed for December 14 to consider what sentence
should be imposed.
</TEXT>
