<HEADLINE>Family holds the key to future of a semi</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DUNCAN CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241273</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE future of the house at 25 Cromwell Street, Gloucester, is still uncertain.
The early Victorian building, stands with its windows and doors bricked up, and
no firm decision has yet been taken. Its future rests largely in the hands of
the West family and solicitors.
The adjoining three-storey property, which is also privately owned, is unfit
for human habitation. Like its neighbour it was once divided into flats.
Number 25 has been gutted by the intensive activities of police search teams.
Its infamous cellar contains tons of concrete poured in after the digging to
preserve the foundations from collapse.
Restoration to any sort of habitable condition is likely to be costly.
Cromwell Street lies just outside an inner-city area which is expected to
attract #15m in regeneration grants.
But the 142-year-old West home - once owned by a former Mayor of Gloucester
from 1974-5, Mr Frederick King - is unlikely to attract much cash aid.
The house forms an important part of Fred West's estate, and automatically
falls to be divided among his widow and his children.
Gloucester City Council holds the mortgage, which is nearing the end of its
term. As the planning authority, it has an interest in any proposals for the
house and its site.
The council has not declared support for any particular option, but is unlikely
to favour schemes which might bring the ghoulishly curious to the area. It is
believed to prefer proposals which would have broad community support.
One scheme thought to be under consideration is the erection of a memorial in
the nearby central park - on the opposite side of which stands the Wests'
former home at 25 Midland Road.
A church group has proposed buying 25 Cromwell Street, razing it and creating a
memorial garden.
One wealthy local businessman, Mr Keith Gardner, raised more than #15,000 to
help the inter-faith group's bid. But he withdrew his support after it emerged
that the group also planned to build an office on the land.
Mr Gardner now plans to form a co-operative to buy the site.
Rosemary West could still benefit financially from her husband's estate of
which the house forms an important part.
As he died without making a will, she is entitled to a share of his estate
which could now be quite considerable.
However the real money-spinner for Rosemary West and the couple's children
could be documents and materials created as a result of the police inquiry.
Rosemary West's solicitor, Mr Leo Goatley, maintains: ``She does not wish to
benefit from Frederick West's estate. Anything of realisable value that is
legitimately within Frederick West's estate she would gift to her children.''
Up for sale are transcripts of more than 100 hours of taped police interviews
and taped interviews by Fred West's first solicitor, Mr Howard Ogden; papers
relating to Fred West's defence and, perhaps most sensational, a lengthy
document he wrote while being held on remand.
The document, thought to be a resume of his life story, and entitled ``I was
Loved by an Angel'', was recovered with other papers after he was found hanged
in his cell.
Potential buyers are likely to be the media. The material could command a
significant price. Already some members of the West family have attracted
five-figure sums for their life stories.
The Official Solicitor of the Supreme Court, Mr Peter Harris, has been
appointed to administer Fred West's estate.
A spokesman for Mr Harris said: ``However distasteful some of the material may
be, his legal duty as administrator of the estate is to obtain the best value
he can for the assets, in order first to satisfy legitimate claims on the
estate.''
</TEXT>
