<HEADLINE>Determined Scot wins duel with Sainz McRae is king of road after emphatic victory</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241274</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOTORSPORT
COLIN McRae yesterday completed an emphatic victory in the Network Q RAC Rally
to be crowned Britain's first world rally champion and the youngest-ever winner
of the title.
To achieve his second successive win in the British event the Scot tamed his
team-mate and rival Carlos Sainz to triumph by 36 seconds at the end of 28
testing special stages and four days of hectic action.
More than 2000 fans chanted ``easy, easy'' at the official rally finish at
Chester Racecourse while McRae sprayed champagne from the bonnet of his Subaru
Imprenza with co-driver Derek Ringer.
``I am sure this will be the first world championship of many for Colin, the
way he is driving at the moment,'' said team manager David Richards, whose
controversial decision last month could have cost 27-year-old McRae the title.
The relationship was strained almost to breaking point when Richards imposed
team orders on the Catalonia Rally in order to ensure that Sainz won, sending
both into the final event level on points.
McRae belatedly obeyed, but all that was forgotten in the moment of triumph
yesterday as he celebrated victory with his father Jimmy, who won the Historic
Rally, and brother Alister, who was fourth overall.
Colin deserved the title for the way in which he battled back after two
punctures had come close to deflating his championship dream on the second day.
``Colin had his setbacks in the early part of the rally, but there was never a
moment when he did not give the impression that he was in total control and
knew he could get the time back,'' added Richards.
The Lanark-born racer - whose previous successes have ensured a luxury
lifestyle, with homes in Switzerland and Monte Carlo - kept himself in
contention by hammering his broken suspension into shape with a log. He had
seen his lead wiped out in killer Kielder Forest in Northumberland, McRae
responded by gradually clawing back the 74-seconds deficit on Sainz.
McRae had to finish ahead of the double champion to take the title and
gradually gnawed away at the Spaniard's lead with a series of storming drives
in the rain-lashed, mud-splattered forest roads of Wales yesterday.
He won six of the seven timed tests to regain the lead on the final stage and
hold a 17-second cushion when the drivers returned to Wales for the climax.
McRae extended that to 38 seconds by winning the first four legs - taking his
rally total to 17 out of a possible 28 - before Sainz finally got the better of
him by three seconds. But he was never going to threaten further.
Richard Burns ensured Subaru added their first manufacturers' title by
finishing third - having nearly gone out on the first stage when his steering
broke - 6min 39sec down on the winner. ``This is just fantastic, especially as
I thought our rally was over after stage one,'' said Burns.
Final positions - 1, C McRae/D Ringer (Britain) Subaru 5-09-19; 2, C Sainz/L
Moya (Spain) Subaru 5-09-55; 3, R Burns/R Reid (Britain) Subaru 5-15-58; 4, A
McRae/C Wood (Britain) Ford 5-20-34; 5, B Thiry/S Prevot (Belgium) Ford
5-21-11; 6, G Evans/H Davies (Britain) Ford 5-42-07; 7, R Madeira/N Silva
(Portugal) Mitsubishi 5-44-04; 8, J Kytolehto/A Kapanen (Finland) Nissan
5-45-19; 9, M Kamioka/K Gormley (Japan/Britain) Subaru 5-50-21; 10, A Oreille/J
Boyere (France) Renault 5-50-40.
World drivers' championship - 1, McRae (Britain) 90pts; 2, Sainz (Spain) 85; 3,
Eriksson (Sweden) 48; 4, Delecour (France) 46; 5, Makinen (Finland) 38; 6,
Thiry (Belgium) 34; 7, Aghini (Italy) 26; 8, Liatti (Italy) 21; 9, Burns
(Britain) 16.
Manufacturers - 1, Subaru 350; 2, Mitsubishi 307; 3, Ford 223.
</TEXT>
