<HEADLINE>Highly rated on shoppers' list</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241275</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PERTH can claim to be Scotland's most popular shopping centre outside Glasgow
and Edinburgh, its pleasant surroundings offering an attractive and individual
environment.
The city has one of the highest proportions of independently owned specialist
retailing businesses in Britain, and with many of the well-known High Street
stores located there, the consumer is spoilt            for choice.
The city centre boasts famous names such as Marks &amp; Spencer, Frasers, Austin
Reid, Laura Ashley, Ernest Jones, James Thin and Waterstone, and the indepedent
sector is represented by McEwans of Perth, a department store with a trading
history of 125 years.
There are many small speciality shops offering a wide range of wares such as
international designer clothes, antiques, home furnishings, art and health
foods. Independent shops such as Ringmaker, Sandalwood Shoes, and Cairncross
the jewellers are also represented.
At the nearby St Catherine's Retail Park, the DIY enthusiast has Textile World,
Texas, MFI, Carpetwise, Concepts, B&amp;Q, Currys and Halfords. There is a Safeway
supermarket in the park, and the city also has Tesco and Asda stores.
Within the past few years, Perth has carried out some structural and
environmental improvements. Sign posting, pedestrianisation, street furniture
and hanging baskets have all received unanimous approval from retailers and
consumers.
There is ample long and short-term parking within a five or 10-minute radius of
the centre, and parking charges are low compared with other cities.
Excellent hotels and restaurants offer high quality cuisine including game,
salmon, beef, lamb, seafood and Scottish fruits. In celebration of the
district's produce and cuisine, Perth has established an annual Food Festival.
In fact, Perth is very much a city of festivals, with a Festival of Jazz and
Festival of the Arts as well as many sports events, including the Perth
Scottish Rally and Perth Golf Festival.
Recently the Fair City was recognised in Europe as the UK entry in Entente
Florale as Perth in Bloom - a city of lovely gardens and colourful hanging
baskets. The Perth in Bloom initiative has encouraged the whole community to
work together to protect and enhance Perth's natural setting and agricultural
inheritance.
It is this blend of civic pride which has brought national and international
awards to a city also renowned for its cleanliness and concern for the
environment.
House prices in and around Perth compare favourably with other areas in
Scotland. The average cost of a two-bedroom flat is #33,250 and a three-bedroom
semi-detached averages #46,600.
Here is how the housing stock breaks down: private 40,594 (sheltered 50), local
authority 13,230 (sheltered 132), housing association 690 (sheltered 174),
Scottish Homes 204.
The Band D council tax of #659 is below the Scottish average    of #670.
</TEXT>
