<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Farmers  may face BSE charge</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241277</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SEVERAL farmers suspected of selling cattle from herds infected with ``mad
cow'' disease BSE face prosecution, Strathclyde Trading Standards officials
warned yesterday.
It is believed that up to six cases are currently under investigation and
reports are being prepared for the procurator-fiscal.
The announcement follows the conviction of an Ayr farmer who admitted
submitting false documents relating to the sale of six cows. Richard Wilson was
fined #400 after he admitted four charges under the Trades Description Act.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Harassment tribunal told of name calling in office</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241278</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN accused of sexually harassing two women was called various abusive names
by colleagues, an industrial tribunal was told yesterday.
One of the women alleging harassment, a 37-year-old office worker, denied
calling or ever hearing colleagues call the man a ``left-footer'', a
``poofter'', or an upstart.
However, giving evidence on the second day of her sex discrimination case
against a Glasgow based company, she agreed he had been called Mr Perfect, a
weirdo, and Hitler, and claimed he described himself as ``the wee brat that
sits in the corner''.
She and another woman claim they were sexually harassed by a male colleague.
The tribunal has ruled that none of the parties involved can be identified
until the panel's decision is issued.
Solicitor David Walker, representing the alleged harasser, suggested to the
37-year-old woman that another woman, who she claimed had left because of the
way his client had treated her, had actually returned north to her family home
because of a business problem there.
She also told the tribunal that she did not know of a nickname being used for
him, and said she had never heard of him being called a rent boy, but agreed
she may have heard of him being called a weirdo, and it had been said he was a
``wee Hitler'', but not a ``poofter'', nor a ``left-footer''.
She said he had responded: ``I'm just the wee brat in the corner'' when someone
asked how he was.
``I don't think I called him any derogatory names, that I can recall. I don't
have a high opinion of him and have spoken to that effect, but I never called
him names.''
She claimed a female colleague would not speak out for fear of being a future
target.
The tribunal was told that he suffered from stress and the allegations made him
ill.
The hearing continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bosnian Serbs angrily reject deal done for them amid warnings that all parties must make it work.Balkan leaders take peace home</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241279</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sarajevo, Wednesday
BOSNIAN Government leaders returned home tonight to the cheers of hundreds of
Sarajevans who hope that they at last are seeing an end to the war that has
kept them bottled up in their besieged capital for three-and-a-half years.
A guard of honour stood at attention outside the presidency building in
Sarajevo and people threw flowers as President Alija Izetbegovic and Prime
Minister Haris Silajdzic arrived home from peace talks in the United States.
``Alija, we love you,'' people yelled, applauding their leader and the peace
they hope he has brought them.
However Silajdzic cautioned that the key to a lasting peace was full
implementation, something for which the international community and a Nato
force of up to 60,000 troops - one-third of them American - will be essential.
``We have peace on paper,'' Silajdzic said. ``Implementation is everything
now.''
``Sarajevo is a free town once this peace is implemented,'' he said. Provisions
in the peace deal reached in Dayton, Ohio, yesterday allow for Sarajevo to be a
united city under government control. Parts are currently held by Serbs.
That was a key government demand, and the spontaneous gathering of about 600
people to welcome him reflected the high hopes of Sarajevans that their city,
under Serb siege since April 1992, will again be free and united.
``I hope there will be no more war,'' said Haris Muratspahic, 11, who joined
the crowd on his way home from school. ``In peace, first I would like to go to
the sea.''
While Bosnian Government leaders reluctantly accepted the peace deal, Bosnian
Serbs angrily rejected it, claiming they were sold out at Dayton by Serbian
President Slobodan Milosevic, who negotiated on their behalf.
Their defiance has scuttled previous plans, and could be crucial once more.
Momcilo Krajisnik, a rebel leader, said the Bosnian Serb leadership rejected
the plan because it kept Sarajevo in Bosnian Government hands, allowed a land
corridor linking the Bosnian capital with the government-controlled enclave of
Gorazde, and did not give the Serbs a wider corridor linking their lands.
The summit deal was also met with silence by Bosnian Serb ``president'' Radovan
Karadzic and his army commander General Ratko Mladic.
No statement came from the pair, who led the Bosnian Serbs through
three-and-a-half years of war and have been indicted twice by the UN for war
crimes.
Hard-liners demanded a session of the Bosnian Serb republic's parliament, which
they control, to oppose the agreement negotiated in their name.
Trifko Radic, president of the war presidency of Serb Sarajevo, said: ``World
powers, and even Yugoslavia, can make different calculations for their own
interests, but more than 150,000 Serbs in Serb Sarajevo cannot accept such a
solution after so much killing and suffering.''
However the Serbs made no threat to break the ceasefire in Bosnia and at least
one senior officer, defence minister Milan Ninkovic, broke ranks to praise the
agreement.
In Belgrade, the Serbian capital, the agreement was welcomed with joyous
anticipation that the United Nations would lift economic sanctions, imposed for
Milosevic's role in fomenting the Serb rebellion against Bosnia's secession
from Yugoslavia in early 1992 that started the war.
Tonight the UN Security Council indeed voted unanimously to lift the strict
trade embargo on Belgrade, and to lift an arms ban on the rest of former
Yugoslavia for a six-month period.
Milosevic, who was portrayed as a hero by Serbian state media, said on his
return to Belgrade: ``The goal.......was peace. That goal has been successfully
reached; a just peace for all nations who live in these regions.''
In Zagreb, Croatian President Franjo Tudjman said the peace deal had
implications beyond former Yugoslavia.
``We got peace,'' Tudjman said. ``Peace for Croatia and Bosnia-Herzegovina, but
also peace for Europe, peace for the world.
UN officials noted that repatriating refugees would be difficult.
``We certainly hope that the peace will work, we would like it to work and for
people to come back,'' said Kris Janowski, spokesman for the UN High
Commissioner for Refugees.
However he urged foreign countries hosting about 700,000 refugees ``not to be
too hasty in trying to send people back''.-AP/Reuter.
q FOREIGN Secretary Malcolm Rifkind welcomed the ``historic'' Bosnian peace
agreement and urged all the warring factions to back it, writes William Russell.
Mr Rifkind pledged to MPs at Westinster that Britain would play a central role
in helping to bring about a lasting peace and announced a Peace Implementation
Conference in London on December 8 and 9, three days after the peace agreement
is signed in Paris.
He cautioned against over-optimism, saying: ``The first requirement is that the
parties live up to their commitments.
``Unless they abide by what they have agreed, and work to make that settlement
a success, the documents initialled at Dayton are just pieces of paper.''
Shadow Foreign Secretary Robin Cook also welcomed the agreement, but warned
that ``implementing the peace accord will require as much effort and patience
as getting agreement to it in the first place''.
Mr Cook offered support for any responsible plan to reinforce British troops in
the region to implement the peace plan, saying: ``The nation will now want
British troops to finish the job by helping to establish the peace.''
Some 15,000 British troops are expected to be deployed, as opposed to the 5000
at present, with a further 3000 based in support services.
</TEXT>
