<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Puma-like animal seen in Highlands</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975241280</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE occupants of two cars reported separate sightings of a puma-like animal on
the A862 between Inverness and Beauly at lunchtime yesterday.
One of the drivers, Ms Lorraine Cullen, 33, of Sunnybank Road, Culduthel,
Inverness, said: ``At first I thought it was a labrador dog, but then I
realised it was bigger and was cat-like in appearance. I think that it was a
beast like a puma, which had escaped back into the wild.''
Lottery help
THE first big lottery donation to Shetland from the National Heritage Fund has
ensured the Bressay Lighthouse buildings will stay in public hands. Shetland
Amenity Trust received 80% of the #100,000 purchase price from the fund.
Power boost
SCOTTISHPOWER is planning to build a high-voltage power electricity station at
Eccles, Berwickshire, to upgrade transmission lines between Scotland and
England.
Skills tested
LAW students will be tested on their interviewing and counselling skills when
they take part in the Scottish Client Counselling Competition on November 25 at
Dundee University. The winners will go on to the international competition in
Australia.
Ski slope plan
PLANS to build a mini ``Swiss village'' with 36 timber chalets, a dry ski slope
and sports and leisure facilities are being proposed for Dunoon. The
application for planning permission, from A.&amp;.G Cox, of Glasgow, goes before
the district council today.
New lifeboat
THE RNLI hopes to build an inshore lifeboat station and slipway at
Tighnabruaich, Argyll. Argyll and Bute District Council will consider the
application today.
Whisky theft
MORE than 1000 bottles of Johnny Walker whisky, worth #16,000, were stolen from
an articulated lorry while the driver slept in the cab at a car park in Hexham,
Northumberland.
Church repairs
TWO of Argyll's most impressive churches are to undergo essential repairs. The
Oban Free High Church is to spend #30,000 to eradicate damp and Kilfinnan
Parish Church is to spend #34,000 on repairs to its Lamont Aisle.
</TEXT>
