<DOCNO>GH951123-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Strain put on capacity at Carstairs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241281</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEALTH boards who were slow to take their patients back have left the State
Hospital at Carstairs close to being full twice this year, general manager Dick
Manson said today in his annual report.
The hospital, which has a capacity of 236, has come within half-a-dozen
patients of that, partly because of increased demand as well as the pace of
return to home health boards.
Carstairs houses and treats patients who are too dangerous to themselves or
others for mainstream psychiatry services, and Mr Manson said: ``We aim always
to have available beds to immediately admit dangerous people who need to be
here for treatment.''
Greater Glasgow is understood to be one of the boards principally involved, but
a spokesman for the Greater Glasgow Community and Mental Health Trust said
yesterday it had been taking more Carstairs patients than in previous years.
``Since 1990 we have averaged 20 a year, but since July this year we have taken
back 16. There have been occasions when we have been unable to take patients,
but this is for a number of reasons.
``One important one is that some of them have worked their way through the
system to the point where they are living in flats on the perimeter of the
state hospital to get used to independence, and our psychiatrists think it
would be a retrograde step to go from there to a locked ward at Gartnavel, for
example.''
q A schoolboy of 15 has been put in a locked psychiatric ward with adults
because there are no facilities for dealing with patients his age in Scotland.
The boy from East Kilbride was in the Adolescent Psychiatry Unit at Gartnavel
Royal Hospital in Glasgow until an incident when he brandished a knife and a
teacher had to disarm him.
Since then he has been in the secure ward at Hartwood Hospital in Lanarkshire.
Now his parents have been told he may have to be transferred to Manchester to
get appropriate treatment in the only unit of its kind in the UK.
His father said: ``He began suffering depression over the past year, missing
school and getting into trouble, and he lost his friends. Now he has been
diagnosed as suffering from psychosis.''
</TEXT>
