<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The making of a rally champion</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN HORTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241282</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COLIN McRae's first steps towards winning the biggest prize in rallying and
becoming the first Briton to win the World Rally Championship began two years
ago with a limited overseas programme, driving a Subaru Legacy.
Team manager David Richards secured the then 25-year-old McRae under contract.
The Scot began repaying the investment in his burgeoning talent with two
victories, New Zealand and Malaysia.
Last year - at the wheel of a Subaru Impreza 555 - he added the Network Q RAC
Rally and Rally Australia to his win in New Zealand. But 1994 also had its
downs. In Monte Carlo, he crashed and was relegated to tenth. Portugal ended
with a fire, and Corsica after an accident. In May's Acropolis Rally, he was
excluded after a verbal clash with officials, and he crashed out of the Rally
Argentina.
He won the final round of the series but it also created new pressures. Colin
and Derek Ringer - his co-driver of nine years' standing - were now tipped as
hot favourites to win the 1995 championship.
In January's opening round in Monte Carlo McRae crashed out on an icy corner.
In the snowy forests of Sweden he retired with engine failure. After two of the
eight rounds he didn't have a single point. He managed third place in Portugal
and, after fifth in Corsica, New Zealand again was the watershed. His
domination was total.
After the Asia-Pacific, it was in September's Rally Australia that a new,
mature McRae emerged. Lying first equal with Kenneth Eriksson's Mitsubishi, he
let the Swede take victory and settled for championship points.
The seventh round was in Spain - home ground for Carlos Sainz, a rival for the
title.
Starting the final day, he was second to Sainz but team orders dictated they
should hold their positions. It was only after much persuasion by Richards and
Colin's father, Jimmy, that McRae reluctantly booked in late at the final
control, letting Sainz win.
The scene was now set for an emotional and public showdown on McRae's home
event. Fairly and squarely the better man won.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000060</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000060</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Peace is worth a risk, says Bruton</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241283</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IRISH Prime Minister John Bruton last night criticised Northern Ireland
Secretary Sir Patrick Mayhew for displaying ``immutability'' in a speech on the
peace process.
Mr Bruton, currently caught up in negotiations with Mr John Major aimed at
resolving the impasse, also said that risks had to be taken to overcome the
current problems.
His comments came after Sir Patrick repeated Britain's demands for IRA moves
towards decommissioning their weapons ahead of Sinn Fein's entry into all-party
talks on the future of Northern Ireland.
Mr Bruton said: ``If we are going to move forward, we must recognise the need
for compromise. You cannot lay down a set, immutable position - as I feel Sir
Patrick was laying down today - and expect there are going to be compromises.
``There must be mutability, not immutability, in this area.''
His remarks were seen as a signal of the Dublin Government's concern over the
address delivered by Sir Patrick in Londonderry.
The tone of the Secretary of State's remarks were regarded by some sources
close to the Irish Government as unhelpful in the present climate.
Mr Bruton also emphasised last night that the so-called twin-track approach
evolved with Mr Major earlier this year had to deal with the arms and all-party
talks issue if it was to succeed. ``Otherwise it is a waste of time,'' he said.
Sir Patrick said yesterday in Londonderry that the paramilitaries had to
provide the confidence necessary to prove that they were committed to democracy.
But they could not expect to ``keep a foot in both camps, to sign up as it were
to `democracy a la carte'.''
He emphasised the need for progress on decommissioning, and insisted that it
did not amount to a demand for ``surrender of the IRA or even IRA weapons''.
The Government had an open mind about how actual decommissioning should happen
in practice.
US President Bill Clinton's is due to visit to Britain and Ireland at the end
of next week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Leniency for school attacker</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241284</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORMER pupil who assaulted a boy at a Glasgow school where racial tension had
led to violent clashes was given a chance by a sheriff yesterday.
Mohammed Ashraf, 17, of Giffnock, was found guilty at Paisley Sheriff Court of
assaulting the 14-year-old pupil during a playground incident at Woodfarm High
School in Robslee Road, Thornliebank, in March.
Sheriff James Spy said he accepted there was a background to the incident and
deferred sentence for six months.
Ashraf had denied the charge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Students provide stern test</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241285</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW Under-21s, who open their district campaign against South next
Wednesday, just edged a testing match at Braidholm last night.
The students led 11-6 at half-time through a try by full back Richard Bailes
and two penalties by Dundee centre Neil Paterson against two penalties by
Martin Hose.
Two tries by winger Geoff Caldwell and a conversion and penalty by Hose put
Glasgow into the lead but two penalties by Paterson and a drop goal by
Edinburgh centre James How almost produced victory for the students.
Glasgow Under-21 - T Greenshields (West of Scotland); G Caldwell (GHK), A
Bulloch (West of Scotland), C Sangster (Stirling County), J Craig (West of
Scotland); M Hose (Edinburgh Academicals), J Weston (Watsonians); D Porte
(Glasgow Academicals), G Bulloch, captain, D Jamieson, G Perrett (all West of
Scotland), S Begley (Glasgow Academicals), D McLeish (West of Scotland), C
Houston (Glasgow Southern), R Wylie (Stirling County).
Scottish Universities - R Bailes (Edinburgh); N Hannah (Aberdeen), J Davidson
(Dundee), J How (Edinburgh), J Cadell (Aberdeen); N Paterson (Dundee), H
Williams; W Mulhall (both Edinburgh), S Forsyth (Aberdeen), T Cohn, A Lucking,
J Hart, R Henley (all Edinburgh), S Byrne (Heriot-Watt), C Roe (Dundee).
Referee - J Platt (Hillhead/Jordanhill).
q WALES stand-off Neil Jenkins kicked Pontypridd to a comfortable win by 31-12
over Milan with his 26 points in perhaps the worst Heineken European Clubs'
Championship match so far.
He landed eight penalties and converted the only try - from David Manley - as
negative play from both sides ruined the Pool C game. Milan had flanker Massimo
Giovanelli sent off for butting in 67 minutes, after he had been warned in the
first half.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MI5 agents tell of following loyalists</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241286</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MI5 ``watchers'' targeted two men codenamed Speaker's Choice and Bad News in a
Scottish pub, the High Court in Glasgow was told yesterday.
The surveillance operation, which spanned four days, started in Tam Bain's, a
pub in Mary Street, Laurieston, Falkirk, and continued with security service
agents shadowing a Renault estate car as it headed south.
They were even watching as one of the occupants of the car was sick near the
front entrance of a motorway service area on the M6. The watching brief ended
outside another pub, this time in Liverpool.
Yesterday, three of the MI5 ``watchers'', their names given in court as Mr C,
Ms D, and Mr G, gave evidence behind a screen so that their identities could be
protected.
It is the first time that MI5 officers have given evidence in a Scottish court,
and only the second time that witnesses have been screened from the public for
security reasons.
On trial are six men - three Scots from Laurieston, Bonnybridge, and Airdrie, a
Liverpudlian, and two men from Northern Ireland.
They are Mr John Johnston, 49, of Campbell Crescent, Laurieston, Mr Francis
Hives, 45, of Liverpool, Mr William McArthur, 41, of Ure Crescent, Bonnybridge,
Mr David White, 29, of Northburn Avenue, Airdrie, Mr Alexander Davidson, 23,
and Mr Lindsay Robb, 28, of Lurgan, Northern Ireland.
Mr Robb was one of the loyalist team involved in peace talks with the
Government at Stormont earlier this year.
All six deny conspiring in their homes and in pubs to further the cause of the
Ulster Volunteer Force by acquiring firearms, ammunition, and explosive
substances intending to endanger life in the UK and Republic of Ireland.
Part of the conspiracy alleges drug trafficking to raise money for use in
connection with terrorism.
The court was told that Mr Johnston was identified by the MI5 watchers as
Speaker's Choice, and Mr McArthur as Bad News.
It was claimed they were joined by Mr White for the journey in Mr McArthur's
taxi to the Market pub in Liverpool.
The agents told Mr Ian Bonomy, QC, prosecuting, how they watched comings and
goings at Tam Bain's, beginning on July 19.
Mr C claimed that one of the men in the pub resembled Mr Robb, and he told how
Bad News - Mr McArthur - possibly identified him, because he was very alert.
Earlier, the court was told of a police search of Mr Johnstone's home, during
which a handgun was found.
The trial before Lord Sutherland is expected to last one month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Oban underdogs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241287</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KYLES Athletic, who declined to take part in this season's national premier
league, face their stiffest test to date when they re-enter mainstream
competition in the Bank of Scotland Celtic Society Cup.
Kyles lead the new South first division by six points and are unbeaten in
league games. They face Oban Camanachd, last season's South champions, who
languish just above the foot of the premier division and have yet to show any
of the form which took them to within an ace of causing a major upset in last
year's Camanachd Cup final.
Camanachd will go to Kyles as underdogs. They are weakened by the continuing
absence of Dougie MacIntyre and Dave McUish, who could be out for six weeks
with a broken hand. But they have Alex MacVicar back after a five-game ban,
although it is not clear where he will play, the defence having played
reasonably well in his absence.
Kyles are likely to persist with the ploy of playing the vastly experienced
Andy Irvine up front.
In the north, Kingussie should comfortably defeat Skye in the MacTavish Cup and
premier side Newtonmore should beat Caberfeidh at home.
The Camanachd Association say they are willing to meet Lochaber District
councillors about their proposals for the upgrading of An Aird Park in Fort
William. Council officials have gone to great lengths to explain that their
plans for national status for the field do not involve a monopoly of major
finals, as had been suggested. Association president Duncan Cameron has
welcomed this clarification.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Personal service is factor in success</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sheila Waddell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241288</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sheila Waddell meets the men behind a successful management buyout
GAELIC Factors is moving towards its twentieth year as a new independent
company. Formerly part of James Finlay, the Glasgow-based tea traders, the
company was recently bought out by its existing management for #1.25m.
James Finlay had previously announced the intention to sell-off the company's
financial interests in order to concentrate on core tea-growing and
confectionery businesses, and the management team of Gaelic Factors seized the
opportunity to buy-out the company.
Managing director David Russell, who set up the company in 1976, explained:
``James Finlay were keen to divest themselves of their interests on the
financial side, and we felt this was an excellent business to purchase. This
also enabled us to maintain our independence from other larger factors or
banks, as well as protecting the jobs of our 30 staff, jobs which were not
guaranteed had the business been sold to another party.
``During the buy-out we were advised by the corporate division of Touche Ross,
who introduced us to several financial institutions and eventually found us a
highly satisfactory package from the Bank of Scotland, who were the company's
first bankers in 1976. The package from the Bank of Scotland means that all the
company's banking will now be carried out at 110 Queen Street, where the
company has enjoyed a tremendous relationship over the years. The legal work
for the buy-out was handled by Semple Fraser.''
Gaelic Factors is basically a finance company which assists in financing the
cashflow of small to medium-sized companies by providing a facility against
their debtors. Rather than waiting for money to come in from invoices - a
process which takes on average 72 days - companies send their invoices to
Gaelic Factors who advance 75% of the payment within 24 hours of the invoices
being sent in. Gaelic takes the legal assignation over these invoices, and the
customers of the company pay them. Gaelic then remit the further 25% to
clients, minus their charges, when they have collected the total amount due.
Charges vary according to the industry a company is operating in, the size of
the company and its turnover, as well as the length of time clients take to
pay.
Gaelic Factors charge on a weekly basis, and, relating costs to turnover, they
expect the total cost to be in the region of 1!s%-45/8, with their interest
charges varying in line with those of the base rate of high street banks.
Finance Director John Doyle pointed out the tremendous growth potential of the
business. ``According to the Bank of England, only 10% of companies who could
benefit from factoring currently use the system, so there is an enormous
potential for growth. It is now being recommended by Government bodies like the
Department of Trade and Industry, because it is sometimes difficult for
companies without the necessary security to obtain loans from a bank or even
overdraft facilities.
``The CBI is also encouraging its members to use factoring services as a tool
to expand their businesses and ensure a smooth cashflow.''
Director James Cameron said: ``We have a wide range of clients in industries as
diverse and printing, engineering, food processing, security, contract cleaning
and grass cutting. Many of these businesses are labour intensive, and therefore
benefit from a smooth cashflow to ensure prompt payments of wages and
suppliers.''
The company prides itself on giving a very personal service. David Russell
emphasised: ``Because of our size we are able to offer a more personal service
than the major players. We have clients throughout the UK, including a large
number recommended by chartered accountants in London. Because of our personal
service we can relate to our clients and understand their needs.''
The company has around 150 clients, the bulk of them small to medium sized
companies. The average company they assist has a turnover of
three-quarters-of-a-million pounds.
The target market is any company with a turnover of between #150,000 and #5m
although, strictly speaking, there is no upper limit.
The benefits of the fast, efficient service Gaelic Factors offer are obvious.
For example, security companies employing factory guards find they can send
their invoices in the morning. If they arrive before 11 o'clock a cheque is
written and ready for that afternoon to pay the guards' wages.
Since 1976, annual turnover has risen from #750,000 to #85m and David Russell
and his fellow directors aim to continue the steady growth of the company,
without losing its service ethic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Business benefits  for working clients</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sheila Waddell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241289</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GAELIC Factors, which operates from Finlay House at 10-14 West Nile Street, was
originally set up by David Russell in 1976.
Within a year it became part of the James Finlay Group, a move that helped
raise its profile, lengthen its reach and allow it to take advantage of
opportunities in a growing market.
The management buy-out completed last month will enable the company to maintain
its independence and its position as the only factor with a head office in
Scotland.
The company is headed by managing director David Russell, 53, an accountant and
company secretary in the printing industry before he became managing director
of City and County House Purchase Company in 1969. When this was bought over in
1975 he established Gaelic Factors.
In 1978 the senior management team was strengthened when James Cameron, 58, a
banker with 20 years experience in the finance industry, joined the company as
general manager. James, who had previously worked with David Russell at City
and County House Purchase, is responsible for the day to day operations of the
business.
The third member of the Management Buy Out team is John Doyle, 43. Formerly a
chartered accountant with Dallas Nicol and Company in Paisley, who were
Gaelic's auditors, John joined the company in 1985 as finance director.
The company also has four managers: sales manager Robin Russell, general
manager Jean Tunmore, senior credit manager Scott Melville and office manager
Jim Walker.
Gaelic Factors places a heavy emphasise on personal service and does not employ
salesmen. Normally inquiries are handled at sales manager or director level.
Because they are dealing with principals of the company, clients receive a
quick decision, certainly within 48 hours compared to the industry norm of
several weeks. This personal contact continues with customers after they are on
the books, as the three directors are available to help with any problems.
With factoring, a regular weekly cashflow is generated, relieving clients from
the worry of temporary difficulties over the payment of wages and accounts.
Through factoring, raw materials may be bought in bulk or at keener discounts
through early settlement. Savings can also be made in labour costs, while
business profitability should improve through savings on bank interest.
Unlike a bank overdraft, there is no limit to the amount of cash available on a
client's account. The only limit to factoring as a source of finance is the
client's own ability to manufacture and sell its goods and services. Gaelic
Factors are members of the Association of Invoice Factors and have credit
facilities from the Bank of Scotland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
