<DOCNO>GH951123-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Meyer earnings take knock</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241293</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TUMBLING softwood prices knocked profits of timber importer and builders'
merchant Meyer International back 27% to #20.1m for the six months to September.
The group does not expect its second half to be as bad, helped by its recent
purchase of branches from Wickes which made the group one of the largest
builders' merchants in Scotland. But full-year profits are still seen falling
below 1994-95's #51.6m. The interim dividend is pegged at 4.2p.
Meyer paid #2m for 21 Builders' Mate branches from Wickes when the latter
decided to pull out of this business. Ten are in Scotland, doubling the number
of Meyer outlets here. The whole chain is being revamped to improve
performance. The group has 210 outlets and is keen to add another 100.
Not much improvement in market conditions is seen for another year yet, though
demand should stabilise earlier. Despite a volume decline of 7%, Jewson held
trading profits at #13.6m in the first half.
The timber importing business saw profits tumble 41% to #5.7m and the similar
Dutch operation was down 43% at #4.4m. There was a glut of timber on the market
as a result of the cyclical upsurge in pulp prices which encouraged a higher
timber cut.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jones on top of the world</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241294</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOXING
PAUL `Silky' Jones climbed up from a first-round knock-down to claim the World
Boxing Organisation light-middleweight title in Sheffield last night.
Jones beat the holder from New York, Verno Phillips, on a split decision to
complete a tremendous boxing comeback.
British judge Roy Francis made him a clear winner by 116 points to 111, while
the Puerto Rican officials, Nelson Vusquez and Cesar Ramos, had it 113-113 and
114-113 - and that after the challenger had a point deducted for a head-butt in
the ninth round.
Jones pulled away from Phillips in the last four rounds as the champion visibly
tired. His early work often lacked conviction, but there was little doubting he
was the master overall.
He constantly switched from an orthodox stance to southpaw to confuse Phillips
- and overall the tactic paid off.
q STEVE Collins, who puts his WBO super-middleweight title on the line against
Cornelius Carr in Dublin on Saturday, last night refused point-blank to defend
against Ray Close.
Close drew then lost against former champion Chris Eubank, but was denied a
third clash when he failed a brain scan.
He went on to pass subsequent examinations in Ireland and America, but Collins
is not convinced. ``I'm not prepared to accept responsibility for Ray's
health,'' said Collins.
``Ray is a friend of mine and I have no intention of doing anything that might
jeopardise his health.''
q MIKE Tyson's postponed clash with Buster Mathis Jr will take place in
Atlantic City on December 16. The fight was scheduled for November 4, but was
postponed when Tyson damaged his right thumb.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forte is vulnerable</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241295</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEHIND the statement from Forte that shareholders should take no action because
the offer totally fails to recognise the group's value, perhaps there is a
secret feeling of relief from Sir Rocco. Certainly he will have to battle very
hard to persuade a sceptical City that the hotels and catering group should
remain independent.
Broker reaction was initially one of surprise but the later view was that Forte
had been asking for it - admittedly sentiment has been swayed by the cogency of
the Granada arguments on hotel branding. There Forte appears to have simply too
many names on the roadside and has positioned Travelodge too closely to Post
House.
Moreover, Whitbread is moving up fast to take market leadership with its Travel
Inns. But these are arguments that will be rehearsed time and time again over
the next several weeks including the unassailable fact that the Forte purchase
of the Meridien chain of luxury hotels is the best thing it has done for many a
year.
Granada said it will raise #500m through the disposal of peripheral assets such
as Lillywhites, Alpha Airports, and the Savoy. That will bring great
unhappiness to the Forte family given that so much blood, sweat and tears have
been shed in acquiring the 68% equity holding over the years.
But there are several honeypots of surplus hotel assets, particularly in London
where the value of properties like the Grosvenor House on Park Lane run into
many hundreds of millions of pounds.
These could be sold and leased back to create an immediate substantial cash sum
and provide a valuable tool in reducing the apparently horrendous gearing of
130% postulated for September next year after the assumption of Forte's #1300m
debt.
As far as the City is concerned, Gerry Robinson seems to walk on water but he
cannot afford to make a slip. However, while this offer may be an initial one,
it will not have to be increased that much to ensure success.
Better way
THE Chancellor of the Exchequer is thought to have enough scope to cut the
basic rate of income tax by 1p to 24p in Tuesday's Budget. Kenneth Clarke
himself fuelled the speculation yesterday by reiterating the Government's
long-term aim of reducing basic rate tax to 20p.
On its Budget race card, chartered accountancy firm Coopers and Lybrand quotes
a 1p reduction in the basic rate as the 1/2 favourite. According to
stockbrokers at UBS, the cost would be #1600m next year and #2000m in 1997-8.
Another route to a 20p basic tax rate would be to increase the band covered by
the 20p lower rate, which currently applies to the first #3200 of taxable
income. Raising this by #2000 to #5200 would cost in the region of #2000m.
So far Mr Clarke has not displayed the same enthusiasm for the lower rate band
as his predecessor Norman Lamont who introduced it in 1992.
A James Capel poll of 1035 individuals who voted Conservative at the last
election shows that only 13% favoured cutting the basic rate, against 19% who
would prefer increases in personal allowances and 37% who supported a reduction
in the 17.5% VAT rate.
The bulk of the extra tax raised from the personal sector in the last three
years has been achieved by not indexing tax allowances against inflation and by
reducing the value of the married couples allowance and mortgage interest
relief.
To those on lower incomes the point at which they start to pay tax is of much
greater significance than the rate at which it is levied. The same is also true
of the Conservative Party's natural constituency among the better off middle
income groups.
It is estimated that since 1989 the number of higher rate taxpayers has
increased by 700,000 to 2,200,000. The higher rate threshold was frozen in the
three years to 1994-5.
For a cost of #2650m the Chancellor could increase all personal and married
couples allowances, the lower rate band, and the higher rate threshold by 10%
above the rate of inflation.
Indexation of allowances and thresholds at September's 3.9% inflation rate is
due. So the overall effect would be to increase the personal allowance by #490
to #4015, the lower rate band by #445 to #3645, and the higher rate threshold
by #3375 to #27,675.
Such a use of the money Mr Clarke has at his disposal would be much more
equitable than a token cut in the basic rate. It might also turn out to be
politically astute.
Cadbury II
A SUCCESSOR body to the Cadbury Committee on Corporate Governance has at last
been formed and fortunately a heavyweight chairman has been found in Sir Ronnie
Hampel, chairman of ICI. He will be supported by other leading business figures
like Sir David Simon of BP and Chris Haskins of Northern Foods.
There had appeared to be some reluctance on the part of top businessmen to take
part in Cadbury II, as it will be known, and it was important that it contained
top business people to have full credibility.
The row in the summer over executive share options involving Sir Richard
Greenbury is thought to have put people off.
Business grudgingly went along with the Cadbury proposals but has baulked at
some of the Greenbury decisions, such as much greater disclosure of
remuneration and performance criteria. However, if public cynicism about big
business is to be checked it is vital that the proposals are implemented and
the Cadbury II members should have the clout to attack any backsliding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
