<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Coach Capello thinking about a new Italian job</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241297</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AC MILAN coach Fabio Capello is thinking of switching clubs next year after
five seasons that made the Italian side the leading lights in Europe.
Capello claims that he has been offered a two-year extension by Milan, the
Serie A leaders, but was unhappy with certain clauses. He said he had until
April 30 to make up his mind.
``By then it will be too late to choose,'' he said. ``I could find a club
before then and not accept the offer from Milan of a contract without (those)
clauses.'' He would not elaborate on the contract tussle.
Capello was talking as speculation mounted that the club was hunting for a
replacement and had several candidates in mind, including Italy manager Arrigo
Sacchi, who moved to the national side from Milan.
Capello dismissed the speculation but added that he felt Milan had not backed
him fully this season. And he said he felt he should have quit after Milan
overwhelmed Barcelona 4-0 in the European Champions' Cup final in Athens in
May, 1994.
``It was really a magic moment. We'd reached the top, so high you couldn't go
higher. Yes, that was perhaps the right moment. There was no lack of offers,''
he said.
q COLOMBIAN defender Albeiro Pico Hernandez, of Club Envigado, was shot dead by
unidentified gumen yesterday in the northwest city of Medellin.
The gunmen is said to have shot seven rounds into 23-year-old Pico as he was
leaving his home for an early-morning training session.
The player had been playing with Club Envigado since 1988. Police said they had
no immediate clues as to the reasons for the killing of the footballer or who
might be behind it.
Medellin has Colombia's highest murder rate. Defender Andres Escobar was gunned
down in the city in 1994, not long after having scored an own goal in a World
Cup finals match against the USA that Colombia lost 2-1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>CBS deal approved</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241298</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Wednesday - The Federal Communications Commission today unanimously
approved Westinghouse Electric Corporation's $5400m acquisition of CBS,
enabling the deal to go through.
The transaction, approved in a 5-0 vote, had been delayed by the federal
Government shutdown and by an internal squabble among the agency's
commissioners over Westinghouse's pledge to air three hours a week of
educational television for children.
FCC chairman Reed Hundt wanted to link the commission's approval of the
acquisition to Westinghouse's pledge. But three other commissioners rejected
such an approach.
In the end, the commission acknowledged Westinghouse's pledge on children's
television but said approval of the deal was not conditioned on implementing
the plan. Each day of delay has added $850,000 to the price tag Westinghouse
must pay for CBS, under terms of the buyout agreement. - Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Strand opens up the door</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241299</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHAMPIONS' LEAGUE
ROUND-UP
ROSENBORG gave their chances of reaching the quarter-final stage a considerable
boost when they defeated Legia Warsaw 4-0 in Trondheim to move to within one
point of the Poles in Group B.
Roar Strand opened the scoring after 17 minutes and just before half-time,
Harald Brattbakk added the second. Then Jahn Ivar Jakobsen put Rosenborg three
up before Vegard Heggem completed the scoring in the last minute. Now Rosenborg
have a great chance of joining Spartak in the next round.
In Spain, a goal from Jari Litmanen after 20 minutes gave Ajax the lead against
Real Madrid in Group D. The Dutch side, many people's choice as favourites to
take the European title, added a second through Patrick Kluivert after 75
minutes, and this victory means that they cannot be caught at the top of the
section.
Bobby Robson's Porto really needed a victory against Nantes to put real
pressure on the French champions in Group A. And the night did not start too
well for the Portuguese side when Reynald Pedros opened the scoring after just
three minutes for Nantes. However, the lead did not last too long for Ljubimko
Drulovic equalised for Porto after 11 minutes.
Halfway through the half, Nantes regained the advantage when Pedros scored his
second but Porto's Jose Carlos equalised after 56 minutes to earn his side a
point.
In the same group, Alexis Alexoudis scored in the first minute to give
Panathinaikos the lead over Denmark's Aalborg in Athens, a second goal coming
after 38 minutes through George Georgiadis, and that is how the tie finished.
</TEXT>
