<HEADLINE>Greeks' victory lands place</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241300</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHAMPION'S LEAGUE
ROUND-UP
GREEK champions Panathinaikos clinched their place in the last eight with a 2-0
win over Aalborg, with goals from Alexis Alexoudis and George Georgiadis,
joining Spartak Moscow, Juventus, Ajax, and Dortmund in the quarter-final stage.
With only one round of the six Champions' League matches to play, Panathinaikos
cannot be caught in Group A, with either Nantes or Porto, who drew 2-2 in
Portugal last night, now joining them.
Nantes play Panathinaikos in their last match on December 6, while Aalborg host
Porto.
``It is a great night for Greek football,'' Panathinaikos' Argentine coach Juan
Ramon Rocha said. ``We now have our last match in France and we will try to
keep the first spot in the group.''
Panathinaikos are the only Greek club to reach the European Cup final,
achieving the feat in 1971 when they played Ajax in London, losing 2-0 at
Wembley.
Last night Porto wasted their best chance when striker Domingos Oliveira missed
a penalty in 75 minutes. ``The game was there to be won,'' said Porto manager
Bobby Robson. ``It was a wonderful opportunity for us,'' referring to the
penalty. ``But I never criticise players who miss penalties.''
Nantes keeper Casagrande guaranteed the draw when he made a spectacular save
from a shot by Hungarian midfielder Peter Lipcsei in injury time.
In Group B, Spartak Moscow were through even before outclassing Blackburn
Rovers and they will be joined by either Rosenborg, who thumped Legia Warsaw
4-0 in Norway, or the Polish champions.
Legia face Spartak in their last match with Blackburn at home to Rosenborg. If
Rosenborg draw with Blackburn and Spartak beat Legia, the Norwegians will
qualify - despite having lost three of their matches to date.
Defending champions Ajax's 2-0 win over Real Madrid in Spain and Ferencvaros's
3-3 draw with Grasshoppers Zurich in Budapest means either Real or Ferencvaros
will join Ajax in the last eight from Group D.
Ajax, who meet Brazil's Gremio in the Intercontinental Cup in Tokyo on Tuesday,
could have settled the issue in the first 20 minutes when their fast-flowing,
one-touch football left Real floundering.
Marc Overmars, Jari Litmanen, and Patrick Kluivert all had well-struck shots
come crashing back off the crossbar, while Kluivert hit a weak shot straight at
Buyo.
However, Ajax won the match with goals from the Finn, Jari Litmanen, and
Patrick Kluivert, anbd their last game is against Ferencvaros, while Real
travel to Zurich.
</TEXT>
