<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>CHEMICALS Courtaulds optimistic despite lower earnings</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241301</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FALLING raw material prices should benefit chemicals group Courtaulds but they
came too late for the interim results which showed a 16% decline in profits to
#68m before tax.
However, the trading performance was not as bad as some industry watchers had
expected and with the company still optimistic about its long-term prospects
the shares jumped 39p to 399p.
The problem areas were the acrylic and viscose fibre businesses. Profits in
fibres and chemicals were down 38% on the previous year, although sales grew by
12%.
It proved difficult to pass on higher costs to customers. What higher selling
prices there were had an adverse effect on demand. The UK market was notably
difficult.
Courtaulds said quarterly contracts prevented it from taking immediate
advantage of sharply-falling acrylonitrile prices, which had soared since the
summer of 1994.
It will not feel the benefit of these lower prices until next spring. However,
there are encouraging signs that other raw material prices may also be on the
way down.
The company said that pulp prices had peaked although they have yet to fall.
However, it emphasised that lower raw material prices do not necessarily feed
through into higher profits because customers postpone orders until they feel
that prices have reached the bottom.
Some parts of the fibre business did well with Tencel sales volumes moving
ahead strongly. A second manufacturing plant is due to open shortly to meet
increased demand. There was also a positive performance in the rest of the
group with profits from Coatings &amp; Sealants up 14% and those in Polymer
Products jumped 33%.
Coatings sales volumes in the Far East rose by more than 15% and the
profitability of the European operations benefited from earlier
rationalisation.
