<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ministerial sell-off means end to free speech</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IIan Bell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975241302</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THEY said it couldn't be done. They said no-one would dare. But they had
reckoned without Her Majesty's Government. At last: the privatisation of John
Selwyn Gummer.
Or so we must believe, given an invitation from the press section of the
British Embassy in Brussels, no less, informing the recipient that he would
shortly receive notification of a Royal Institute of International Relations
lunch at the local Hilton.
There our Environment Minister (or ``drittsek'' to give him the title EU
protocol demands) would deliver a speech on, of all things, environmental
policy, followed by a press conference on same.
Given the laws of supply and demand, the conference would of course be free. As
for the lunch, however, only a bank transfer of 1500 Belgian francs ``will
secure your place''.
Or to put it in layman's terms: one absolutely unforgettable John Gummer speech
delivered as part of the ministerial duties for which we pay him well? That
will be #34, please.
Half-cocked Robin
``SEND your Christmas post off to a great start,'' says the advertising copy,
``with Royal Mail's new festive stamps featuring Britain's best-loved bird -
the robin - a traditional symbol of the season.'' It adds: ``So why not post
your Christmas cards early and allow your family and friends to enjoy them
longer?''
Why not indeed? Presentation packs of these lovely stamps are available,
apparently, from the British Philatelic Bureau, 20 Brandon Street, Edinburgh -
where 600 post boxes have just been sealed because of a strike by distinctly
unfestive postmen.
Breeding violence
NOT WEIRD, just American. Last month 21-year-old Jeremy Brown was arrested in
Dover, New Hampshire, for beating up his girlfriend in a dispute over whether
the O J Simpson jury had reached the proper verdict.
Fast mover
A SPLENDID example of consensus politics is being set in the Borders, where
Councillor Jim Nairn, elected as an independent to represent Gordon and
Greenlaw, has just switched to the Liberal Democrats.
Two years ago Mr Nairn defected from the Tories after being elected to
Berwickshire District Council as a Conservative candidate. Last year he won the
West Berwickshire seat on Borders Regional Council as an independent, and this
year was elected to the new Scottish Borders Council as an indie before
deciding recently that, on the whole, he'd rather be a Lib-Dem.
This is not as surprising as it might sound, since before moving to
Berwickshire and joining the Tories Mr Nairn was (but you guessed) a staunch
Liberal. The local Lib-Dems are, in any case, delighted, stating: ``Jim Nairn
has the potential to be a good Liberal Democrat as he has a lot of experience
which we will take full advantage of.''
Somehow you just bet they will.
Taking stock
THE TORIES have been keeping busy meanwhile, attempting, after only 16 years in
power, to discover what people really think. Thus Ian Lang has sent out no
fewer than 10,000 questionnaires to his constituents in Galloway, at a cost
estimated by his agent at #5000, to ``measure public opinion'' on a variety of
issues.
Funnily enough, Michael Forsyth, with a majority even punier than that of his
Scottish Office predecessor, has also been bombarding voters in Stirling with
forms for the filling in of. There seems to be an awful lot that these vastly
experienced politicians don't know.
Still, all this might be regarded as open government, or an example of local
MPs taking a deep interest in the views and wishes of their constituents, were
it not for the admission by Lang's agent that ``all the information is fed into
computers at Central Office''.
Thus, for the first time, Tory headquarters in London's Smith Square will have
scientific proof of the existence of Scotland.
Name-dropping
IT OCCURS to us, though, that among the questions Galloway voters might ask of
Ian Lang is how anyone can mislay around a million pounds. The trouble is the
MP himself doesn't seem to have an answer.
Thus the president of the Board of Trade, a member ``name'' of the hapless Rose
Thompson Young syndicate (1092 members; #428m down the plug-hole), has joined a
High Court action claiming that Lloyds of London was negligent in its
underwriting procedures.
One small snag: Mr Lang runs the Department of Trade and Industry; the DTI
regulates Lloyds; and the president is suing that institution for big numbers.
Not to worry: earlier this year Lang delegated responsibility for the insurance
market to a junior minister, Anthony Nelson.
That's all right, then. After all, we couldn't have anyone suggesting that
outside commitments were preventing the president from carrying out a fairly
crucial part of his job.
Cudgel thy brains
BULLETIN, Edinburgh University's newsletter, is running a competition for which
the prize is a pair of tickets for any night in the final week of the Royal
Lyceum's production of Hamlet (``by William Shakespeare'', it says here).
It's one of those fill-in-the-missing-word jobs, and a real toughie.
Thus: ``Alas poor Yorick, I knew him . . ?''
Should Edinburgh's esteemed department of English literature fail to win we
will, of course, draw our own conclusions. Next: ``The capital of Scotland is .
. ?''
n AND WHILE we're at it, a little quiz of our own for the arts department of an
Edinburgh morning newspaper. Is ``Fraser Hood'' a) a terribly well-known actor
who will star in the BBC's forthcoming series Bad Boys; or b) just the name of
a character played by said terribly well-known actor whom you interviewed at
length yesterday in the clear belief that he is actually called ``Fraser
Hood''?
Prizes for the real name, when you find it, will be small and deeply
patronising.
Thought for
the week
``HEREDITARY succession is a burlesque upon monarchy. It puts it in the most
ridiculous light, by presenting it as an office which any child or idiot may
fill. It requires some talents to be a common mechanic; but, to be a king,
requires only the animal figure of man - a sort of breathing automaton. This
sort of superstition may last a few years more, but it cannot long resist the
awakened reason and interest of man'' - Thomas Paine, 1792.
Yes, as recently as that.
IAN BELL
</TEXT>
