<HEADLINE>Dow pushes further into record ground</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241303</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
New York, Wednesday - The Dow Jones industrial average pushed further into
record territory today, one day after closing for the first time above the
5000-point level, as investors bet that an interest-rate cut was on the horizon.
The Dow ended with a gain of 18.06 points at 5041.61, eclipsing the record
close of 5023.55 set yesterday.
In the broader market, advancing issues led declines by a small margin on
active volume of 408 million shares.
The broader market was flat ahead of the Thanksgiving Day holiday.
``There's confidence on the Street that 5000 was a speed bump to higher
numbers,'' said Charlie Crane, a director of research at Spears, Benzak,
Salomon &amp; Farrell. ``People are looking through the current economic
sluggishness.''
US stock markets will be closed tomorrow for the holiday and will shut early on
Friday.
Meanwhile, the Morgan Stanley cyclical index jumped six points, or 1.85% to 343.
``Stocks with a cyclical flavor are having a good day,'' Mr Crane said.
``Investors are envisioning the next Fed easing and looking into 1996 and
seeing a sluggish economy with no sign of inflation on the horizon and
anticipating the next acceleration.''
Christine Callies, a technical analyst at Brown Brothers Harriman, said the
``rally was only in the Dow components. It is probably the narrowest rally the
market has had all year.
</TEXT>
