<HEADLINE>EU expansion could pose difficulties for Scotland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Charlie Woods, chief executive of Scotland Europa,</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241304</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE expansion of the European Union to include the former Communist states of
Eastern and Central Europe could have important implications for the future
plans of many businesses in Scotland.
While there is widespread support in principle within existing EU member states
for expansion, the timing and nature of what will happen is very uncertain.
The countries which have so far made a formal application to join the EU or
have expressed a very serious interest in joining are Bulgaria, Poland,
Hungary, Romania, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Estonia, Lithuania, Latvia, and
Slovenia. In large part the timing of their entry will be determined by their
economic, adminstrative, and political readiness.
Together these countries would add more than 100 million people to the EU (an
increase of around 25%), yet their income per head is currently only 25% to 45%
of the EU average. Their growth rates over the next few years are at best only
likely to be a little above those in Western Europe, so it will take them a
long time to catch up with the west.
Their unemployment levels vary but many have rates above the European average.
Most have at least 10% of their workforce dependent on agriculture - compared
to an EU average of 6% - and some, like Poland with around 30% in agriculture,
have an employment structure that is far from that of the more modern European
economies.
Annual inflation rates vary between 10% in the Czech Republic to more than 130%
in Romania (the average rate in 1994 was 45%).
By comparison, the two poorest members of the EU as it currently stands have a
combined population of 20 million, income per head of around half of the EU
average, below average unemployment, around 20% of their workforce in
argriculture, and inflation averaging 6%.
In 1994, the EU had a trade surplus of #5000m with the countries of Eastern and
Central Europe, with exports of #32bn and imports of #27bn. Trade between the
EU and Eastern and Central Europe grew by around a quarter between 1993 and
1994. Germany was by far the dominant partner with over half the imports and
almost half the exports. UK exports were #1800m (5.5%) against imports of
#1900m (6.8%).
The prospects of countries like the Czech Republic and Slovenia being ready to
join the EU in the relatively near future are much stronger than other
countries in the region. There seems to be little point in delaying the
membership of those that are ready while others try to catch up.
Closer links to the EU and eventual membership are a vital part of any
effective economic development strategy for Central and Eastern European
countries. If their economies don't develop strongly their citizens could
quickly become disillusioned with economic and political reforms; this could
result in a return to less enlightened governments and a much greater degree of
insecurity on the EU's borders.
As well as the security problems posed, such an outcome would also represent a
wasted opportunity to build on the economic potential of these countries, not
least as thriving markets for Western European products and services.
The EU, therefore, has a strong self-interest in supporting the development of
these countries.
As well as the Central and Eastern European countries being ready to join the
EU, the Union also needs to be ready to accept them. One of the hurdles to
expansion, which will be on the agenda of the Inter Governmental Conference of
EU members next year, is reforming the Union's decision-making processes to
handle more members. As well as revamping the decision-making procedure the EU
faces other problems.
The economic condition of the countries of Central and Eastern Europe would
result in all of them being major recipients of the EU budget. According to a
recent report from the Commission, the EU budget would have to rise by 38bn Ecu
a year - an increase of around 50% - to accommodate the new members if there
were no change in current policies.
Despite the political attractions of expansion eastwards to net contributors to
the EU budget like Germany, it is hard to see them being willing to foot such a
bill. So an overhaul of the agricultural and structural policies of the Union
will be needed.
A transition phase where new entrants agree to stay outside the full scope of
some common policies is also almost certainly needed if the current major
beneficiaries of the agricultural and structural funds are not to be scared off
and to veto expansion.
To begin this phasing in process, the most important thing that the EU could do
would be to further open the single market to companies from the East. This
would give a major boost to economic development in the eastern countries and
demonstrate a real commitment to integrating them into the Union. This will
also benefit business in the West, with easier access to a developing market of
100 million people who will require investment goods, consumer goods and
business and personal services.
Problems for poorer regions in the exisiting EU will doubtless result in them
seeking some form of compensation in return for their agreement to open up the
single market. Such compensation would be on top of any rich-to-poor financial
transfers needed to get economic and monetary union off the ground and to keep
it airborne.
This increased compensation to the poorer areas of the Union could create some
problems for areas like Scotland which currently benefit from EU structural
policy but which are nowhere near the foot of the development league table.
They may well be required to make sacrifices to accommodate increased
compensation elsewhere.
For Scotland as a whole, sacrifices in the short term needed to ease the entry
of East and Central Europe into the EU should be an investment that will pay
off handsomely in the future.
However, individual firms, industries and areas will need to consider carefully
what the threats and opportunities for them will be. The timing and terms of
any expansion will be critical to determining the implications and planning an
appropriate response.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
