<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#460,000 extra for chief</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241305</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FRESH row over ``fat cats'' pay erupted yesterday as it emerged that the new
managing director of the National Grid would receive a #460,000 package on top
of seven-figure earnings for the year.
The deal brought an immediate call from the Labour Party for a last-minute
postponement to the flotation of the Grid next week.
Figures published yesterday in the prospectus for the new GridCo company show
that  Roger Urwin, former chief executive of London Electricity, would receive
pay and perks worth #253,000 and shares worth #207,000.
He is already estimated to have earned #152,000 in the six months from April at
London Electricity and stands to make a total of more than #1m from a variety
of share deals and options.
Shadow Chancellor Gordon Brown dubbed the package ``the biggest privatisation
scandal so far'' and accused the Government of riding roughshod over the
proposals of the Greenbury Committee on executive pay.
The prospectus also revealed that Mr Urwin was being hired on a fixed two-year
contract despite recommendations that top executives should be employed on
rolling renewable contracts designed to reflect performance.
</TEXT>
