<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Footsie at record on bid for Forte</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241307</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UK share prices hit a record high, boosted by Granada's mega-bid for Forte and
fresh gains on Wall Street.
``The rally is not over yet. Wall Street looks like it will go a lot higher,''
one senior dealer said as the Dow Jones Industrial Average cruised higher after
breaking the 5000 barrier on Tuesday.
``But with Thanksgiving tomorrow, we may have to wait until next week before we
see any new highs,'' he added.
In London, the FTSE-100 index of leading shares climbed 28.3 points to an
all-time closing high of 3632.4, beating the record of 3628.8 set on Monday.
Today's Thanksgiving holiday in the United States is likely to cool the
temperature on Wall Street until next week, dampening upward pressure on UK
shares as well.
Second line shares again lagged behind blue chips. The FTSE Mid-250 index
closed up only 8.1 points at 3949.3.
Bonds made modest gains in quiet trade, boosted by German bunds and the pound's
recovery on the foreign exchanges. The December long-gilt future closed up
17/32 at 108-27/32.
Granada's #3400m hostile takeover bid for the Forte hotels and leisure group
stunned the City which had been expecting an offer for either Ladbroke, the
hotel, casino and betting shop empire, or the Pearson media organisation.
Forte raced ahead 72!sp to 347!sp, while Pearson, which owns the Financial
Times and Thames Television, dipped 11p to 648p.
Granada has announced plans to raise #500m from selling off several branches of
the Forte group to avoid a clash with the Monopolies and Mergers Commission,
dropped 48p to 649p.
These include Forte's motorway service stations and its 68% in the Savoy hotel
group. Savoy shares rocketed 142p to 1025p.
Stakis, the Glasgow-based hotel and casino operator, rose 2p to 85p amid the
euphoria.
Cable &amp; Wireless jumped 37p to 466p after chairman Lord Young and chief
executive James Ross announced they were quitting to resolve a personality
clash in the boardroom. The announcement on Tuesday evening came after the
stock market had closed but prompted renewed takeover speculation yesterday.
Courtaulds was another strong performer. The textiles and chemicals group
gained 39p to 399p after saying that steep increases in the price of raw
materials had peaked.
Vodafone was a major faller, shedding 23p to 21p, after heavy selling overnight
in the US in the light of Tuesday's disappointing results.
After the recent excitement of the electricity sector, it was the turn of water
stocks to enjoy strong rises in the expectation of merger moves. North West
Water gained 15p to 605p, while Thames Water firmed 10p to 570p.
Thorn EMI bounded ahead 20p to 1543p in the afterglow of Tuesday's stunning
results.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
