<DOCNO>GH951123-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Granada bids #3400m for Forte Sir Rocco says offer is strategically flawed and totally fails to recognise the group's value</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241308</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FACT FILE
Final 1994-95 1993-94
Turnover #2381m #2098m
Pre-tax profit #351m #265m
EPS 39.1p 32.0p
Dividend 11.75p 10.0p
CORONATION Street to roadside restaurants giant Granada yesterday took the City
by surprise with a #3400m takeover bid for the Forte hotels and catering group.
The hostile offer was immediately rejected by chairman Sir Rocco Forte who said
it was strategically flawed and totally failed to recognise the group's value.
Granada is offering a mixture of four new shares and #23.25 in cash for every
15 Forte shares.
Granada shares tumbled 48p to 649p yesterday so the offer values Forte at 328p
compared to last night's closing price of 347!sp, up 72!sp, on turnover of more
than 47 million shares. The price movement indicates there could be more to go
for through either a counter-offer or an improvement in the Granada terms.
Granada chief executive Gerry Robinson, who will become chairman in succession
to Alex Bernstein next year, said he had been planning the takeover move for
the past three years.
The Forte brands include the Happy Eater and Little Chef restaurants which Mr
Robinson claimed were becoming ``tired''. He said Granada had the highest
margins in the industry and suggested the profitability of the Forte outlets
could be improved by introducing Burger Kings which now account for 40% of the
Granada turnover in this sector.
A Forte failing had been the confusion of hotel branding, he added, with Post
Houses and Travelodges coming too close together. The misfits would be sold as
would the peripheral interests such as the 68% holding in the Savoy, the
Lillywhites sports shop and the quarter stake in Alpha Airports catering, he
said. Together these should raise about #500m.
The Meridien hotels which Forte acquired last year from Air France would be
further developed as an international brand, while the existing Forte Grand
hotels would be incorporated into the chain. These include the George V in
Paris and the Ritz in Madrid as well as the Waldorf in Warsaw.
Mr Robinson is credited with turning Granada round since he moved to the
company from the Compass catering group in 1991 as successor to Derek Lewis,
who went on to run the prisons in England and Wales until earlier this year.
Mr Robinson had tried to contact Sir Rocco first thing yesterday morning but
apparently he was on a shooting holiday.
One possible threat is that, while the Forte family including Sir Rocco's
sister Olga Polizzi own about 8% of the shares, effective voting control is
vested in the Council of Forte.
That is an historic remnant of the merger with Trust Houses in 1970 when the
temperance hotels company, founded in 1904, had its identity assured by a board
of independent trustees. It is chaired by Hugh Astor and its members include
former Labour Prime Minister Lord Callaghan.
The council owns just 780,000 Forte shares but has 50% of the votes. In 1971
Allied Breweries bid for the then Trust House Forte and the council stood aside
under a Takeover Panel dispensation, again renewed, to allow shareholders to
decide for themselves. The offer was dropped.
In the past five years, Forte profits have disappointed, falling from #176m in
1991 to a low of #49m, which resulted in a reduced dividend, and recovering to
#127m last year.
In contrast, Granada has shown a sharp improvement, albeit from a very
depressed base, with it too having to cut its dividend and requiring a rights
issue in 1991. The profits for the year to September have shown substantial
growth with the pre-tax total rising to #351m.
The impetus for this came mostly from television with strong underlying growth
and a full-year contribution from LWT as well as from the 10.8% stake in BSkyB
which is now worth almost #700m.
There was also a good performance in road services including Pavillion Lodges
as well as from the rental and computer services operations. The dividend total
has been raised 17.5% to 11.75p with a 7.9p final.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A matter of conviction: it would never have happened here Why she would have gone Scot free</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241309</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The evidence against Rosemary West was at best flimsy, argues James Freeman who
points out the trial would almost certainly not have gone ahead North of the
Border. What questions does this raise for Scottish and English justice?
DESPITE one of the most exhaustive police investigations mounted, no one ever
found a shred of concrete evidence against Robert Black.
No fingerprint, no bloodstain, no damning fibre, no witness placing Black with
one of the young girl victims was ever traced. Black was convicted nonetheless.
It would be hard to find one soul, particularly among those who listened
throughout to the case, who would disagree with the Newcastle jury's verdict.
Similarly with Rosemary West. Not one witness placed her beyond reasonable
doubt in the presence of any of the hapless girls who died in the most
appalling circumstances imaginable in the Cromwell Street cellar, and neither
did any vital shred of forensic evidence. Yet she was convicted.
Both were convicted, legitimately, in English Crown Courts under the English
doctrine of evidence of similar facts and the harsh reality is that, while no
one seriously questions their guilt, the chances of either being prosecuted in
Scotland would have been so small as to be non-existent.
They would literally have walked away Scot free, out of legal reach because of
the Scottish requirement for corroboration and the basic requirement of
fairness.
From the first moment that both Black and West appeared before the jury the
atmosphere was poisoned. In both cases the Crown began by introducing their
previous criminal convictions, rehearsing the gory details in technicolour,
lingering over the brutality and the horror. In both cases the Crown then went
on to say, essentially, that, although we have no real evidence against them,
because they had behaved like this in the past they are guilty of multiple
murder.
In the trial of Rosemary West, the evidence of Caroline Owens, who was raped
and sexually abused after being given a lift by Fred and Rosemary West and of
Miss A, who was lured into a trap of sexual assault by the couple, was
considered in advance of the trial to be strong enough to help prove that the
couple operated two definite systems for finding victims.
It was also used to rebut Rosemary West's defence that she knew nothing of the
killings, which she blamed on her husband.
On the other hand, the use of this technique allowed two monsters who were
patently guilty to be locked away forever and the public thereby protected.
This begs the question of whether evidence of similar facts could usefully be
adopted in Scotland.
Most lawyers here appear to be against it, but then most have been bitterly
opposed to the small changes - designed to move back towards the centre a
pendulum perceived by many to have swung too far in favour of the accused -
which have recently been made. These include modest measures such as the
removal of the right to challenge jurors' selection, the removal of the right
to know jurors' occupations, and the Crown's right to remark on accused's
refusal to answer questioning.
In Scots law there exists the Moorov Doctrine, little known to the public at
large, and Professor Fraser Davidson at Glasgow University Law School says that
in England similar facts is being used in a very similar way. Under Moorov if
the Crown has only one piece of evidence in relation to a particular crime, but
there is a causal connection between that and other actions of the accused,
evidence of these individual acts may be used to corroborate each other.
In England the idea is close to that, but without the need for corroboration.
If someone is charged with a number of offences similarities in the evidence
can be drawn out to persuade the jury that it is not coincidence.
Evidence of similarity can be drawn from cases not actually being prosecuted
against an accused at that particulare time - an anathema here.
Profesor Davidson says that while the Moorov Doctrine goes along with the idea
some of the way, the English have ``a very elastic concept of what similar
facts are''.
He adds: ``It really is no more than saying that this person is the kind of man
who would abduct a child, and if that is really all you are saying then it is a
doctrine of giving a dog a bad name and condemning him. That is why the law has
to walk a tightrope. You cannot just convict people because of their general
character.
``They have to find some very striking similarity linking a number of cases and
while I can see the attractions of using similar facts the law is walking a
tightrope.''
It has got to the stage in England, Professor Davidson believes, where they are
using the doctrine to say ``this is the kind of person who might commit such
offences therefore he did commit them. In the West case the Crown was basically
saying she was sexually depraved therefore nothing would be beyond her.''
It is difficult, Professor Davidson says, when looking at something like the
Black case to argue that the English have got the balance wrong, yet he still
believes it is a shaky basis on which to prosecute.
``The English,'' he says, `` go too far, saying that the slightest evidence of
similarity allows you to bring in character evidence under the heading of
similar facts.''
Cameron Fyfe, the Glasgow lawyer, takes a cautious but more positive view,
however.
Involving, as it does, the disclosure at the outset of an accused's previous
criminal record, it requires a very delicate balance. He comes down in favour
of disclosure of convictions, which, he says, need not always be prejudicial,
in circumstances where the balance clearly lies with an overwhelming public
interest.
Defence lawyers, including himself, have no hesitation in using evidence of a
man's good character when he has a blameless past to persuade a jury. Why, in
all fairness, cannot the Crown do that in reverse, he asks?
Mr Fyfe points to the Robert Black case, where, as he was led below, Black
turned to the detectives a yard behind him and said:``Well done,lads'' - taken
by most to be an admission the police had got the right man. If that is correct
then the similar facts doctrine worked well in the public interest.
Cameron Fyfe believes that it can never be cut and dried, that there is always
a risk of prejudice when an accused's past character is introduced. But that
could be balanced by a warning to the jury from the Bench, or by defence
counsel in the closing speech.
He admits to the weakness of the principle, put memorably by one counsel when
he said that introducing past character was like bringing a skunk into the
courtroom, taking it away and then expecting the jury to ignore the smell.
``With some misgivings, I would say that in certain cases with a major public
interest I would be in favour of the use of similar facts here, but is always
going to be a close call,'' he says.
Other lawyers, however, reject similar facts as a dangerous road to take. David
Pirrit, of Ross Harper and Murphy in Hamilton, a member of the Law Society of
Scotland's criminal law committee, says that in Scotland the Crown would never
get a conviction on the basis of association but that the accused has to be art
and part.
While rejecting complacency about the law here, he says: ``You may live in a
house with a man who has murdered people and buried bodies in the house. There
may have been knowledge that there was something untoward, or something you
ought to have found untoward, but that does not make you guilty of murder.
``I have misgivings about the West case, that someone could be convicted
because she was married to a maniac. She has confessed to nothing. I would not
like similar facts to be enough - you would have to have some direct evidence.''
Kenneth Pritchard, secretary of the Law Society of Scotland, declares: ``The
law here is that previous convictions are not disclosed until the accused is
convicted of these charges on which he is being tried at that precise moment.
Similar facts simply amount to bringing in evidence of previous convictions
early on.
``There is no good reason advanced, only emotion, to suggest the law here
should be changed. A vast amount of emotion surfaces around cases such as Black
and West with a strong public feeling that they must be convicted at all costs
and if you can use evidence of previous convictions then you should do so.
``I would not like to see it in our law because it would be sure to prejudice
the minds of juries. Emotional cases do not justify changing the law by
shooting from the hip.''
But would it not have been monstrous had Black, or Rosemary West, walked away
Scot free for lack of direct evidence, probably missing because of the passage
of time?
Mr Pritchard: ``We have to live with this. The problem is that you are so
anxious to get someone convicted that you lose sight of what could happen in
thousands of other cases coming along thereafter. By introducing what an
accused has done in the past it of course ignores the fact that he or she may
have in the interim changed their ways and that is deeply unfair.''
</TEXT>
