<HEADLINE>The Glasgow connection in search for `missing'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>James Freeman Home Affairs Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241310</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOW many more bodies litter the trail of Frederick and Rosemary West, and where
do they lie?
That now is the question uppermost in the minds of the authorities concerned
with the investigation, although direct interrogation of West will have to wait
until after her appeal.
It is that questioning which will hold the key to any future discoveries.
Yesterday, Gloucestershire's chief constable, Mr Tony Butler, said his force
would be ``reviewing potential areas for further investigation'', and whether
or not Strathclyde Police becomes involved will depend on Mr Butler.
There are many precedents. Following the conviction of Robert Black, the most
recent serial killer prior to West, and the rejection of his appeal, police
forces in whose areas girls went missing in strikingly similar circumstances to
Black's known victims, sought to question him further.
Black has never cracked, but Rosemary West may not be so strong.
Strathclyde Police yesterday reiterated that, at the moment, it has no direct
interest in the case, but that might change in the light of the further
interrogation of Rosemary West.
Should she choose to confirm what many people already believe - that there are
further bodies - then any search in Glasgow would have to concentrate at the
site of Frederick West's former allotment in Gower Street, Kinning Park.
According to witness John McLachlan, who took The Herald to the spot, the
allotment has been largely built over, although portions may remain in the form
of back gardens.
Mr McLachlan has repeatedly said that West often spent many hours at the
allotment by himself, sometimes until the early hours of the morning, and that
he may have been using a hut there to meet girlfriends.
Police have never closed their file on teenage waitress Mary Bastholm, who
vanished from a bus stop in Gloucester in 1968, and became a key figure in the
trial of Rosemary West nearly 30 years later.
Mary, 15, was last seen alive on a Saturday evening in January, 1968, while
waiting at a bus stop outside the city's Avenue Hotel.
But police believe that instead of taking the bus to the home of boyfriend Tim
Merrett at Hardwicke, five miles away, she might have accepted a lift because
it was raining.
Officers mounted a huge search for her, and inquiries were made throughout the
country, but the trail went cold until Frederick West admitted she was dead.
Voluntary worker Janet Leach told Rosemary West's trial that Fred West had
admitted to her that Mary Bastholm was dead, and that her remains were ``in a
farm''.
West also told her during their confidential conversations that he knew Mary,
and had picked her up, Mrs Leach said.
Mary's brother Peter, 50, who still lives in Gloucester, but was serving with
the Royal Navy, in Singapore, at the time she disappeared, said he now believes
she was one of West's victims.
Police yesterday appealed for information on the whereabouts of nine women who
visited the Wests and have since disappeared.
The women were aged between 13 and their late 30s when they were known to have
been at the Wests' Cromwell Street home.
However, in a statement released after the verdicts in the trial, detectives
said there was as yet no evidence that the missing women were victims of the
Wests.
Missing are:
q Marilyn, a white woman in her late 30s in 1973, and thought to have been a
devout Christian.
q Donna Lynn Moore (or similar), described in 1973 as white, aged 13 or 14,
slim and pretty, and who spoke with an American accent, and may have been the
daughter of a US serviceman from an East Anglian airbase.
q Name not known, but police issued a photograph of the woman which is thought
to have been taken when she visited in 1975. It shows a full-faced brunette
with rosy lips.
q Maria Ann, a white woman in her early 20s in 1991. She had long, blonde hair
and may have been a student.
q Mireeker or Marieka (or similar), a white woman in her late 20s in 1977/78,
who may have come from Holland.
q Name not known, a white woman aged between 18 and 20 in 1978.
q May have been called Ingrid, a white woman aged around 18 in 1978/79, who
possibly spoke with a German accent.
q Marilyn, aged 18 or 19 with long, blonde hair in 1973.
q Name unknown, a white woman aged 17 to 20 in 1973, with blonde hair and who
spoke with a Swedish or Dutch accent.
</TEXT>
