<BYLINE>JAmes Traynor Chief Sports Writer Glory of Gascoigne strike is still not enough for Rangers                                       ...</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241311</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GROUP C TABLE
P W D L F A Pt
Juventus  5 4 0 1 15 4 12
Dortmund  5 2 2 1 6 6 8
Steaua  5 1 2 2 2 5 5
Rangers  5 0 2 3 4 12 2
Remaining matches (Dec 6): Broussia Dortmund v Rangers, Steaua Bucharest v
Juventus.
Rangers ........ 1  Steaua Bucharest.......1
PAUL Gascoigne offered the fleeting possibility of glory, but Rangers were
disabused of any grand and ultimately ridiculous notions by an efficient team
from Romania, and also by events which unfolded eslewhere in the footballing
world.
Even before the crowd had deserted Ibrox last night, it was clear Rangers'
Champions' League campaign was over so far as qualification to the final stages
was concerned.
Walter Smith's side had to win on their own turf, and also hope that the
Italian champions and comfortable leaders of Group C, Juventus, would beat
Borussia Dortmund for a second time.
But success could not be secured on either front.
Rangers' draw with Steaua has left them at the bottom of their section with
only two points after five matches, and they will be travelling to Dortmund in
a fortnight with only the desire to restore some credibility.
The Germans, on the other hand, know they have secured second place. To keep
their pride absolutely intact, they will want to beat Rangers.
If they can go to Turin and beat Juventus 2-1, as they did last night, then
they must be favourites to win at home against Rangers, while Steaua are
unlikely to beat the Italians, who would still win the section even if they
were to lose.
The Germans also have a superior head-to-head record over Steaua, as well as a
better goal difference should the Romanians catch Juventus sleeping.
Rangers' most damning examinations in this contest were against Juventus, but
it was the failure to win any of their matches so far against the other
also-rans in Group C which caused them greatest damage.
The fans were left still wondering what might happen if Brian Laudrup and
Gascoigne were able to produce their best on a regular basis, especially in
Europe.
One flash of Gascoigne's brilliance was enough to inject fresh enthusiasm and
hope into the 30,882 crowd which was the lowest Ibrox attandance this season.
However, he faded, and Laudrup, playing in only his second match after having
returned from a lengthy idle period because of injury, tended to be anonymous
as he remained out wide. In fact, Steaua's coach, Dumitru Dumitriu, delivered a
telling assessment on Gascoigne after the match.
``He is dangerous if you let him have the ball at his feet. He has vision, and
he is good with free kicks, but I don't think he can play for 90 minutes,'' he
said.
The Romanian also was critical of the other Rangers players, pointing out:
``They seem to be waiting all the time for Laudrup and Gascoigne to do things
when they should be trying to do things for themselves.''
It was also Dumitriu's belief that his side would have won had they not been so
anxious to subdue Gascoigne, but Steaua did play with much more momentum in the
second half when Andy Goram had to produce another series of marvellous saves.
``It was obvious, I think, that we had more chances to win than Rangers,''
Dumitriu said.
Apart from offering Goram, who had memorable saves from Antonel Pirvu, Daniel
Prodan, Ion Vladoiu, and Marius Lacatus, his thanks again, manager Walter Smith
also praised his captain, Richard Gough, who has played pretty well throughout
even though the statistics suggest the opposite.
Rangers, who have scored only four goals in five matches, have conceded 12, but
Smith said: ``I thought Gough was outstanding tonight.''
Gough's defensive partner, Gordan Petric, was not mentioned, but then he was at
fault for the Romanian side's equaliser in 55 minutes. He played a poor pass
forward to Stuart McCall, who had to stretch and lost possession allowing
Steaua to surge forward.
They shuttled the ball ahead quickly and Adrian Ilie, who had given Alan
McLaren such a difficult time in Bucharest two months ago, raced into Rangers'
box and placed the ball in the net.
If the truth be told, however, Rangers were already being shown the door
because Dortmund were leading Juventus.
Indeed, the Germans were ahead before Rangers scored their goal, but that
didn't dampen the wild celebration of Gascoigne's contribution in 31 minutes.
A high Petric clearance fell to Laudrup just inside his own half, and he played
the ball inside to Gascoigne, who immediately started forward.
But when he had crossed into enemy territory and looked up, he saw not one of
his colleagues in an ideal position.
No choice, then, than to sprint into the heart of Steaua's defence and all
around him defenders panicked.
Gascoigne seemed to increase pace, and from about 18 yards out, he put the ball
beyond Bogdan Stelea's reach and into the net.
It was Gascoigne, not Gazza. It was the footballing genius and not the
bad-tempered loutish character who often is the more dominant personality
within this troubled player.
It was the player Rangers believed they were buying when they paid Lazio #4.3m
in the close season.
Walter Smith started the match with John Brown at the heart of the defence with
Gough and Petric and McLaren filling in at right fullback for the suspended
Alex Cleland, but even though Gascoigne gave the side hope, the midfield was
not functioning properly, and Ally McCoist, with Ian Durrant playing just off
him, was too often isolated.
Support rarely arrived in time for McCoist, who had only one chance to score.
A minute into the second half, a Gascoigne free kick from the right, flicked on
by McLaren, arrived at the far post and, somehow, Stelea managed to dive to his
right and slap McCoist's powerful header away. It was a save of which even
Goram would have been proud.
Two Rangers players, McCall, who injured his groin and is doubtful for
Saturday's match against Hibernian, and Petric, were booked.
It was Petric's second caution of the competition and he will miss the final
game in Dortmund.
Lacatus will sit out Steaua's last game because he, too, received his second
caution, and another Romanian, Vladoiu, also was booked.
RANGERS - Goram, McLaren, Petric, Gough, Brown, Robertson, Gascoigne, McCall,
Laudrup, Durrant, McCoist. Substitutes - Miller, Murray, Bollan, Boyack, Scott.
STEAUA BUCHAREST - Stelea, Filipescu, Dobos, Prodan, Csik, Pirvu, Militaru,
Bucur, Lacarus, Vladoiu, Ilie. Substitutes - Rosu, Panait, Nagy, Raducan,
Gherasim.
Referee - N Levnikov (Russia).
</TEXT>
