<HEADLINE>Deal for airline will expand Edinburgh tour operator's route network Globespan buys Excalibur</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241312</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLOBESPAN, the Edinburgh-based tour operator, has bought Excalibur Airways, a
charter airline, to expand its long-haul route network.
The price of the transaction has not been disclosed, but is believed to run
into several million pounds.
Tom Dalrymple, the chairman and owner of Globespan, said the deal would enable
his company to start charter flights from Scotland to Australia next winter.
It would also lay the foundations for expanding Globespan's route network to
areas such as east and west Africa, the Far East and the Caribbean, he added.
Until now the company has concentrated on charter flights from Scotland and
England to a dozen destinations in the USA and Canada using planes chartered
from North American airlines.
Globespan also runs charter flights to Majorca and seasonal services from
London to Johannesburg and Sydney. But it has often found difficulty obtaining
planes to operate long-haul routes outside the transaltantic sector.
Excalibur Airways, which was founded in 1991, operates five leased 180-seat
Airbus 320A airliners on charter flights to European destinations.
But it will take delivery of two McDonnell Douglas DC-10 350-seat planes in the
spring which are ideal for long-haul routes.
The airline, which is based at East Midlands airport, carried 700,000
passengers last year. Although it makes a profit during the busy summer months,
a slump in winter traffic has plunged it into loss for the last two years.
``It is their purpose for selling. They could not solve the winter problem, but
we can,'' Mr Dalrymple said, noting that Excalibur made a loss of #1.6m last
year on turnover of #52m.
Globespan can solve this problem by using Excalibur planes on long-haul
services during the slack winter months. It plans a new weekly flight from
Glasgow to Sydney which will start in October 1996.
``The purpose really of buying the airline is to run charters to Australia,''
Mr Dalrymple said.
Globespan has made a profit every year since it was founded by him in 1974.
The company, which arranges package holidays as well as charter flights, made a
profit of #2m on turnover of #53m in the year to October 1994 and carried
180,000 passengers.
``We expect an increase in both turnover and profits for the year ending in
1995,'' Mr Dalrymple said.
Globespan is a classic case of a business built up from scratch by a self-made
Scottish entrepreneur.
Mr Dalrymple, who is Edinburgh born and bred, left school at 16 in 1961 to work
for Mackay Brothers, which was then the largest travel agency in Scotland.
At the age of 29 he launched Globespan and has not looked back since.
The company has grown cautiously but steadily, avoiding the boom and bust cycle
which many other UK tour operators have suffered and is the biggest tour
operator based in Scotland.
``We started off with straight charter flights, but now we sell almost 50% of
our package holidays on the charter planes,'' said Mr Dalrymple, who is 51.
Excalibur Airways is Globespan's first ever acquisition and the deal was
carefully planned to benefit both businesses.
``We are a very prudent Scottish organisation. This is not a bolt out of the
blue,'' Mr Dalrymple said.
He reckons that Globespan will add up to #17m of extra business each year to
Excalibur's existing turnover.
But the airline will continue to be run by its present management and will
actively seek new business from other sources.
Until now Excalibur's directors controlled 40% of the voting shares, with Air
Malta and the venture capital firm 3i each holding a further 30%.
Mr Dalrymple will become chairman of Excalibur once the deal is completed next
Wednesday, but Bob O'Donnell will stay on as managing director and four other
directors will keep their seats on the board.
``Globespan is an ideal partner for Excalibur,'' Mr O'Donnell said. ``The
ability to add in-house flying to Excalibur's existing portfolio of customers
will allow us to develop the company in a way that would not have been possible
from our own resources.''
Globespan has financed the acquisition of Excalibur entirely from its own
resources. ``We are a very cash-rich business relative to our size,'' Mr
Dalrymple noted.
</TEXT>
