<HEADLINE>Gallacher ready for off</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241313</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STEPHEN Gallacher today heads a seven-strong Scottish contingent seeking to
secure their European Tour cards at the nineteenth Qualifying School at San
Roque in the south of Spain.
He makes the often perilous transition from the amateur ranks into the realms
of paid play when he tees off at Guadalmina today at the outset of the 108-hole
event. With a field of 183, competition will be fierce for the 40 available
spots.
With the financial backing of his uncle Bernard - winning European Ryder Cup
captain - Stephen is confident about his chances. ``I'm looking forward to
it,'' he said. ``I am playing some great golf from tee to green and my putting
is solid.''
A record 670 players have attempted to gain access to the circuit this year,
and tournament director Andy McFee said: ``I have been at this event since 1983
and I can safely say it's the toughest one yet.''
Elsewhere, Raymond Russell, Scott Henderson, Andrew Crerar, David Scott,
William Guy, Stephen Thompson, and veteran Brian Marchbank will compete.
q A DOUBLE bogey on the 471-yard par-4 last cost Gary Weir his second outright
win of the season at the East of Scotland Alliance outing after a gap of almost
15 years at Monktonhall, Musselburgh, yesterday.
Stuart Callan also won the handicap Jordan Cup with a better inward half,
three-under-par 32, from Weir and amateur David Smith (Dunfermline), who had a
78 off 9. Results:
Scratch: 69 - S Callan (Dalmahoy), G Weir (Braid Hills DR). 70 - C Brooks
(Glencorse). 71 - F Mann (Monktonhall), P Terras (Goswick). 72 - G Walker
(Royal Musselburgh). Handicap (Jordan Cup): 69 - Callan (b.i.h.), Weir, D Smith
(Dunfermline, 9). 70 - P Ritchie (Bathgate, 10). 71 - A Wight (Glencorse, 3).
72 - R Patrick (Glenbervie, 8), G Johnston (Glenbervie, 7), M Louden
(Glencorse, 4), R Gibson (Newbattle, 3). Assistants: 72 - Walker.
q OPEN champion John Daly, Greg Norman, and Steve Elkington are some of the
star attractions at the Australian Open, which starts today at Kingston Heath,
Melbourne.
There are many Europeans in the line-up, including Volvo Masters winner
Alexander Cejka and the French World Cup pair, Jean Van de Velde and Jean-Louis
Guepy, plus Englishmen Gary Evans, Steven Richardson, and Steven Bottomley.
</TEXT>
