<HEADLINE>IBM executive director retires</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241314</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN WARD has retired as an executive director of IBM after a 29-year career
with the US-based computer company. Mr Ward, above, joined IBM in 1966 and was
appointed resident director for Scotland and Northern England in 1991, with
direct oversight of the group's huge personal computer factory in Greenock.
IBM said he would retain his association with the company in a non-executive
capacity as a member of its advisory board. Mr Ward, 55, ended a two-year stint
as chairman of the Confederation of British Industry in Scotland in September.
But he is far from seeking early retirement. Last week he was appointed a
non-executive director of the Glasgow-based Macfarlane (Clansman) packaging
group.
</TEXT>
