<HEADLINE>Double penalty save fails to stop Hibs Weir, McAllister finally put Thistle's lights out</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241315</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Hibernian 3, Partick Thistle 0
THE lights shone all night at Easter Road but Thistle were left stumbling into
the team bus, bedraggled and beaten by a Hibs team that rediscovered the
shooting form that had been so evident earlier in the season.
The capital side were comfortable winners in the game rearranged after the
floodlights had failed to come on two weeks ago, and in the process,
consolidated their third place in the premier division. They also crept to
within four points of Celtic in second place and ended a hiccup in which they
had lost their previous two games.
They will, therefore, go into their next challenge, against Rangers on
Saturday, in much better fettle than might have been the case and will
entertain a much bigger crowd than the 7137, the lowest in the league so far,
last night.
Thistle were still in with a shout midway in the second half, at which point
they were only down by a Darren Jackson first-half goal, but when Mickey Weir
and then Kevin McAllister scored, the contest was over.
Jackson appeared in the side following a bout of flu, and that was to prove
fortunate, but before then, the international striker felt the full weight of a
tough tackle from Gregg Watson in the first minute and needed attention.
Jackson's namesake, Chris, almost startled the few Thistle fans in the south
stand when he seemed sure to score from a fine pass by Mickey Weir, but a
superb tackle by Alan Dinnie saved Partick.
Thistle had appeared to have withstood the early fire from Hibs, shooting
downhill, and indeed, they came close with a Steve Welsh header from an Ian
Cameron corner, but they were caught out after 20 minutes.
Steven Tweed had done the work, breaking down the inside-left channel, before
the ball broke to Weir, who passed it on to Jackson, and he hammered the ball
home from the edge of the box.
Thistle had to take off Steve Pittman, who had suffered a knock, and bring on
Calum Milne. The former Hibs man soon upset his ex-team's fans with a scything
tackle on Chris Jackson which earned him a yellow card.
Hibs tried to claim a penalty when Weir was hampered by Tom Smith but the
referee was not fooled. Andy Millen had his name taken for persistent fouling
which gave Thistle a free kick and some respite into the bargain.
Thistle began the second half without the injured Wayne Foster. Andy Gibson was
his replacement and the new man let Derek McWilliams in with a chance, but the
midfield player lofted the ball over the bar. The Firhill team looked to be
down and out in 52 minutes, however, when Hibs were awarded a penalty. Darren
Jackson was impeded, albeit marginally, by Tommy Turner, as he worked a 1-2
with Weir, and referee Tait, who was close up, gave the spot-kick instantly.
Jackson hit the penalty hard but Nicky Walker flung himself to his right to
block the ball and, while still on the ground, managed to parry the second
attempt by the striker and eventually grasp the ball to his chest.
However, Hibs went two clear. Joe Tortolano deceived the entire Thistle defence
with a marvellous pass through the middle and Weir ran on to it, got around
Walker and kept his head while being challenged to slide the ball over the
line. Three minutes later the points were safely locked away. Darren Jackson
went speeding through the middle, and timed his pass to McAllister perfectly
for the winger to shoot out of Walker's reach.
Hibs' manager Alex Miller was happy that his team had recovered their form. ``I
thought we showed a wee bit of character tonight, especially after missing a
penalty, because we put up our sleeves and worked hard again.''
HIBERNIAN - Leighton, Dods, Tortolano, McGinlay, Tweed, Hunter, McAllister,
Millen, Weir, D Jackson, C Jackson. Substitutes - Evans, Donald, Miller.
PARTICK THISTLE - Walker, Dinnie, Pittman, Smith, Welsh, Watson, McWilliams,
Turner, Foster, Cameron, Docherty. Substitutes - Milne, Gibson, Curran.
Referee - R Tait (East Kilbride).
</TEXT>
