<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Juventus bow to Dortmund double</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241316</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BORUSSIA Dortmund's victory over Juventus in Turin last night secured their
place in the quarter-finals of the European Champions' League in Group C
alongside the Italian champions.
Well-taken goals from former German internationalist Michael Zorc and Lars
Ricken ended the Italian side's 100 per cent record in the group and gave the
Germans revenge for a humiliating 3-1 defeat at home earlier in the year.
Zorc opened the scoring after 29 minutes with a powerful right-foot shot from
the edge of the box. Ricken made it 2-0 in the sixty-fourth minute, quickly
latching on to a misdirected header from Juventus defender Massimo Carrera and
drilling the ball past keeper Angelo Peruzzi.
Juventus, whose home form has faded after an impressive start to the season,
grabbed an injury-time consolation goal through second-half substitute
Alessandro Del Piero, who has now scored in each of his team's five cup matches
to date.
``We paid for two defensive mistakes,'' said Marcello Lippi, the Juventus
coach. ``My players tried hard, but it was not their best night.''
Ricken, cautioned for the second time in the tournament, will miss Borussia's
last qualifying match, against Rangers on December 6.
JUVENTUS - Peruzzi, Porrini, Pessotto, Carrera, Vierchowod, Tacchinardi, Di
Livio, Jugovic, Vialli, Marocchi, Padovano.
BORUSSIA DORTMUND - Klos, Kree, Schmidt, Freund, Kohler, Sammer, Reuter, Zorc,
Ricken, Moeller, Herrlich.
Juventus 1, Borussia Dortmund 2
</TEXT>
