<HEADLINE>Record entry draws large crowd to Scottish National Winter Fair at Perth Cross-bred Limousins triumph</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241317</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
X
BEEF cattle judge Ewen Macpherson of Benderloch, Oban, hailed yesterday's
Scottish National Winter Fair at Perth as one of the best for many years. ``It
is debatable whether we will see any better cattle at Smithfield next week,''
he said.
His choice for the overall championship was a lightweight cross-bred Limousin
steer from A Macgregor (Allanfauld), Kilsyth. Reserve was a 415kg cross-bred
Limousin heifer shown by Ray Grieve of Carlhurlie, Lundin Links, by Leven, Fife.
The champion, which weighed 465kg, is a son of Scottish Livestock Services'
renowned bull Shatton Pedro, which, coincidentally, was put down yesterday at
the age of 16.
The overall championship and reserve in the sheep classes went to the
father-and-son team of Richard and Granville Colegrave of Guardswell, Abernyte,
Inchture, who were showing at their first winter fair. Their winning pen of two
ewe lambs were from a Beltex tup out of a Dutch Texel ewe. The Colegraves have
400 ewes and 130 cows.
Judge Malcolm MacDiarmid of the Perth Fresh Meat Company said the lambs showed
excellent quality stemming from skilled stockmanship. He added they were ideal
for the export trade and that he expected to see many more like them coming on
to the market. His company was currently buying 1000 lambs a week for export.
Andy Hamilton, president of the Scottish National Fatstock Club, was well
pleased with the support for the fair. ``We have had a record number of entries
and numbers through the gate must be at least the same as last year,'' he said.
By afternoon the organisers were having to divert vehicles to an overflow car
park.
Arrangements were already in hand for next year at Perth, he said, but he was
cautious about suggestions that the event could stretch to two days. ``I would
prefer one day which is full of interest all day,'' he said.
Beef championship results: Lightweight steer - A Macgregor (Allanfauld),
Kilsyth; reserve John Y Currie, Southook Farm, Kilmarnock. Intermediate steer -
George McFadzean Jnr, Woodhead of Mailer, Perth; reserve AR Grieve, Lundin
Links, by Leven, Fife. Heavyweight steer - J Scott Watson Balhousie Farm,
Carnoustie; reserve Jack S Wight, Midlock, Crawford, Biggar.
Lightweight heifer - AR Grieve; reserve Hugh Dunlop, Mill o' Shiel, Barbieston,
Ayrshire. Heavyweight heifer - David B Sinclair, Abernyte House, Inchture,
Perthshire; reserve Bertie S Paton, Spott, Glenprosen, Angus. Supreme heifer -
AR Grieve; reserve Hugh Dunlop.
In the carcase section (live) the championship went to David Cunningham,
Walkerdyke, Strathaven; reserve David Robertson, Crail, Fife.
Sheep - champion Monzie Farms, Crieff; reserve Mary Dunlop, Corstane, Biggar.
Pigs - champion J&amp;H Traquair &amp; Son, Wellington Farm, Dalkeith; reserve W.&amp;.AM
Meiklejohn, Pitkennedy, Forfar.
