<HEADLINE>High-flying Livingston to launch a new pilot scheme</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241318</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIVINGSTON'S players are going back to school in an attempt to spread the
football word around the town.
The club are to start a pilot scheme in the primary schools in the area and
hope to extend it to all of West Lothian.
Manager Jim Leishman said yesterday: ``The plan is for all our full-time
players to go into schools on a Monday and Tuesday and carry out coaching when
the youngsters are at physical education classes.
``This is a trial project, but, if successful, I would hope to see it expanded.
If any other schools in the West Lothian region are interested they should get
in touch.
``I don't think there is another club in Scotland attempting this. But it's
another example of the way we are integrating into the area and we now have a
restaurant and a social club open.''
Premier division Kilmarnock will visit Livingston on Monday to inaugurate the
floodlights at the new Almondvale Stadium, and Leishman added: ``It's kind of
Killie and their manager, Alex Totten, to come and we expect another full
house. Tickets are on sale and I hope the Killie fans who slagged me so often
will come along.''
q UNLUCKY Berwick central defender Mark Wilson is heading back to hospital in
another attempt to discover the cause of a mystery injury. And as the Berwick
injury list lengthens, manager Tom Hendrie yesterday pleaded for money to keep
alive their promotion hopes.
Wilson was carried off in the match against Queen of the South on Tuesday and
Hendrie said: ``It is a recurrence of a knee injury and this time we will need
to find the cause. He had a cartilege operation, but then had further trouble
in the knee.
Things are so bad at Berwick that Hendrie was on the bench for a recent match
and assistant, John Couglin, had to be included in the side against Clyde, even
though he had not played in the top team for two years.
q RYAN Hegarty has signed for Dunfermline after having been given a free
transfer by Dundee United.
</TEXT>
