<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Captain McKimmie hopes to follow in Buchan's footsteps Victory will make a dream come true</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ken Gallacher Chief Football Writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241319</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
q ABERDEEN are odds-on favourites to beat Dundee and lift their first trophy in
over five years. Corals have made the Dons 5-6 to triumph in Sunday's Coca-Cola
Cup final at Hampden while the Dens Park men are 11-4, with a draw after 90
minutes on offer at 9-4. Scott Booth is favourite to score first at 5-1, with
Pittodrie team-mate Billy Dodds 6-1. Dundee's George Shaw is 7-1 and Jim
Hamilton 8-1.
ABERDEEN captain Stewart McKimmie will travel to Hampden on Sunday hoping to
fulfil a lifelong dream he felt had moved beyond his grasp.
McKimmie, who will lead his home-town team into the Coca-Cola Cup final against
Dundee, still remembers the taunts and jeers which followed him for so much of
last season, wants to be the first Aberdeen-born captain of the Pittodrie team
to hold a trophy since Martin Buchan 25 years ago.
``It's something you dream about,'' said McKimmie, ``but last season, when
things were going so badly, I just could not believe it would happen for me.''
Then, of course, Aberdeen were fighting for league survival and McKimmie was
the target for the boo boys, just as other home-town skippers have been down
through the years.
Says McKimmie: ``It has always been the case that Aberdeen-born captains get a
hard time from the support. It happened to me last season, but now it seems to
be in the past. Of course, now the team is playing better and that helps.
``When I was asked to be captain last season I began to think how it would be
to win a trophy and to hold it above my head at Hampden. But the way we were
playing I became convinced that that would never happen. Now there is a chance
to do it.
``It will not be easy against Dundee. They have beaten two premier division
sides already.''
The Scotland international full back believes that the pressure on Sunday will
be on Aberdeen. He says: ``Dundee are not expected to win and people will look
to last season when Raith Rovers defeated Celtic. All of that will put pressure
on us, but we have to be able to handle that.
``The one thing which may work in our favour is that Dundee, like ourselves,
are a team who like to attack. This could be a high-scoring final, because both
of us have so many potential scorers.
``Last weekend we gave our worst performance of the season at Kirkcaldy against
Raith Rovers. They just did not give us any room to play. Teams who close us
down give us problems. But Dundee would have to change their style if they were
to try that.''
The captain and the rest of the Aberdeen players know that their best games
this year have been in this tournament. On their way to the final they had
notable victories over Motherwell and Rangers.
But McKimmie stresses: ``We still don't have consistency. When I first came
here we seemed to be in a cup final every season - and we were winning them,
too. You just didn't think about losing.
``Now there has been a gap of five-and-a-half years since we last won a cup. We
want to win this one and only consistency will do that.''
Manager Roy Aitken also was preaching consistency. He pointed out: ``When we
are at our best we can match any team in the country, but sometimes we let
ourselves down.
``In the quarter-final and the semi-final against Motherwell and Rangers we
showed what we can do. If we play in that manner in the final then we will win
the cup.
``As far as I'm concerned if we do win then that will simply be the start of
something here.
``If we could go on a run of success then I might be able to bring more quality
players to Aberdeen. Players like to be associated with successful clubs. In
fact, it would help me keep some of our good players here.
``This will be an attractive final, a big crowd, a great atmosphere, and is a
challenge for the players we have here at Aberdeen, if they take up the
challenge then we all have a new beginning.''
Aberdeen have just one player ruled out through injury, defender Colin
Woodthorpe, who is still suffering the effects of a broken bone in a foot.
Two more players, Theo Snelders and Eoin Jess, are doubtful, but Aitken
insisted yesterday: ``We have an extra day to get them ready with the final on
Sunday. I'm confident that I'll have both players.''
Meantime, Dundee managing director Nigel Squire yesterday told exiled chairman
Ron Dixon: ``You can have my seat at Hampden.''
Canadian chairman Dixon, whose #2m investment has helped keep Dundee in
business, has been out of Scotland for a year - and was out of contact with the
Dens Park board for more than six months.
But Squire revealed yesterday that Dixon had made a transatlantic call from
Vancouver to wish the club all the best for Sunday's final. ``I've had a
telephone call from Ron and he knew all about the club's progress - the
semi-final win over Airdrie, and the derby win,'' said Squire.
``I told him we would love to see him at Hampden on Sunday, but he has a lot of
business on at the moment. I'm keeping one seat for him if he needs it.''
</TEXT>
