<HEADLINE>McRae shows he's simply the best</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241320</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IMPRESSIVE, imperial, Impreza. Lanark's Colin McRae is rallying's best in the
world, along with his Subaru team. And he's the first Briton to have won the
title.
What was a turbulent Tuesday, with mishaps flying about like the mud of the
difficult courses set for the Network Q RAC Rally, turned into a welcome
Wednesday as McRae charged through the final stages to finish in Chester as
overall winner ahead of rival Carlos Sainz, and take that coveted world crown -
and at 27, he is the youngest to do so.
On top of all that, it suddenly became a family affair, with 24-year-old
brother Alister taking fourth place overall. The previous best by two brothers
was in 1989 when Kenneth and Hakan Eriksson finished first and tenth in the
Swedish Rally.
``It hasn't sunk in yet,'' said Colin. ``I am delighted - this was my, Derek's,
and the team's goal this year. I've struggled for years to get a good result on
the RAC Rally. We put in a very quick time on Monday's first gravel stage which
gave me confidence.''
Co-driver Derek Ringer added: ``There were a few   hairy moments, of course,
but most of the time, Colin drove very smoothly.''
Dad Jimmy McRae, who began the family's celebrations by winning the RAC
Historic Rally on Sunday said: ``I am very proud of them both. I was a bit
worried I'd put too much pressure on Colin by winning,'' he joked.
In third place, behind Carlos Sainz, were Richard Burns and co-driver Robert
Reid from Spittal, near Perth - making it a 1-2-3 for Subaru.
Kilmarnock's Robbie Head finished fifteenth overall in his Renault Clio Maxi,
four places behind was Brian Lyall from Aberdeen driving a Ford Escort.
King of the road - Page 34
</TEXT>
