<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The making of a rally champion</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241322</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COLIN McRae's first steps towards winning the biggest prize in rallying and
becoming the first Briton to win the World Rally Championship began two years
ago with a limited overseas programme, driving a Subaru Legacy.
Team manager David Richards secured the then 25-year-old McRae under contract.
The Scot began repaying the investment in his burgeoning talent with two
victories, New Zealand and Malaysia.
Last year - at the wheel of a Subaru Impreza 555 - he added the Network Q RAC
Rally and Rally Australia to his win in New Zealand. But 1994 also had its
downs. In Monte Carlo, he crashed and was relegated to tenth. Portugal ended
with a fire, and Corsica after an accident. In May's Acropolis Rally, he was
excluded after a verbal clash with officials, and he crashed out of the Rally
Argentina.
He won the final round of the series but it also created new pressures. Colin
and Derek Ringer - his co-driver of nine years' standing - were now tipped as
hot favourites to win the 1995 championship.
In January's opening round in Monte Carlo McRae crashed out on an icy corner.
In the snowy forests of Sweden he retired with engine failure. After two of the
eight rounds he didn't have a single point. He managed third place in Portugal
and, after fifth in Corsica, New Zealand again was the watershed. His
domination was total.
After the Asia-Pacific, it was in September's Rally Australia that a new,
mature McRae emerged. Lying first equal with Kenneth Eriksson's Mitsubishi, he
let the Swede take victory and settled for championship points.
The seventh round was in Spain - home ground for Carlos Sainz, a rival for the
title.
Starting the final day, he was second to Sainz but team orders dictated they
should hold their positions. It was only after much persuasion by Richards and
Colin's father, Jimmy, that McRae reluctantly booked in late at the final
control, letting Sainz win.
The scene was now set for an emotional and public showdown on McRae's home
event. Fairly and squarely the better man won.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>We can't have our oatcake and eat it</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Brian Meek</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241323</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SURVEYS can be very entertaining, though not always particularly enlightening.
I once asked a group of residents whether they wished to have a bus service
introduced into their area. ``Yes,'' replied 98%.
Would they use it? You bet, chorused the same number. Would they be prepared to
have the bus stop outside their front gate? ``No,'' replied 98%.
Would Scottish businessmen like a Scottish parliament? The Fraser of Allander
Institute for the Scottish Chambers of Commerce did not, for reasons best known
to themselves, actually ask that question in their survey entitled
``Constitutional Canvass''.
Instead they invited companies to indicate whether decentralising
decision-making from Westminster would improve business prospects. I would have
thought this was akin to inquiring whether they would prefer dry to wet weather.
No matter, 50.1% of those who bothered to reply - there was only a 19% response
rate so you can judge what a hot topic this is - agreed with the proposition
and 38.1% said it would make not a blind bit of difference.
To my utter amazement this is interpreted as ``Business chiefs back home rule''.
Mr Peter Dunn, acting director general of the Scottish Chambers, declares that
the survey shows ``a tidal move'' in attitudes and posed questions for all
political parties. Like, what's this guy talking about? I wish to see a
Scottish parliament. And an English parliament and a Welsh one and another in
Northern Ireland; for I am a federalist. What I do not wish to come to pass is
the pig's breakfast which is being proposed by the Labour Party, the Liberal
Democrats, and the Canon's kids of the Convention.
And nor, very decisively, does the vast majority of Scottish business. Nearly
70% say a tax-raising assembly would harm their companies' prospects and,
should that come to pass, some of them will think of relocating elsewhere in
the UK. How could this be translated into business backing home rule,
particularly when 74.4% also reject independence?
But the Lib-Dems are terribly pleased with themselves. In Edinburgh their
leader, Councillor Donald Gorrie, a man so enamoured by a Scottish parliament
that he has spent most of his days trying unsuccessfully to get to Westminster,
is forever producing motions congratulating his own party and suggesting we
should all join in the big jamboree next week. If he had any pride at all he
would be putting his kilt over his head.
For the Lib-Dems are perhaps most to blame for the daft scheme which lies on
the table. It was they who sold their souls for a mess of potage.
Don't we all remember the lectures we were given on proportional
representation, the saviour of all mankind? And not just any old PR system
would do.
Councillor Gorrie for one has harped on continuously about the fairness of the
single-transferable-vote method. He is quite right.
So are we to have that? Not a chance. Donald's ducks chickened out. They and
Labour did a dirty deal and adopted the additional-member system. Thus, in a
parliament of 129, we are to have 56 members who will be elected only by the
party hacks. Getting your name on the list will be better than a council job in
Monklands.
Mrs Marilyne McLaren, Donald's left-hand woman, told me on Tuesday this system
was ``reasonably proportional''. A bit like becoming slightly pregnant, one
assumes.
The Lib-Dems wanted a bigger parliament. They lost. The Convention told us they
would impose gender balance. They won't.
We have still to hear the fate of the Secretary of State for Scotland and his
ministers in these exciting new arrangements. Will they even exist? If so, what
are they to be doing - carrying messages from Regent Road to Westminster,
pleading for English hand-outs, trying to persuade foreign companies to locate
in the highest-taxed area of Britain?
The English backlash to these arrangements will not be long in the making. It
will occur, even to the dimmest honourable member, that the Scots are trying to
have their oatcake and eat it too.
We are already over-represented at Westminster. Now we are to have our own
parliament, partly paid for by the rest of the UK, in addition. And we can
still vote on English legislation.
Those are the fundamental flaws in this scheme for an assembly. If it is set up
I do not believe a future Conservative government would ever dismantle the
parliament.
Much more likely would be a move to cut the Scottish MPs and reduce the
contribution from the Treasury. Try keeping the tax at 3p extra then.
The Fraser survey was based on the opinions of fewer than one in five of
Scottish businesses but we should not condemn it for that. Nor should any
Conservatives think they can sit smugly back.
There was considerable dissatisfaction with the status quo. People from all
walks of life feel that the Government is too remote, that decisions should be
taken nearer the grass roots.
We need new, innovative ideas to counter that feeling.
I could be wrong, of course, but I rather think the Secretary of State may have
something to say on the subject this week. Time for another survey, perhaps?
</TEXT>
