<HEADLINE>Meyer earnings take knock Opec extends freeze to buoy world prices</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241324</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Vienna, Wednesday - Opec today agreed to freeze its output quota into an
unprecedented third year in an attempt to buoy sagging world oil prices.
A ministerial conference of the Organisation of the Petroleum Exporting
Countries ended in an accord to stay with a ceiling on total output set in 1993
at 24.52 million barrels daily for six more months to June next year.
Oil futures prices showed little reaction. Although they may find support for
now, market experts doubted if they would rally strongly.
The Opec meeting ended with no decision on Gabon's wish to leave the cartel
unless it is excused full annual membership fees. This will be discussed when
the organisation meets again in June.
Weak prices below $17 per barrel, compared with an Opec goal of $21, had left
little option for the 11 participating ministers but to extend output quotas.
Ministers also had to address the problem of the alleged quota violations by
several of the 12 members including Venezuela, Qatar, and Nigeria that have
lifted actual Opec volume some one million barrels daily above the agreed
ceiling.
But a communique made no mention of quota compliance.
Geoff Pyne, an energy economist at banking house UBS, felt that Opec should
ideally have cut production.
The quota rollover ``is bad news for producers because prices may soften,'' he
said. ``But a crash is unlikely. Industry conditions have changed.''
</TEXT>
