<HEADLINE>Lease deals go flexible</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By Stewart McIntosh Property Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241325</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW flexible lease terms are being introduced north of the Border in a bid to
attract business start-ups into industrial premises. London-based CINIO Estates
believes that the traditional 25-year property lease is frightening off new
businesses which are reluctant to see themselves lumbered with a factory which
is no longer required, or of being unable to buy a property if the business
expands rapidly.
Now CINIO, which recently purchased some 352,750 sq ft of light industrial
space from Glenrothes Development Corporation, has introduced a new flexi-lease
scheme for potential occupiers. The scheme allows new businesses to take short
leases of units at competitive rentals. The initial lease term is for two
years, accompanied by an option to extend the lease or to buy the unit outright
at a predetermined price, if preferred. The incentive is available at CINIO's
Bankhead and Eastfield industrial estates in the Fife new town.
John Sims, managing director of The IO Group, one of the joint venture partners
of CINIO Estates, says: ``At the tail end of a recession we have to stimulate
new business more than ever before, but many potential start up companies,
often with technically brilliant ideas, are scared off by the stringent terms
of traditional leases.
``With flexi-lease we have ended one of the main anxieties of the new venture -
either being stuck with a factory lease when it is no longer required, or
conversely being unable to buy the property if the business takes off.
``We have listened to a lot of people across the UK in devising this scheme,
and we know it is something that the market place badly needs.''
Several units have been let since CINIO initiated its refurbishment programme
in Glenrothes, with new occupiers including Amtrak, Valhope Ltd, and Ryehill
Wines. Other tenants on the estates include United Artists, Apricot Computers,
and Jewsons. The joint letting agents are Gooch &amp; Wagstaff and Graham &amp; Sibbald.
Michael Court of Graham &amp; Sibbald says: ``The inquiry level has noticeably
increased for these premises since the refurbishment has been completed, and we
are finding that potential occupiers welcome being able to tailor the lease
terms to suit their individual requirements.''
The initiative has been welcomed by Joe Noble, director of property and
environment at Fife Enterprise. He says: ''Flexible lease lengths can be
important to expanding companies and therefore this innovation in Glenrothes is
to be welcomed.''
</TEXT>
