<DOCNO>GH951123-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rents and prices hinder building</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241326</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE of Scotland's most important industrial locations has no new factory or
warehouse space under construction. A combination of low rents and high land
prices is hindering development in West Lothian, according to a new analysis of
Lothian Region's industrial property sector by surveyors King Sturge &amp; Co.
The report reveals that although West Lothian remains one of the prime
industrial locations north of the Border, speculative development is still
being viewed as uneconomic.
Lothian's highest industrial rents are being achieved in South Gyle and
Sighthill at #5.15 per sq ft. Assuming a land value of #125,500 per acre, the
surveyors calculate that a rent of #4.50 per sq ft should justify new
development and provide an acceptable profit for the developer.
Lothian Region contains some 20.4 million sq ft of industrial floorspace of
which only 30% is situated in Edinburgh, while half the space is in West
Lothian.
The survey analyses the stock by size and reveals that over 80% of all
industrial units offer less than 11,000 sq ft, with two-thirds of the space
being less than 5400 sq ft.
The late 1970s and early 1980s saw a boom in industrial development in
Edinburgh, a trend which dropped off sharply in the 1990s. This has resulted in
over 55% of industrial units in Edinburgh being built in the 1980s, accounting
for 36% of the total industrial floorspace. The lower vacancy rates of 1990s
accommodation indicate greater demand for modern space - only 3.6% of
industrial space built since 1990 is vacant.
Some 8.1% of Edinburgh's industrial floorspace is vacant. The region's highest
vacancy rate is in Midlothian where 11% of the space is available. King Sturge
points to a continued demand for units at the larger end of the market and is
optimistic about the Lothian market's future.
Demand for industrial accommodation has improved over the past 12 to 18 months,
but not sufficiently to raise rental values enough to give developers
confidence to build new property. The situation is exacerbated by a shortage of
suitable development sites, especially in the area west of Edinburgh.
Meanwhile, on the investment side of Lothian's industrial market, deals
involving nearly 1.3 million sq ft of space have been concluded by surveyors
Ryden. The firm has completed five major transactions involving the sale or
acquisition of industrial buildings for almost #7.5m.
Acting on behalf on Macdonald Martin Distilleries plc, producers of
Glenmorangie whisky, Ryden has acquired the Bells bottling complex at East
Mains Industrial Estate in Broxburn.
The facility, which provides more than 840,000 sq ft of bottling, production
and office space on a site area of 30 acres, cost #4.25m.
</TEXT>
