<HEADLINE>Reed papers sold to Scots</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS STONE City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241327</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MANAGEMENT buyout team headed by two Scots has bought Reed Regional
Newspapers (RRN), which has 129 principal titles, from Anglo-Dutch media group
Reed Elsevier in a #205m deal.
The buyout team is backed by Kohiber Kravis Rovers (KKR), a New-York based
venture capital buy-out specialist, in its first European acquisition.
Jim Brown, who has been chief executive of Reed's newspaper division for five
years, will be chairman and chief executive, while Paul Davidson will be deputy
chief executive of the new company. Finance for the deal has been sourced by
Glenisla Group, the privately held corporation backed by KKR and headed by
former Grand Metropolitan deputy chairman Ian Martin.
The six-strong buy-out team beat off several rival bidders to secure the
company and together will have a ``substantial'' stake in the operation. The
129 separate principal titles, a combination of regional evenings, weeklies and
free papers, have an aggregate circulation of around 4.1m copies per issue and
7.5m readers. Among the titles is the Worcester Journal, the world's oldest
newspaper at 305 years.
KKR said its philosophy in acquiring companies is to become a partner with
management, offering a buy-out team a significant equity ownership stake and
providing support and advice at the board level to assist the company in
building long-term value.
It said the partnership with KKR will create an independent company out of a
larger business and provide the capital and resources.The new company, yet to
be named though likely to be Prospect Media Group, is expected to take over the
business by the end of the year and would ``be looking for sensible
acquisitions in the local paper field,'' said Mr Brown.
Commenting on the acquisition, its attraction and future potential, Scott M
Stuart, general partner of KKR, said: ``RRN has a strong management team led by
Jim Brown with extensive experience of the regional newspaper industry. Most of
the senior management have five or more years experience at board level and
have been the architects in growing the business.
``Already one of the four largest publishers of free newspapers in the UK, RRN
is at the forefront of the development of quality free newpapers, a sector in
which RRN is a market leader. With KKR's backing and support, the management
team is now well placed to accelerate further the growth of the business.
Regional newspapers have particularly good prospects for growth both
organically and through acquisition.''
Mr Brown said: ``The management team were greatly impressed with KKR,
particularly their ambitions to grow the company. We know of their track record
of being patient investors and we are confident that working together with them
we will be seeeing quite a success story in the future.''
Reed Elsevier's divestments of its consumer businesses, the majority of which
were put up for sale in July, has so far raised #685m. It is part of the
group's strategy to focus on more profitable professional publications and
business information.
In addition to the RRN deal, four transactions have been agreed - three in the
Netherlands and one in the US. Perracombinatie, a publisher of Dutch daily
newspapers, said yesterday that it had completed the acquisition of
Dagbladunie, which published two big Dutch newspapers, NRC Handelsblad and
Algemeen Dagblad, for Reed Elsevier.
This is expected to be completed on December 29 to raise #346m. Other
agreements include the sale of a Dutch regional newspaper and also six Dutch
consumer magazines. In the US, K111 Communications agreed to buy the consumer
magazines of Chaners Publishing.
The five transactions result in an exceptional gain of around #385m but this
will be reduced by the non-cash exceptional loss which Reed Elsevier expects to
make on the sale of Reed Consumer Books which is already at an advanced stage.
Restructuring charges relating to the consumer business divestments as well as
further exceptional losses from the planned disposal of other non-core
activities will also reduce the exceptional gain. Meanwhile, current trading of
the group remains fully in line with its expectations in August when it said it
expected further growth in the second half of the year.
</TEXT>
