<HEADLINE>Chairman who started career as a reporter</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241328</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN asked about his leading the management buyout of Reed Regional Newspapers
(RRN) from Reed Elsevier, Jim Brown was quick yesterday to point out that two
Scots were behind the deal - himself and Paul Davidson.
Mr Davidson will be deputy chief executive of the new company. Mr Brown, who
has been chief executive at RRN for five years will add chairman to his title
when the deal is completed at the end of December.
Now 60, and from Ayr, he cut his teeth in journalism on the Ayrshire Post,
following his brother Ian on to the paper after leaving Ayr Academy at 16. Ian,
now retired, later became editor of the Scottish Daily Express.
Jim Brown did a six-year stint in as a journalist on the Glasgow Evening
Citizen then moved to the management side of the business at Edinburgh for
Thomson where he was promotions manager.
He then became general circulation manager in Aberdeen for two to three years
before setting off on his travels again, working on various papers before
moving to the Manchester Evening News where he was circulation director and
charman of two groups of newsagents.
Thomson then claimed him back and in 1980 he was a main board circulation
director and after that managing director of Thames Valley Newspapers.
Ten years ago he was headhunted by RRN. Except for his first job on the
Ayrshire Post, he can proudly claim that he has always been headhunted.
Mr Brown, who in his youth found time to play rugby for West of Scotland, is
coy about the exact stake the management team will have in the new company
except that it is ``substantial''.
Any possible flotation on the stock market is still a long way off. ``We've got
to learn to swim first,'' he said. First priorities will be to expand the
business, and acquisitions are in prospect.
Family connections with newspapers are strong. Apart from his brother, the
editor of the Ayr Advertiser is a relative and one of his daughters works as a
journalist on the Daily Mail in London. Another daughter is in newspaper
advertising.
Mr Brown tells the story of how he ``snatched'' the notorious Walter Scott
Ellis outside the Glasgow High Court during a riot which followed the not
proven verdict, after interviews, it seemed, had been promised to everyone.
The car was waiting and he bundled Ellis into it, only to discover it was the
Daily Record car, not the Evening Citizen.
Fortunately the other car had followed and a transfer was managed and Ellis was
rushed to a hotel hide-out at Loch Lomond. A phone call was made but Mr Brown's
brother at the Express had tapped the line and Express journalists had to be
repelled.
Mr Davidson, 40, the deputy chief excutive is from Govan and started his
newspaper career with Thomson in Aberdeen before setting up his own advertising
training business.
Both men's wives come from Kilmarnock but, said Mr Brown, this is pure
coincidence.
</TEXT>
