<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>UTILITIES Heavy demand for National Grid</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241329</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE National Grid, the electricity transmission network which is to be floated
next month, began trading in the grey market yesterday at 230p.
In heavy trading of around 15 million shares, the price rose quickly to 240p
but ended off its best levels at 228p, but still valued in excess of #3500m.
Although most City analysts believe the shares are worth about 200p, heavy
demand from financial institutions is expected to buoy the share price for some
time.
The shares are expected to be a solid if not spectacular investment. While
there will be a large stock overhang, only 44% of the shares will be on offer,
the business is a monopoly.
Four directors of National Grid are sitting on a #1.3m-plus potential cash pile
since the start of share trading. Chairman David Jeffries and John Uttley, Eric
Chefneux and Colin Gibson together own 590,000 shares in the company, which
have earned them more than #300,000 in dividends. Mr Uttley, the finance
director, has said he will donate his dividend to charity.
The National Grid is being demerged from the 12 regional electricity companies
(RECs) of England and Wales. Only six of the companies are committed to
distributing their holdings to their shareholders.
Midlands Electricity may decide to distribute its 9% holding. REC shareholders
will be asked to approve the Grid distribution at extraordinary meetings on
December 8. Each REC has said that it will cut domestic charges from next April
by a one-off #50 as part of the Grid demerger.
The National Grid increased its interim profits by 25% to #335.5m in the six
months ended September 30. The profit growth came despite increased losses from
its Energis telephone company of #40.1m, up from #19.2m previously. Profits
from the transmission business, which accounts for around 5% of consumer bills,
rose by #38m to #356.8m.
Turnover from continuing businesses rose by #70m to #706m. The directors have
declared an interim dividend of #70m up from #54m previously.
The interim dividend is expected to represent around 40% of total net dividends
and will be paid in February each year. Capital expenditure in the six months
was #107.7m, down from #186.9m previously.
The decrease was mainly a result of lower expenditure in Energis and the
transmission business, with the latter due to delays in obtaining planning
approvals.
Although the business is thought to have scope to cut operating costs by as
much as 30%, political and regulatory worries could dampen some of the
enthusiasm for the stock.
</TEXT>
