<HEADLINE>No tears for the woes of Windsor</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jimmy Reid</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241330</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ACCORDING to the press we are all worry-ing about Charles and Diana and the
future of the monarchy. Well, include me out, and I'm a born-again worrier. I
worry about the un-employed, our pensioners, the health service and the sick,
the plight of the Ogonis in Nigeria. I worry about Scottish football and a
myriad of other things you might consider unworthy of worry. I even worry about
not worrying. And say to my-self, ``Why aren't you worry-ing? Who gave you the
right not to worry?''
But confess I must, I've nev-er worried about the royal fam-ily and their
hangers-on. Maybe it's because I don't give a tosser about them and their
lackeys. If the word parasite has any meaning it is for this shower. Princess
Margaret has boozed her way through life, mouthing obscenities, in a golden
carriage, at our ex-pense, and those who get apo-plectic at so-called social
security scroungers say nay a word.
The suffocating snobbery surrounding royalty with its bowing and scraping
subverts our society. The democratic el-ement within our parliamenta-ry system
is called the House of Commons. Last week as the Queen's Speech was being read
in the Lords, the MPs from the Commons stood while their Lordships, unelected
to a man, and a few women, lounged on their seats looking down at them. The
upstart MPs knew their place and deferred like mad.
The Queen wore a crown dec-orated by the jewels of Henry the Eighth who when
tired of a wife had her put down or put away. A power Nicholas Soames no doubt
wishes had been pre-served for monarchs and heirs to the throne. It would save
a lot of hassle. Ta ta Di - off you go to a nunnery, that's a girl.
Like Nicholas Soames, Henry the Eighth was a man of con-spicuous consumption,
but be-fore the phrase was invented. This paragon of the Christian faith
founded the Church of England, so that he could have his way with a string of
young ladies. Among our Queen's many titles is Defender of the Faith. Whose
faith? Henry's.
The British class system with the monarch at the top has made common a term of
abuse. To call a person com-mon means that they manifest the attributes of the
common people. Tut, tut. That will nev-er do. And, of course, common ownership
is bad. Against God's design. Better by far that everything is owned by the
few, as it was in the past, and so it is being done again.
Have I no tears for Charles and Diana? Not really, but at heart I'm a softie
and have a little sympathy. They are vic-tims of a system but it's their
system. Millions more are vic-tims of this system. The prince and princess were
cocooned in wealth from birth. They know nothing of the self-esteem shat-tering
problems of youngsters who were born to fail in all things through poverty and
lack of opportunity.
Their wings were clipped be-fore they could fly, their youth-ful fancies turned
to dust as a lifetime on the dole and social security beckoned. If only a small
percentage of the ava-lanche of concern for the spoiled brats of the Windsors
were shown to the really hard-done-by youngsters in our soci-ety, then maybe,
just maybe, Britain would become a bit more civilised.
And if Diana's avowed con-cern for the common people is genuine why send her
son to Eton? Why not a local compre-hensive? Will he be allowed to move in
circles beyond a taw-dry circle of rich nincompoops? What are the chances of
him meeting and marrying a lass from Castlemilk? Zilch. He will move in the
same society as moved his father, whose mis-tress, now divorced, lives in a
house worth nearly a million quid.
Few of these people have ever earned anything. They've inherited wealth often
based on the robbery, in years long gone, of the common lands of the common
people. Or given by a king to a bastard son. Our aristocratic blue bloods, as
dis-tinct from our working-class blue noses, come from a long line of thieving
illegitimates.
They are proud of this lineage and claim governmen-tal privileges through the
House of Lords and the monar-chy because of these fore-bears. It's like Al
Capone's offspring claiming access to the US Government because Al was a
latter-day robber baron. If they had any decency they would be ashamed of their
an-cestors and seek to make amends. They could then take their place among us,
share our worries, and then legitimately make claims on our love.
In the meantime, as our press sobs for the plight of the poor Windsors, may I
remind you of the words of an old Scottish Presbyterian hymn: ``When wilt thou
save the people oh Lord of mercy when, the Peo-ple Lord, the People, not
thrones or crowns but men.''
TAGGART without Taggart is like Hamlet without the prince, or bam without the
boozle. Last week it started with a summation of the story so far. The
complexities were bewildering and made War and Peace seem like the Beano. More
people had already died than at the battles of the Somme, the Bulge, and the
Boyne, put together.
I switched off. A bad sleeper counting sheep, I don't fancy counting corpses,
trying to re-member names, who did what to whom, and what for, or who gave
somebody what for.
Now I don't want to give Taggart what for. The camera work is brilliant, the
produc-tion gave Glasgow a delightful gritty ambience which is nearer the truth
than the som-bre starkness favoured by ``re-alist'' film-makers. The script was
never trite. But Mark McManus was fundamental to the format.
It didn't matter if you totted up the people topped in the se-ries and found it
exceeded the population of Glasgow. Nobody was counting. The lived-in face of a
decent wee man confront-ing mind-boggling complex-ities, while people dropped
like flies all around, engaged the sympathy of viewers. No smart-alec dick, he
solved murders that would have beat Sherlock Holmes and Hercule Poirot.
Without Mark it's another police series. The plots become implausible. People
start counting. If not rethought, with a new format, the series will fizzle
out. A pity, for it reached parts no other Scottish series had reached. The
Chi-nese loved it. Tongs ya bass.
</TEXT>
