<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Small, Hendry waste no time</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241333</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SNOOKER
AFTER John Higgins' quickfire 9-1 win over Alain Robidoux on Tuesday, fellow
Scots Chris Small and Stephen Hendry also raced into the third round of the
Royal Liver Assurance UK Championship at Preston yesterday.
Small, the world No.62 from Edinburgh, beat Basingstoke's Mark Flowerdew 9-2.
``The money will come in handy, because my girlfriend is expecting a baby next
month,'' said the Scot, who reached the semi-finals of last season's Regal
Welsh Open. He next meets the 1993 UK winner, Ronnie O'Sullivan, for a
quarter-final place.
Hendry, 6-2 up, completed a 9-3 win last night over Anthony Hamilton, the world
No.31.
Nigel Bond reeled off five frames in a row to beat Tony Knowles 9-4. Dennis
Taylor, now 46, produced a vintage comeback from 8-5 down to win 9-8 against
world No.8, Welshman Darren Morgan.
Steve Lee, conqueror of Steve Davis, beat Neal Foulds 9-7 but 17-year-old Paul
Hunter could not follow up his upset win over Alan McManus. He led 5-3 but won
only one more frame in losing 9-6 to Welshman Wayne Jones. Results:
C Small (Sco) beat M Flowerdew (Eng) 9-2, J Parrott (Eng) beat W Thorne (Eng)
9-3, R O'Sullivan (Eng) beat P Davies (Wales) 9-4, D Taylor (N Ire) beat D
Morgan (Wales) 9-8, S Hendry (Sco) beat A Hamilton (Eng) 9-3, N Bond (Eng) beat
