<TEXT>
SWIMMING
ABERDEEN Swimming Club's refusal to join a new development initiative within
the city has put it on a collision course with the Scottish association.
Following the decision to stay independent, the club has been informed that it
will be barred from using the Bon Accord pool, thereby losing half its training
time.
Club officials, parents, and swimmers are upset, and Martyn Woodroffe,
Scotland's director of swimming, faces a hard time at a specially convened
meeting in Aberdeen this evening.
``We'll listen to what he has to say, but there are a lot of questions to be
answered,'' said Eileen Adams, head coach of an Aberdeen club that won this
year's Scottish age-group championship and finished top Scottish club at the
recent Cumbernauld international meet.
``It is a case of joining the scheme or being squeezed out. Bon Accord is the
best facility and, who knows, perhaps the next move will be to pull the plug on
us using the school pools.''
The new scheme is a partnership involving the SASA, City of Aberdeen Council,
and the Scottish Sports Council, and a head coach, Alastair Johnson, assistant
at Stockport Metro, has been appointed to start the 25,000 plus post on 11
December.
Adams contends that instead of evicting Aberdeen, the SASA should have provided
assistance to one of the few prospering clubs. ``We're easily among the top six
in Scotland and we're very happy with what we've got,'' Adams said.
</TEXT>
