<HEADLINE>Feed costs could reach new highs warns UKASTA</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT ROSS Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241338</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITISH livestock producers could be placed under unprecedented pressure by
increased feed costs over the next few months, it has been claimed.
The United Kingdom Agricultural Supply Trade Association fears price rises are
inevitable as world markets for grain and proteins tighten. UKASTA director
general Jim Reed said: ``Experts in the farming and feedstuffs industries can
already foresee most ration prices having to rise by at least another 15% over
the winter, simply to absorb the cost increases already hitting us, let alone
any more which may be in the pipeline.
``UK and European grain prices are already at a 20-year high, dragged up by a
world market shorter of cereals than many of us can ever remember,'' he said.
Mr Reed pointed out that protein prices were now following a sharp upward
trend, with high quality, home-produced rape seed meal in particularly strong
demand due to the very high price of imported alternatives. ``Inevitably this
has driven up the price of all other ingredients in sympathy,'' he added.
Clear reasons for the upward trend had been identified, he said. US soya
production was well below last year's level, with prices approaching 20% more.
World fish meal supplies were also down and prices were fully 30% higher.
Steadily rising demand for vegetable oils and protein meals in developing
countries was helping to push protein prices very much higher across the board.
``Our concern has to date been for the hard-pressed pig and poultry producers,
but we must now recognise that the effects will also be severe for dairy, beef
and sheep producers,'' Mr Reed said.
``No livestock sector will be immune from the cost-push effect. Unfortunately,
buyers of livestock products are largely unaware of these world events which
will mean a much higher cost for feeding animals.''
UKASTA noted the trend in rising raw material prices earlier this year and
lobbied for the European Commission to reduce set-aside sharply and to manage
European markets to restrain prices as far as possible. The cautious measures
taken so far had had little effect, Mr Reed said.
The whole industry should now be lobbying Brussels to renew its efforts, he
added. UKASTA deputy president Pat Lake would be leading a delegation to meet
commission officials to explore the scope for further action to safeguard the
livestock industries throughout Europe.
</TEXT>
