MANCHESTER was the city of celebration last night, with United narrowing the
gap at the top of the Premiership to three points, while City moved off the
bottom of the table.
Brian McClair inspired United's 4-0 win at Coventry that plunged Ron Atkinson's
side to the foot of the division. The Scot struck twice, with Denis Irwin
opening the scoring and David Beckham putting the match beyond the home side.
The victory was a boost to United's city neighbours, who took full advantage by
snatching a last-gasp 1-0 win over Wimbledon. Niall Quinn netted his first
league strike of the campaign with only a minute left after Wimbledon had
frustrated their fellow strugglers all night.
Bolton missed out on their first away point in the Premiership when Chelsea won
3-2 at Stamford Bridge. The visitors led after 10 minutes but David Lee
equalised five minutes later and Gareth Hall put Glenn Hoddle's side in front
just before the hour.
Scott Green looked to have secured a point for Wanderers after 68 minutes but
Newton's header kept the pressure on the Burnden Park management team of Roy
McFarland and Colin Todd.
q AC MILAN coach Fabio Capello is thinking of switching clubs next year after
five seasons that made the Italian side the leading lights in Europe.
Capello claims that he has been offered a two-year extension by Milan, the
Serie A leaders, but was unhappy with certain clauses. He said he had until
April 30 to make up his mind.
Speculation has been mounting that the club was hunting for a replacement and
had several candidates in mind, including Italy manager Arrigo Sacchi.
q COLOMBIAN defender Albeiro Pico Hernandez, of Club Envigado, was shot dead by
unidentified gumen yesterday in the northwest city of Medellin.
The gunmen is said to have shot seven rounds into 23-year-old Pico as he was
leaving his home for an early-morning training session.
