<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP alleges threat from councillor Confrontation outside inquiry room</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241345</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN English Tory MP claimed yesterday that he and his family had been
``threatened'' with a visit by the leader of Monklands District Council,
Councillor Jim Brooks, after giving evidence at the government inquiry into
alleged corruption at the Labour-controlled authority.
Speaking at Question Time in the Commons yesterday, Mr David Shaw - one of the
strongest critics of the council - used parliamentary privilege when he told
the House: ``I have just come back from giving evidence to the Monklands
inquiry this morning in Scotland.
``On my departing from the inquiry, I was given the usual threat by the leader
of the council, who insisted on threatening to visit myself and my family.''
Mr Shaw, who represents Dover, pressed Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth: ``Do
you consider that these sort of people should be in charge of councils in
Scotland, and do you not think the Labour Party has a lot to answer for on the
failings of local government in Scotland?''
Mr Forsyth replied: ``I am sure you will understand why I am not in a position
to comment on the remarks which you have made.''
But he added, ``in defence of the Labour Party'', that he was sure it was as
anxious as Tories ``to ensure the highest standards of conduct in local
government''.
Mr Brooks last night denied that he had in any way threatened Mr Shaw and
claimed the MP had made the allegation because he did not like being called
``Davie''.
He said: ``There is no way I threatened him. I was just teasing him. I said we
would go down to his area to see how good it was because he is up here all the
time. I think he's a silly man.''
The ruling Labour group on Monklands District Council was suspended in June by
party leader Tony Blair following allegations of ``jobs for the boys'',
nepotism, and sectarian discrimination.
For the Opposition, Mr John McAllion protested in the House of Commons that
``ill-tempered, ill-informed, and inaccurate attacks on elected Scottish
councils by the likes of Mr Shaw merely serve to weaken an already very weak
Government case in Scotland, particularly when he in Scotland this morning
admitted that his allegations were based upon circumstantial evidence and
anonymous correspondence''.
A confrontation between Mr Brooks and Mr Shaw occurred in a small foyer outside
the inquiry room at the council headquarters in Coatbridge after Mr Shaw had
given evidence, in which he described Monklands as the most corrupt local
authority in Britain.
Mr Brooks got up from the public seats and walked briskly out of the chamber
before asking Mr Shaw if he had been paid to raise questions on Monklands in
the House of Commons.
Mr Shaw replied: ``No, I was not. Were you paid?''
Mr Brooks then said he and several other councillors would be visiting Mr
Shaw's Dover constituency at the New Year.
Mr Shaw said: ``Remember to bring your company books.''
Afterwards, Mr Brooks said he only wanted to ask Mr Shaw if he had accepted
money to raise questions in the House of Commons ``like some of his Tory
colleagues''.
He added that he and other councillors would be visiting the MP's constituency
at New Year for ``a party''.
Mr Brooks was not available later to comment on Mr Shaw's ``threat'' claims
made in the House of Commons.
Mr Shaw admitted at the inquiry that he had no firm evidence involving
individual cases of nepotism but said there was an ``overwhelming weight'' of
circumstantial evidence which in itself was enough to condemn the council.
His own investigation had uncovered more than 20 cases of councillors'
relatives in jobs at Monklands.
He also admitted that the high profile of two local Labour MPs - the late
Labour leader John Smith (Monklands East) and the then Shadow Scots Secretary
Tom Clarke (Monklands West) - was a factor in his constant attacks on the
authority.
The inquiry before Mr William Nimmo Smith, QC, continues.
q A controversial inquiry into allegations against the council by Professor
Robert Black, whose findings were released in June, was said last night to have
cost less than half the #50,000 the council said would be available.
Mr Archie Strang, the council's director of finance, said a total of #23,000
had been paid for the report, adding that although costs had been on public
display, he had received no comments.
Mr Strang said: ``I do not know how much these things should cost. I'm not in a
position to say it was cheap or expensive.''
</TEXT>
