<HEADLINE>Chancellor taunts Labour as he pledges Budget aimed at a recovery `that is for keeps' Clarke and Brown in tax battle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241346</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHANCELLOR Kenneth Clarke yesterday set out the economic principles that will
define his Budget next week and ``make Britain the enterprise centre of
Europe'' by reiterating his target of a 20p standard rate of tax.
Unable to give details of a Budget that is expected to include vote-winning tax
cuts, Mr Clarke concentrated on attacking Labour. He described Shadow
Chancellor Gordon Brown's plan to reduce the lowest rate of tax to 10p as
``bizarre and ill-judged.''
The Tories were committed to reducing borrowing to zero and the share of public
expenditure to below 40% of Gross Domestic Product, he said, and to keeping
inflation below a target of 2.5%.
The last day of the Queen's Speech debate turned into a showdown between Mr
Clarke and Mr Brown. The two were evenly matched, Mr Brown's quick-fire wit
against Mr Clarke's bar-room bluster.
Mr Clarke accused Labour of producing light entertainment rather than policies
of its own. At one point, he implored someone - anyone - on the Labour benches
to stand and explain Labour's policy on inflation, interest rates and tax.
``Everybody I meet in the Rose and Crown tells me what they want me to do with
the Budget. (Mr Brown) is the only man . . . with no advice,'' he said. ``It's
not an impossible question on the eve of the Budget to ask the Labour Party
what do they think the basic rate of tax should be,'' he said.
By contrast, he said, he would introduce a Budget ``dedicated to making this
country the enterprise centre of Europe'' based on ``the clear consistent
policies we have had in place for delivering a recovery that is for keeps and
which will increase living standards for families year after year.''
However Mr Brown said nothing the Government could do in the Budget would
restore the 21 consecutive tax increases imposed since the 1992 election.
``This is the Tory strategy to try to win the people of this country - but a
tax cut every five years can never make up for the 21 tax rises in the years
between,'' he said.
Mr Clarke said the only policies Labour had were to introduce a minimum wage
and sign up for the Social Chapter of the Maastricht Treaty on employment
legislation. These would ``drive unemployment up and destroy jobs.''
Mr Brown said the Government would be judged on its claim, made by Mr Major on
Tuesday, that tax increases had been introduced to ``protect people who were
vulnerable. Tell that to the pensioners, the weakest and frailest in the
country who had VAT rises imposed upon them by the Government.''
Mr Malcolm Bruce, for the Liberal Democrats, said: ``There was a time when
Government Ministers on the Tory side took pride in the fact that they were the
sound financial managers of the economy.
``But they no longer listen to their own advice because the General Election is
pressing hard down upon them and good economic management is less important
than kidding the voters that you can somehow deliver them a miracle.''
The Government's legislative programme for the last full session of Parliament
before the General Election was later backed when Labour's attack on the Tories
over their stewardship of the economy was defeated by 298 votes to 271, a
Government majority of 27.
q Twenty Labour MPs want the rich to pay more tax, according to a new survey. A
higher income tax rate should be imposed on the top 10% of taxpayers, the MPs
said in a survey published in today's edition of the left-wing Tribune
newspaper.
q A new opinion poll shows another increase in Labour's huge lead over the
Tories. The Mori poll in the Times today puts the Tories on 26% (compared with
27% at the end of October), with Labour remaining on 56% , a lead of 30 points.
The Liberal Democrats are on 14%, one point higher than a month ago.
</TEXT>
