<HEADLINE>Firm refuses to insure bull-bar vehicles</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241347</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOTORING organisations in Scotland last night welcomed an insurance company's
decision to stop offering cover for vehicles fitted with bull bars.
The decision, announced yesterday by CGA Direct, makes it the first in Britain
to take a hardline stance against the bars, which are fitted to many off-road
vehicles used solely for town driving.
A number of people have been killed or seriously injured in accidents involving
vehicles fitted with the accessories
CGA, which is based in Sussex and underwrites policies on behalf of Ganminster,
a French-owned company, said there were social and financial reasons behind its
decision.
Mr Paul Purdy, CGA's marketing director, said: ``There is conclusive evidence
that they increase the chance of injury and death to pedestrians and other
motorists.
``The bars do more damage to other vehicles in collisions, so claims involving
cars fitted with bull bars tend to be higher.''
Ms Sue Nicholson, of the RAC in Scotland, said: ``We would support anything
which encourages the removal of bull bars fitted only for cosmetic reasons.''
The AA also gave the announcement a broad welcome. A spokeswoman said: ``We do
not believe that drivers with existing bars should be punished but we are in
favour of them being phased out.''
Welsh MP Paul Flynn, who has been campaigning against the bars, said: ``This is
a major step forward in the cause of safety on our roads. Hopefully, this will
be the catalyst which will force other insurance companies to follow suit.
``These are bully bars worn by macho owners which transform their vehicles into
killing machines. They are totally cosmetic and have no place in our towns.''
The Association of British Insurers said it would not oppose new legislation,
but was not campaigning for change.
</TEXT>
