<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Silence at the local when it's his shout</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>stuart trotter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Commons Sketch</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975241348</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN the Chancellor of the Exchequer drops into the saloon bar of the Rose and
Crown, he told us yesterday, he is bombarded not so much with cries of
``What'll you have, Ken'' as with suggestions about what he should put in his
Budget.
A convivial soul who likes his pint and a good cigar, Mr Clarke cannot help
noticing this taciturn chap who is noted for never joining in with suggestions
of his own. ``It's as if he thinks that talking about economic policy and
taxation policy is not allowed in polite company,'' Ken chortled.
This tall, dark, taciturn figure turned out to be the Shadow Chancellor, Mr
Gordon Brown, who, Mr Clarke surmised, could be a Trappist monk. The
improbability of a Trappist monk regularly frequenting the Chancellor's
hostelry or, indeed, representing Dunfermline East in the Commons, indicated
this was a mere flight of fancy, something which Mr Clarke, who never seems
oppressed by the number-crunching aspects of his job, is readier to indulge in
than most of his predecessors.
Mr Brown might observe that this is because the Chancellor is not a details
man. Mr Brown is. An admission in a Government White Paper that Britain has
slipped from 13th to 18th in the world prosperity league, is snapped up, but
the Shadow Chancellor can delve much deeper than that.
No privatised industry chief can hope to escape Mr Brown and his research
postulants discovering how much his generous pension arrangements are actually
going to cost the company, the shareholders, and the taxpayer.
The Shadow Chancellor lugs into the Chamber an impressive array of files from
which might be plucked a statistic troublesome to the Government or a speech by
the Chancellor when he was something else entirely, advocating policies with
which he either does not now agree or, at least, given the current climate of
the Conservative Party, does not wish to say he agrees.
However, Mr Clarke is resilient and not easily abashed. ``I am one of the last
survivors of the long march,'' he declared proudly. On the scenario being
painted by Mr Brown, this was a Tory hike from being the party of One Nation to
the provider of goodies for small selfish interest groups.
For the Shadow Chancellor is, and was yesterday, quite eloquent about many
things. Where he turns taciturn is when it comes to diving into one of the
folders and producing a taxation policy.
One minute he is denouncing the high level of unemployment, Government waste
and totting up ``the bills of economic failure'' with the fervour of a
revivalist preacher. But, ask ``Is current borrowing, current spending, current
interest rates too high, too low, or about right?'' and, without so much as a
clap of thunder, the preacher has metamorphosed into a Trappist monk devoted to
his vow of silence.
Mr Clarke asked the questions, achieved the metamorphosis, then read out the
favourable economic statistics about which Mr Brown had adopted the Trappist
approach. In a forlorn bid to try to make the Shadow Chancellor feel small, he
then praised the Liberal Democrats. They have the courage of their convictions.
They produced an alternative Budget for all to see and analyse. ``They're not
in danger of becoming the next Government,'' Mr Brown might have thought.
Challenged by Mr Peter Hain (Neath - Lab.) to commit himself to producing a
detailed alternative Budget if he became Shadow Chancellor in a year or two, Mr
Clarke behaved like the man in the saloon bar who realises it's his round next
and made an excuse for moving elsewhere.
</TEXT>
