<HEADLINE>Clinton set to delay visit to Britain and Ireland</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241349</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
US PRESIDENT Bill Clinton is almost certain to postpone by one day the start of
his planned trip to Britain, Ulster and the Republic of Ireland next week, it
emerged last night.
The delay will enable him to court American support to send US military
personnel to join the Nato peacekeeping force in Bosnia.
This is bound to lead to a major re-scheduling of the President's engagements
which include an address to both Houses of Parliament on Wednesday.
Downing Street said last night it ``entirely understood'' the reason behind the
delay.
There have been hopes that President Clinton can use his influence to try to
end the deadlock in the Ulster peace process.
He is now expected to curtail his visit to Ireland, visiting only Dublin after
engagements in Northern Ireland and Britain and calling off a schedule of
events in the west of Ireland.
He will leave Ireland early to visit US troops based in Germany, who are facing
duty in Bosnia.
Meanwhile, last night Irish Prime Minister John Bruton criticised Northern
Ireland Secretary Sir Patrick Mayhew for displaying ``immutability'' in a
speech on the peace process.
Mr Bruton, currently caught up in negotiations with Mr Major aimed at resolving
the impasse, also said that risks had to be taken to overcome the current
problems.
His comments came after Sir Patrick, speaking at Londonderry, repeated
Britain's demands for IRA moves towards decommissioning its weapons ahead of
Sinn Fein's entry into all-party talks on the future of Northern Ireland.
Mr Bruton said: ``If we are going to move forward, we must recognise the need
for compromise. You cannot lay down a set, immutable position - as I feel Sir
Patrick was laying down today - and expect there are going to be compromises.''
Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble said that the peace process semed to be in
a state of ``stalemate.'' He did not think the current approach of the British
and Irish governments was ``going to go anywhere.''
Mr Trimble suggested that, instead, a Northern Ireland assembly should be set
up and elections held quickly as they would ``clear the air.''
He believed they would see the eclipse of some of the smaller groups that had
sprung up since the process began but which had, he thought, little popular
support. They also would show whether there was any mandate in Northern Ireland
for significant change in the present constitutional arrangements.
Elections also would force Sinn Fein-IRA to put forward more detailed policies
which could be scrutinised and questioned and tested by the voters. Mr Trimble
said: ``We know the private armies are still there.''
</TEXT>
