<HEADLINE>On target for single currency</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241351</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EUROPE is making economic progress towards a single currency but there is still
much room for improvement, according to three reports published yesterday.
Two of the reports - from the European Commission - confirmed Chancellor
Kenneth Clarke's claims that the British economy is on track to meet the
conditions for joining a single currency as laid down in the Maastricht treaty.
Britain has the right to remain outside a single currency if it wishes.
More significantly, the report - published yesterday by EU finance commissioner
Yves-Thibault de Silguy - points to progress by the French in meeting the
so-called Maastricht convergence criteria for monetary union. It suggests
France is likely to meet targets on debt as a percentage of gross domestic
product (GDP), one of the most important criteria.
French participation in the birth of a single currency is seen as critical to
the success of the venture, which is expected to be launched by an exclusive
group of EU member states with the strongest currencies.
Under the Maastricht timetable for a single currency in 1997, the EU member
states must make their economies converge in areas including inflation,
interest rates, currency stability, debt, and government deficits.
Mr de Silguy, reporting progress towards the single currency as positive, said:
``The situation is largely satisfactory as far as inflation and interest rates
are concerned but much less so regarding budgetary performance.''
</TEXT>
