<HEADLINE>Protest at tree felling</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241352</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COUNCIL workers and locals clashed yesterday over tree felling in a Glasgow
park.
Protesters tried to stop the workers cutting down more than 20 trees which line
Govanhill Park.
The council's environment department said they had Dutch elm disease.
However, the residents claim it is to enable the Glasgow District parks and
recreation department to make way for a park development.
Ms Alice Caldwell, 47, yesterday confronted the council workers. ``I asked them
what they were doing and when they told me I informed them there was no way
they were going ahead with it,'' she said. ``I just stood in the way so they
couldn't go near it.''
She added: ``They only got away with cutting down a sapling earlier because
no-one noticed them doing it.''
Pensioner Sheila Thaw, from Copelaw Street in 1951, said: ``I'm really angry
about the way we've been treated by the council.
``If the council get their way there'll be none left. It's disgraceful.''
The council's environment manager, Mr Brian Atkinson, denied they were cutting
down healthy trees.
He said: ``Nineteen trees will be removed. All are either at different stages
of Dutch elm disease, or have come to end of their lives.
``We have had extensive consultation with community groups concerning our plans
and have indicated right from the beginning that trees would be removed.''
</TEXT>
