<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scotland proposals are the best we can do, says Forsyth</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241353</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S political parties were at war yesterday as the argument over
devolution dominated Scottish Question Time in the Commons.
At a Westminster news briefing, Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth said that he
had sat down with his officials within a week of taking office and had spent
most of the summer working on the matter.
He gave away few details of what his proposals - to be announced next Thursday,
St Andrew's Day - will contain, but he confirmed that he had contacted Shadow
Scottish Secretary George Robertson over a plan to hold 12 sessions of the
Scottish Grand Committee at different locations in Scotland between now and
June of next year.
Mr Forsyth also praised the input of the Prime Minister to the debate on
Scotland's future. He said: ``People must wait and see, but the proposals are
my best shot, the best we can do. We will never have proposals which will
damage the Union and harm Scots by making them pay more tax.''
He acknowledged that the Government had to respond to the feeling of the people
of Scotland that they wanted more say in their own affairs, and that the
accountability of the Government north of the Border had to be improved.
``I started with a clean sheet of paper and asked officials to look at all the
options on how we can improve the governance of Scotland,'' he said. ``The
Prime Minister is passionate about the Union, and is very concerned that we
take proper account of the Scottish dimension.
``He has been a very doughty and stong ally. Without him I doubt if we could
have agreed on the proposals I will announce next week.''
In the Commons, Mr Forsyth insisted that Scotland got a good deal from its
Union with England as he resisted demands for a separate parliament. He said
spending per head was currently running at #4185 a year, 21% higher than for
England.
Mr Robertson accused him of using ``smears, distortions and downright lies'' to
oppose devolution.''
Despite this, he claimed, there had been a decisive swing towards the idea of a
devolved Scottish parliament among the business community - a reference to the
recent survey conducted by the Fraser of Allander Institute for the Scottish
Chambers of Commerce.
Mr Robertson said: ``When are you going to recognise you have got it wrong and
business opinion now realises devolution will be good for Scotland, for Britain
and for British business?''
Mr Harry Greenway (Ealing North - Con.) said it was naive of Labour and the
Liberal Democrats to expect the high level of funding for Scotland to continue.
Replying, Mr Forsyth poured scorn on claims that a Scottish parliament could
use its powers under a ``tartan tax'' to lower taxation to below the level it
was in England.
For the Liberal Democrats, former party leader Sir David Steel (Tweeddale,
Ettrick and Lauderdale) referred to the recent elections in the devolved region
of Catalonia in Spain and asked: ``Why is it that what is possible and welcome
in Spain is impossible in the United Kingdom?''
Mr Forsyth turned the question round to Canada and asked Sir David: ``In
Canada, the argument was that by going for devolution they would prevent
separatism and that ended in division and disruption. The lesson of Canada is
that you feed the crocodile and one day you get eaten.''
For the SNP, party leader Alex Salmond challenged Mr Forsyth on inward
investment, and he said last night: ``While the other parties argue about
variations on the Union and tinkering with the Scottish Grand Committee, we
have a clear stand on Scotland's future. The tide of opinion appears to be
moving in our direction.''
q Scottish Local Government Minister George Kynoch claimed at Westminster
yesterday that council reorganisation would allow many of Scotland's new local
authorities to reduce local tax bills next year if they maintained current
spending levels.
However, council leaders have warned Ministers that they face such grave
financial problems as a result of Government policies that council tax levels
are likely to rise significantly while services may also have to be cut.
Mr Kynoch was announcing Scottish Office agreement to Cosla proposals for a
self-financing three year transitional scheme to deal with mismatches over the
allocation of funding thrown up by the break-up of the large regional councils.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Staff reject pay cut</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241354</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE future of 350 manufacturing jobs at the Harper-Collins book plant in
Glasgow looked increasingly insecure last night after staff rejected a proposed
pay cut of about 25%.
Officials of the Graphical, Paper and Media Union, which represents more than
300 of the workers, said its members had unanimously thrown out the proposal.
The reduction in salaries had been put forward by the prospective owner of the
manufacturing arm of the Bishopbriggs plant, Mr Chris Hardie, who currently
owns a printing company in Berwick.
He is thought to have claimed that the huge cut is a necessary part of a
buy-out package backed by the Bank of Scotland. The plant has made losses of
more than #10m in the past five years.
However, Mr David Munro, Scottish branch secretary of GPMU, said yesterday:
``The ball is back in their court.
``We would expect a new owner to observe the legislation governing transfer of
engagements, which is there to protect existing wages and conditions.''
Mr Hardie was not available for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>More people are moving to Scotland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241355</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORE people are moving to Scotland, according to Government figures released
last night. Since 1988, there has been a net gain of 7000 a year in Scotland's
population. Last year, the migration of people to Scotland from elsewhere in
the UK was 47,000.
Scottish Office Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton said: ``People are coming
in increasing numbers to Scotland in recognition of the standard of living and
quality of life the country offers.''
THE Government promised yesterday to do all in its power to improve safety
standards on cross-channel ferries - but refused to set a time limit on how
long vessels must stay afloat after an accident. However, as the Department of
Transport published its response to a Commons committee's report into ferry
safety, Transport Secretary Sir George Young said the Government accepted the
broad thrust of the committee's recommendations.
LEADER of the House Tony Newton announced that the Commons Christmas recess
will be from Wednesday, December 20, to Tuesday, January 9,
</TEXT>
