<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Changed names protect innocent</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241356</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE four youngest children of the West family are living under new identities
in foster homes far removed from Gloucester.
The programme for caring for them is currently costing around #250,000 a year.
The three girls and a boy - now aged between 12 and 17 - have been given new
names to protect them from the publicity surrounding their parents' infamy.
They are all with foster families at unknown locations outside Gloucestershire.
Another daughter of the West family, now aged 17, is believed to be living with
relatives in Gloucestershire. She successfully applied to have the care order
on her lifted a few months before her mother's trial at Winchester Crown Court.
All the children were placed in care after allegations were made against their
parents in August 1992.
The four still in care are expected to remain there until they are 18.
The fathers of two of the girls are unknown, but Fred West was the father of
the others in care.
Gloucestershire County Council's social services department is footing the
annual bill of around #250,000 a year for the West children, mainly in the
costs of fostering and the special back-up services.
The children are also understood to be receiving special counselling which is
likely to continue for some considerable time - for some, possibly all their
lives.
A High Court Family Division order prevents the media from publishing details
of the children's new homes or making any approaches about their care.
In making a previous order, Mr Justice Thorpe said that he regarded two of the
children as ``extremely vulnerable''. They had been affected by the case and
its publicity, he said.
Meanwhile, their mother's days in prison will be divided between 12 hours
locked in her cell and a routine of exercise, education, and work activities.
That is the basic daily regime of Durham jail's H wing, widely known as ``She
wing'', where West can expect to spend most of the rest of her life.
There are currently 44 inmates, Moors murderer Myra Hindley is the best-known,
in Britain's only unit for long-term women convicts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour leaders see snags over `modern' parliament</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975241359</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PLANS to ensure that a Scottish parliament adopts a consensus approach and does
not slip back into the ``childish confrontation'' of Westminster were unveiled
yesterday by a Labour think tank.
However, the success of the measures will depend on winning over a sceptical
Labour hierarchy which already feels it has conceded enough in agreeing that
the parliament will be elected by proportional representation.
The updated proposals by retired politics professor Bernard Crick and former
Westminster and European Parliament civil servant David Millar were welcomed as
a ``contribution to the debate'' by Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson.
However, it is understood that he already has indicated privately to the
authors that there would be ``problems'' with some of their ideas.
``To make the Parliament of Scotland a model for democracy,'' is an update of
previous work by the authors, and is published by the John Wheatley Centre.
The authors have attempted to ditch almost every facet of Wesminster practice
in favour of more modern, less confrontational practices. For example, the
largest party would not select the Prime Minister and Speaker, posts which
would be voted on in a secret ballot by the parliament as a whole.
The party hierarchies, represented by the whips, would be stripped of much of
their power by handing over to a powerful business committee, chaired by the
Speaker, control over the timetable of business on the floor and in committees.
Committees, in turn, would be far more powerful and would actually be able to
initiate legislation.
The result of this would be a legislature controlled by its membership as a
whole, rather than dominated by the largest party.
``Openness, consistency and the search for consensus'' were the guiding
principles, said Mr Millar yesterday.
The Parliament would meet during office hours and take the Scottish school
holidays, to get away from the unsocial and anti-family nature of Westminster.
However, the admission in the report that the withering of the present Scottish
Secretary post at Westminster may be inevitable in time, will be seized on by
opponents of change, who will claim that Scotland will lose a valuable source
of influence and power.
</TEXT>
