<HEADLINE>It was a marriage of evil and a series of girls paid the price The fatal attraction</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241360</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Allan Smith
A Chat between a group of schoolchildren and a beat bobby in a street in
Gloucester started the House of Horrors investigation. Friends of one of
Rosemary and Fred West's children triggered the inquiry when they stopped the
officer on an August day in 1992.
What they told him cannot be published - but it prompted Gloucester County
Council's social services department to take all five of the West's children
who were still under the age of 16 away from their home at 25 Cromwell Street
and into care within days.
Builder Fred West and his wife Rosemary, 12 years his junior, ended up in
Gloucester Crown Court facing charges of sex abuse involving a young girl.
They were acquitted because two main prosecution witnesses suddenly decided not
to testify.
But the investigation which led to their appearance in court set off a train of
events which was to uncover a horrifying trail of murder, abduction, sexual
torture, and depravity.
Investigations started at the West family home, an unremarkable house in
inner-city Gloucester, because of the tenacity of Detective Constable Hazel
Savage.
She heard about a West ``family joke'', which the children told to social
workers, that the couple's missing 16-year-old daughter Heather was ``under the
patio''.
When the West children were taken into care in 1992 there was no sign of
Heather, and efforts to trace her failed. It was believed she had simply left
home.
But Detective Constable Savage eventually convinced senior officers in the
county's small police force of the possibility that the ``joke'' was not merely
black humour - but a macabre veil for a grim truth.
Her insistence led to police asking the city's magistrates, in February 1994,
for a warrant to search the rear garden in Cromwell Street.
The searchers were to uncover what Mr Brian Leveson, QC, prosecuting, told
Rosemary West's trial was a scene ``more terrible than words can express''.
Their discoveries were to destroy the facade of normality which Fred and
Rosemary West had so cunningly projected for so long and expose a tale of
sexual obsession, promiscuity, torture, and sadism.
Fred and Rosemary West were to find themselves ranked among the cruellest and
most depraved murderers of the century, a pair whose grotesque sexual appetites
cost the lives of ten young women - including their own child who was murdered
to ensure her silence.
The trail of horror started, and was to end, at the village of Much Marcle, on
the borders of Gloucestershire and Herefordshire, where Fred West was born on
September 29, 1941.
West, the son of farm worker Walter West and his wife Daisy, who lived in a
cottage in the hamlet, was one of the family's three sons and three daughters.
At school he was described as a ``troublesome'' pupil, and he left at the age
of 15, working on local farms and later as a baker's delivery boy and a lorry
driver.
The youngster, known for his fondness for his 125cc motorcycle, which he sold
after being seriously injured in an accident, was also known for his fondness
for the dances regularly held in the local hall.
But the darker side of Fred West's character was already beginning to show, for
he had a reputation for forcing his attentions on girls.
In 1961, before his first marriage, he was to appear in court charges with a
sex offence against a 13-year-old girl. He was acquitted.
That same year he met Scots waitress Catherine Costello at nearby Ledbury. They
were married at the local register office the following year.
The marriage was to be a disaster and would end in multiple murder.
Catherine was already pregnant. The child - Charmaine West, who was to become
the youngest victim of the House of Horrors tragedy - was not West's but was
fathered by a previous boyfriend.
Soon after the marriage the couple moved to Scotland, where both of their
daughters were born, and Fred found a number of casual jobs, including work as
an ice-cream salesman.
But in December 1965 West was back in Ledbury, claiming his wife was a
prostitute and that he was being chased by Glasgow gangsters over unpaid debts.
The two daughters were to go in and out of care over the next five years.
Fred West and Catherine were reunited, on and off, but Catherine often returned
to Scotland because of their marital problems and West's violence.
By 1966 Catherine West was again in Scotland. West persuaded 17-year-old Anne
McFall, a Scottish friend of his wife's, to live with him in a caravan park
near Gloucester.
She was the child-minder but swiftly became West's lover.
The following year, in July, Catherine West again returned to the family to
take over the care of her children.
Anne McFall, who was heavily pregnant with West's child, was last sighted about
this time.
West told inquirers that she had gone back to Scotland. But she had become Fred
West's first known murder victim. He strangled her and buried her in a field
near Much Marcle.
By December 1969, Catherine West had returned to Scotland yet again.
While she was away, West, now working as a baker's roundsman and living in a
caravan park at Cheltenham, embarked on an affair with 15-year-old Rosemary
Letts - which was to lead them into a downward spiral of vice, sadism, and,
ultimately, serial murder.
In Rosemary, West had found ``the perfect companion'', Mr Leveson was to tell
the trial 26 years later.
Rosemary Letts, who was brought up in Stoke Orchard, near Cheltenham, was a
stubborn and rebellious teenager, and kicked constantly against her parents'
strict discipline.
She came from a church-going family who were brought up to understand clearly
the difference between right and wrong.
Although she tried to act older than her age she was regarded as being a little
slow and backward.
Her family was not in the least impressed with West - his habit of laughing at
anything and everything was unnerving, he was not very good-looking, and he was
always untidy and dirty.
But Rosemary, fresh out of school, persisted in her affair. Her parents grew so
angry and upset that they put their wayward daughter - by this time pregnant by
West - into care.
On leaving care in 1970 she returned to West's arms. Shortly afterwards the
couple moved to Cheltenham, then to Gloucester, where they set up home in a
flat at 25 Midland Road - a stone's throw from Cromwell Street.
By this time Catherine West had also disappeared. She was last sighted in March
1970, when she visited her daughters at the home of foster parents.
She had also met a violent end at the hands of Fred West and was to be dumped
in a cornfield just a few hundred yards from Anne McFall's grave.
Fred and Rosemary West were still at Midland Road when their first daughter,
Heather, was born, on October 17, 1970.
Within a month, West was in court again, being jailed for 10 months for theft,
motoring offences, and breaching a suspended sentence.
In March 1971 came the last positive sighting of Charmaine, Catherine West's
first daughter. The child, who by now was eight years old, went to a hospital
to be treated for an ankle injury.
Rosemary West was later to tell inquirers - who included the mother of the
little girl's best friend - that Charmaine had gone to live with her mother
``and bloody good riddance''.
Charmaine's body was to be found buried under the kitchen floor at 25 Midland
Road some 23 years later, on the tenth day of a police search.
Fred West was to tell police that he strangled the little girl but police
maintained he was in prison at the time and Rosemary was the killer.
Rosemary West's trial was told that it was obvious that she was having
difficulty with Charmaine. The self-willed Rosemary was, after all, only some
eight years older than her step-daughter, and had a younger step-child and a
baby to care for.
Rosemary West's lies about Charmaine's fate were part of the link which held
her and herhusbandtogether.
The prosecution case was the essence of the relationship between the couple -
what they knew about each other, what they did together, what they did to
others, and how far each was prepared to go.
Rosemary had already, after leaving Fred West and returning home, given her
parents a hint of the darkness in which she was to envelop herself, telling her
father when Fred West arrived to talk her into returning: ``He's capable of
anything - even murder.''
Much of the events which were to follow could, Mr Leveson said, be ``explained
in the context both were obsessed by sex''.
Also binding the pair together was Charmaine's murder.
That knowledge, and their increasingly bizarre sexual activities, were to end
the lives of nine other young women, and damage the lives of an unknown number.
Late in January the following year, Fred West and Rosemary married at
Gloucester City Register Office, when he was 30 and she was just 18.
It was a marriage based on a lie. Fred West falsely described himself as a
bachelor on the marriage certificate, which avoided difficult explanations
about his first marriage. For Catherine had been dead for two years.
Six months later the West's second child, Mae, was born, and the couple moved
to 25 Cromwell Street.
The burly builder rapidly established a reputation as a simple, hard-working
family man, although he was also nicknamed Jackanory - after the children's
television series in which well-known people read fairy stories - because of
his habit of telling tall tales.
But the grim reality of the private life of Fred and Rosemary West was soon to
surface.
The couple had befriended 17-year-old girl Caroline Owens, persuading her to to
work for them as a live-in nannie.
But she moved out after a few months, worried by Rosemary West's peculiar
behaviour - she had taken to stroking Caroline's hair, walking in and looking
at her while she was naked in the bath, and telling her that she had lovely
eyes.
But four weeks after quitting, while returning to her parents' home in
Cinderford after a night out, she accepted a lift from the Wests.
It was to lead to a night and a day of terror and torture at the hands of her
former employers during which she was raped, assaulted, and subjected to sexual
abuse.
She was finally allowed to leave the house the following day, after promising
that she would return to work for the couple as their nannie. Instead, the
terrified Caroline told a friend of her ordeal, then went to the police.
The Wests were subsequently fined #50 each after they admitted indecent assault
and causing actual bodily harm.
Caroline Owens may have been their first sexual torture victim.
She was also to be the only girl abducted to their house and used as the object
of their perverted sexual desires who would live to tell the tale. Others would
not be so lucky - their lives would be simply ``snuffed out'', as Mr Leveson
told the jury.
Alarm signals about the Wests were not sounded because, as they had pled
guilty, the court never heard the full facts about Caroline Owens's dreadful
ordeal.
Instead, the couple returned to the apparent normality of 25 Cromwell Street,
the unremarkable house where five unsuspecting young women were murdered in the
space of two years. Four more were to die before the killings were finally
revealed last year.
For Fred and Rosemary West, the house had a major advantage - a large cellar.
No one would be surprised if a builder improved his own family home - but the
work could also be a camouflage for other activities.
West told Caroline Owens as she lay bound and gagged in his bedroom: ``I will
keep you in the cellar and my black friends will use you. Then when I have
finished with you we will kill you and bury you under the paving stones of
Gloucester.''
Caroline's abduction set the Wests' future strategy. If their victims could not
be trusted to keep quiet they would simply have to be murdered.
The first victim to fall prey to the Wests was 19-year-old Lynda Gough. The
seamstress, whose family was from Glossop, Derbyshire, worked in the Co-Op
store in Gloucester and slept with a number of lodgers at the Wests' home.
She disappeared without trace in April 1973, after telling her parents that she
had a flat in the centre of the city.
Her mother traced to 25 Cromwell Street, where she was told that Lynda had
moved on. She had talked of going to Weston-super-Mare, but, said the young
dark haired woman at the door, she did not know whether she had actually gone
there.
But Lynda's mother noticed the woman was wearing Lynda's slippers, and some of
her clothes were hanging on the clothes line in the back garden.
Lynda's body was found in March 1994, buried under the ground floor bathroom at
the house. She had been gagged with adhesive tape.
The next victim was 15-year-old Carol Ann Cooper, who was known as ``Cass''.
She was in the care of Worcestershire social services, at a children's home in
Worcester.
She disappeared in November 1973, after catching a bus back to the home
following a night out with friends. She had probably been picked up while
hitch-hiking the final leg of the journey to the children's home.
``Cass'' came from a broken home and was taken into care after her mother died
and her father re-married. She had no known connection with the Wests or 25
Cromwell Street.
But it was under the floor in the cellar of that house that her decapitated and
dismembered body was eventually to be found. There were signs that she had also
been gagged and tied.
The final victim of 1973 was 21-year-old student Lucy Partington, who was
studying English at Exeter University and had a promising future specialising
in mediaeval art.
Lucy, a niece of the novelist Kingsley Amis and described by friends as
``gentle and serious'', disappeared just two days after Christmas Day. She had
gone to a village near Cheltenham to visit a friend who was confined to a
wheelchair.
She left the friend's home that evening to catch a bus back to her family's
home at Gretton, near Winchcombe, north-east of Cheltenham, and disappeared
without trace.
The evidence, Mr Leveson told the trial, was that Lucy Partington was kept
alive at 25 Cromwell Street ``for hideous purposes'' for a number of days.
She was doomed from the moment she was abducted as a victim who ``would never
have joined the West household voluntarily''.
Her dismembered remains were found under the floor of an alcove in the cellar
at 25 Cromwell Street in March 1994. She too had been gagged and tied.
The killings continued the following year, with Swiss-born Therese Siegenthaler.
The 21-year-old student at a London college disappeared at about Easter, 1974,
while hitch-hiking to Ireland to visit a priest friend.
Her remains were found jammed into a grave under the floor in front of the
fireplace in the cellar of 25 Cromwell Street. She, too, had been gagged before
she met her death.
Shirley Hubbard was next. The pretty fifteen-year-old lived with foster parents
in Droitwich. She was taken into care at the age of two after her parents
separated.
On November 4, the schoolgirl left home for a day's work experience on the
make-up counter at the Debenham's store in Worcester. She disappeared after
leaving at 5.30pm.
Her decapitated and dismembered remains were unearthed under the floor in the
cellar at the Wests' home. She had been made to wear a head-mask made of thick
tape. Only a three-inch piece of tubing through the mask prevented her
suffocating.
She was kept ``alive but helpless'', Mr Leveson told the jury.
``That can only have been for sexual gratification so that her living but
restrained body could be used or abused at will.
``Furthermore, this wasn't necessarily abuse over a short period of time.
Precisely how long, and when what you may think was the blessing of death came
to her, we can't say.''
Eighteen-year-old Juanita Mott was their next victim. She vanished in April
1975, the day before a friend's wedding. Juanita lived in a number of bedsits
in Gloucester, and worked at a local soft drinks firm. She was probably picked
up as she hitch-hiked back to Gloucester after an evening out.
She too was to become a bound and gagged cellar victim.
There then came a three-year gap before the Wests changed their methods, even
preying on girls who lived or visited their home.
Eighteen-year-old Shirley Anne Robinson, who was put under the supervision by
Gloucestershire County Council's social services department after her parents
split up, moved into the house in about April 1977.
She also fell under West's spell - and within months was pregnant by him.
Shirley Anne was last seen at Gloucester Health Centre in May, 1978, when she
was eight months pregnant.
West had even talked of marrying her. But within days of her medical check-up
she disappeared. Her body and the foetus was buried at Cromwell Street.
She was murdered, Mr Leveson told the trial, because she presented a threat to
the stability of the relationship between Fred and Rosemary West.
The Wests, however, had run out of space to hide bodies in the cellar - where
their victims' remains were buried in clockwise order of death. Shirley Anne,
her head and legs cut off, was buried in the small back garden at the house.
The following year, 1979, 17-year-old Alison Chambers - who was in the care of
Swansea social services and lived at the Jordan's Brook Children Home in
Gloucester - fell into their clutches.
Alison, who ran away from the home several times, finally disappeared after
telling her mother she was living with a ``homely'' family and looking after
their children.
Alison vanished in August that year. Her dismembered remains were unearthed in
the garden at 25 Cromwell Street almost 15 years later. A buckled leather belt
was found close to her skull.
The murders then seem to have stopped for a number of years.
But while killing many victims, the couple were also indulging in bizarre
sexual practices with vulnerable young people they befriended and lured into
their home.
One young woman, Miss A, told of being brutally assaulted, raped, and subjected
to other attacks. She only came forward to tell of her ordeal - shame and
confusion had kept her silent for years - after reading about the House of
Horrors investigation.
Lodgers told how Rosemary West worked as a prostitute. She entertained men -
often more than one at a time - in ``Rose's Room'', a ground floor room outside
which was a red light to warn the children to keep out when their mother was
``busy''.
One lodger told how they became used to the sounds and screams of what they
assumed was ``kinky sex''. They took it as a huge joke - but ``sometimes the
screams became quite frightening, and then the joke went sour''.
It was, as far as is known, to be eight years before the Wests returned to
murder.
But their final victim is the one whose death demonstrates that there was no
depth of evil which Fred and Rosemary West were not prepared to plumb.
The West's oldest daughter Heather, was a 16-year-old who had just finished her
GCSE examinations in 1987. Jack True, her former headmaster, remembered her as
a ``very pleasant young girl''.
But Heather had also been a child at 25 Cromwell Street as her parents embarked
on the murderous spree which turned their own home into a charnel house.
Fred West admitted killing his daughter when he appeared in Gloucester
magistrates' court after her body was found.
The trial jury heard the killer confess how he strangled her and then cut up
her body with an ice saw.
In the taped admission to police, he told how he put her remains in a dustbin
before burying her near a Wendy house in the back garden.
The trail was to lead them to nearby Midland Road and on to Much Marcle, Fred
West's birthplace, where the fields of Kempley gave up the bodies of his first
wife Catherine, baby-minder Anne McFall and her unborn baby.
The Wests, meanwhile, were separately held in custody as murder charges mounted
against them.
On the occasions that they appeared in court together, West wanted to have some
contact with his wife but she ignored him.
It was becoming every woman for herself - a game the manipulative Rosemary West
was well-equipped to play.
Without the woman with whom he had been besotted for so long, he began to
disintegrate, like a character from a Victorian novel.
He finally became isolated and withdrawn, lapsing into brooding sullen silences
for hours on end. In interviews with police he became rambling or utterly
incoherent.
Fred West was found hanging in his cell at Winson Green Prison, Birmingham, on
New Year's Day, 1995.
He had escaped justice, and his wife was left to face the courts, and the
world, alone.
</TEXT>
