<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bible defended</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241363</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WAS dismayed to read of yet another leading churchman engaging in this
pseudo-intellectual game of bringing the Bible up to date. If the early
Christians had been Bishop Holloway clones, apologising to Roman society for
Old Testament moral teaching, where would Western civilisation be now?
If he and others like him would spend their time emphasising the relevance of
the Bible to today's society, perhaps churches would find people flocking
through their doors again.
In my experience most of the churches which teach how up-to-date and relevant
the Bible is are full to overflowing, especially with young people.
As an example of this ``outdated moral teaching'', is it a coincidence that, in
25 years, I have only seen three marriages break up in these churches? Of
those, two were as a result of infidelity.
Let's hear more church leaders defend the Bible rather than rip it apart with
these irrelevant (and irreverent) arguments.
Willie Campbell,
59 Woodhead Avenue,
Kirkintilloch.
</TEXT>
