<DOCNO>GH951123-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>When every day is special</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241364</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I READ with interest Chris Holme's article, Cancer system failing women, which
highlighted the shocking but true breast cancer statistics (November 17).
However, it would be encouraging to hear more of the women who have come
through the experience and find that life is still very much worth living.
Much as I wholeheartedly support new trials and regular screening, especially
for woman under 50, I feel there is too much emphasis on doom and gloom to the
point where, rather than encouraging women to have regular tests, they are
being frightened away.
Having been through the experience myself, which resulted in a radical
mastectomy, I can honestly say that, four years on, life is very sweet indeed
and every day is special.
There are thousands of women who like myself have been successfully treated and
I genuinely believe that if the positive results of early detection were given
more publicity, the number of women going forward for testing would rise
dramatically.
Elizabeth Cameron,
13 Muir Bank,
Scone.
</TEXT>
