<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sad claims</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241365</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I fully agree with Calum MacKinnon. On nearly every street we see derelict
churches which, together with the declining numbers on the rolls of the Kirk,
would seem to bear out John Lennon's quote (Weekend Extra), ``Christianity will
go. It will vanish and shrink. We're more popular than Jesus now: I don't know
which will go first, rock'n'roll or Christianity. Jesus was all right, but his
disciples were thick and ordinary.''
I may be thick and ordinary but I believe that our island home is a more
Christian place today than it was in the days when kirks were packed to
overflowing.
For it was in these days, among other sacrileges, that coal miners, the less
than human scum of the earth, were forbidden burial in sacred ground.
By legislation and every fair-minded means at our command, health and safety at
work must be of paramount concern. What I find sad is that every hiccup in the
lottery of life should be seen as a possible source of financial compensation.
James Blyth,
Cherryfield,
Glebe Road,
Muthill.
</TEXT>
