<HEADLINE>James McAdam Clark</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241366</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
James McAdam Clark, CVO, MC, BSc, diplomat and scientist; born September 13,
1916, died October 15, 1995
JAMES McAdam Clark, the scientist and diplomat, has died at the age of 79.
Fiercely proud of his Scottish ancestry, he was educated at Edinburgh Academy,
where he was, in his own words, ``undistinguished but not unhappy''. On leaving
school in 1933 he was awarded a Leverhulme Scholarship and graduated from
Edinburgh University in 1938 with first class honours in chemistry.
On the outbreak of the Second World War he joined the Royal Artillery, serving
in the UK, North Africa, and Italy, where as a captain in Heavy Artillery he
was awarded the MC for bravery in the field. Thanks to his scientific
background he was sent at the end of hostilities to the Royal Military College
of Science, remaining there till 1946.
On return to civilian life he joined the Ministry of Fuel and Power as a civil
servant before being transferred to the Foreign Office and diplomatic service.
In a career lasting almost 30 years, he went first to Ecuador, as a young head
of chancery, then to Lisbon in 1956 (where he was appointed an Officer of the
Order of Christ).
From 1960 to 1964 he was posted to Vienna as counsellor and the UK's
representative to the Atomic Energy Authority, where his Soviet opposite number
was the demoted former Foreign Minister Molotov. After a spell in London he was
seconded from 1966 to 1970 to the Ministry of Technology under Tony Benn.
Finally in 1970 he was sent as Consul General to Paris, where he was to serve
under three ambassadors in a seven-year tour of duty. He was appointed CVO in
1972 in recognition of his contribution to the success of the Queen's visit to
France that year.
Retiring to Aldeburgh in Suffolk, he pursued his interests in writing poetry
and lowering his golf handicap.
James Clark met his future wife Denise Dufournier, a young French barrister, in
1939. She was to achieve fame as a Resistance worker for Reseau Comet. Betrayed
in 1943, she survived incarceration in the Ravensbruck concentration camp to
return to England, marry James Clark in 1946, and bear him two daughters. She
died in January last year.
</TEXT>
