<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>John Collier</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241367</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
John Collier, FRS, chairman Nuclear Electric; born January 22, 1935, died
November 18, 1995
THERE can be few people who have achieved such sustained success in tackling a
dauntingly difficult task during the last years of their career as did John
Collier before his untimely death.
In November, 1989, when the nuclear power stations were taken out of the
electricity privatisation, John Collier was asked by John Wakeham, then
Secretary of State for Energy, to be chairman of the state-owned company
Nuclear Electric to run the stations in England and Wales.
Nuclear power was at its nadir. Generating costs appeared to be out of control;
construction projects had run over time and over budget; de-commissioning and
fuel cycle costs were not known with any confidence but were expected to be
prohibitively large; and there was little public support for nuclear power.
In the following years, under John Collier's leadership, Nuclear Electric made
improvements on all fronts.
Output rose steadily, costs were reduced, and staff numbers were brought down
without compulsory redundancy. Estimates of decommissioning costs were refined
and reduced. Firm fuel cycle contracts were negotiated. Sizewell B was built to
time and cost.
Safety standards also improved - Collier was convinced that good business
performance and good safety performance go hand in hand - and public and
political attitudes slowly became less hostile to nuclear power.
How was this achieved? John Collier had remarkable strategic vision;
immediately after his appointment he set out key objectives for the company
(with safety and environmental protection dominant) which determined the
company's agenda and which have all been achieved.
He unfailingly led from the front and his intellectual flair and human warmth
enabled him to attract and weld together a group of talented people on the
company's board.
His integrity engendered confidence in the public and staff about Nuclear
Electric's commitment to safety. He gave the firm a belief in itself and its
technolgy which underpinned its rapid progress.
The outcome was the Government's conclusion last summer that Nuclear Electric's
AGR and PWR stations were capable of being privatised. This reversal of the
1989 decision was the crowning achievement of Collier's career.
Aged 16, Collier left St Paul's School to become a Harwell apprentice against
the wishes of his headmaster. From Harwell he went to University College,
London, where he obtained a first class degree in Chemical Engineering. In 1957
he embarked on a career in the chemical engineering division at Harwell,
interrupted by a spell of two years with Atomic Energy of Canada Limited and
three years with Atomic Power Construction Limited.
He worked on the key nuclear safety areas of heat transfer and two-phase flow
where he made outstanding contributions. By 1975, he was head of the division.
The book he wrote at Harwell, Convective Boiling and Condensation, is one of
the standard international texts.
By 1977 it became clear Collier's abilities would enable him to contribute to
strategy and policy and he became head of a central technical policy team in
the AEA. He played a prominent part in achieving a sensible successful outcome
to the International Nuclear Fuel Cycle Evaluation initiated by President
Carter; he helped assess the safety of light water reactor pressure vessels for
the UK and provide evidence for the Sizewell B inquiry; he worked on developing
joint arrangements between the Central Electricity Generating Board (CEGB) and
the National Nuclear Corporation (NNC) for PWR design and construction.
In 1982 he was made director of the UKAEA's Safety and Reliability Directorate.
In 1983 Walter Marshall persuaded him to become director general of the CEGB's
Generation Development and Construction Division. He transformed the division
into an internal contractor within CEGB and oversaw the fusing of NNC and CEGB
staff to form the PWR project group which was responsible for the design and
construction management of the Sizewell B    station.
In January, 1987, he became chairman and chief executive of the UKAEA. By the
time he left in June, 1990 (after some months as both chairman of AEA and NE),
a new business-orientated structure had been set up tailored to the AEA's new
circumstances.
His massive contributions to nuclear engineering, to management in the nuclear
industry, and to increasing public understanding of nuclear issues were
recognised by his election to the fellowships of the Royal Academy of
Engineering and subsequently of the Royal Society.
He worked actively to improve the quality of engineering education and raise
the status of engineers. His efforts were reflected by his election as
president of the Institution of Chemical Engineers.
John Collier was a big man in every sense. He dominated any room by his
physical presence and dominated meetings by the depth of his technical
understanding and the force of his personality. He was essentially a very
private and serious man, though with a ready sense of humour. He had a deep
Christian faith and was a regular worshipper at his village church in
Sheepscombe, Gloucestershire.
The overwhelming memory of John Collier must be of a man of enormous humanity,
modesty, kindness, and unfailing courtesy who was regarded as a real friend by
his many colleagues and contacts.
He is survived by his wife, Ellen, who supported him actively throughout his
career and played a key role in his success, and by a son and daughter.
n.Appreciation by Dr ROBIN JEFFREY, chairman and chief executive of Scottish
Nuclear.
</TEXT>
