<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scotland and the constitution</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241368</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WRITE to congratulate you on the splendidly balanced political coverage in
the aftermath of the Prime Minister's recent pronouncements on Scotland and the
constitution (November 18).
John Major may yet be hoist with his own petard - and Michael Forsyth up there
along with him - but at last we have a credible heavyweight newspaper agreeing
with him over Scotland; namely, independence is a genuine option.
May we now put behind us the tired old chestnuts: oh, you could never manage on
your own; you would have to go through customs to visit your granny; you would
need to change your currency to see the Scotland football team in England, and
so on.
With regard to the currency, incidentally, many people do that already, so
problematic is Scottish sterling south of the Border. We all know that to be
the case and your leader chooses three interesting small countries to compare
with Scotland - Finland, whose cultural identity, like ours, waxed strong
before the break with Mother Russia; Estonia, which is defying all gloomy
predictions and dire consequences as she has successfully gone her own way; and
Luxembourg, which has the highest standard of living in Europe.
Not a bad choice without bringing in the equally strong Norwegian or Danish
parallels.
Some of us are already detecting a sea change, but given that the
constitutional issue simply refuses to go away, why won't the democratic will
of the people of Scotland force a referendum on this matter?
With regard to the role of Prime Minister, Mr Major ought to understand by now
that when he says ``the UK will be the poorer without Scotland'' he is palpably
compounding a very basic misunderstanding - without Scotland, there is no
longer a United Kingdom.
Would England be the 17th member state of the European Union?
Councillor Marion Anderson,
Municipal Buildings,
Cotton Street,
Paisley.
</TEXT>
