<HEADLINE>Glasgow Salutes Hungary, Cottier Theatre, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Harry Magee</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241369</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN impressive line-up of high-profile instrumentalists was brought together by
Music-Makers Organisation for this commemoration of the fiftieth anniversary of
the death of Bartok. Link-man appeared to be pianist Gusztav Fenyo who has
recorded with two of the evening's guests, the violinist Susanne Stanzeleit and
clarinettist Michael Collins.
However, first to show his form was the horn player, Stephen Stirling, with a
highly translucent account of his part in the Brahms Trio for piano, violin and
horn. He made it all look and sound so easy, projecting a warm mellow tone with
some vigorous violin accompaniment in the thoroughly enjoyable Scherzo.
With violinist and horn player both standing to play, Susanne Stanzeleit's
particularly physical style of attack was pointed up, an approach echoed by an
equally nimble of foot Michael Collins in the next two pieces. He brought a
delicacy of expression to the Ballade for Clarinet and Piano by Weiner and then
teamed up with Stanzeleit for what became almost a balletic interpretation of
Bartok's Contrasts as both bobbed and weaved their way through the complexity
of breathing and fingering demanded in the writing.
After the interval Fenyo squeezed plenty of rhythmic atmosphere from Kodaly's
original piano version of Dances of Marosszek, setting the scene for an
astounding piece of ensemble playing as Susie Meszaros, viola, and Timothy
Gill, cello, joined Collins, Stanzeleit and Fenyo in Dohnanyi's Sextet.
This formidable array of talent locked together into one dynamic unit, sending
sparks round the theatre. This was playing you wanted to go on and on.
</TEXT>
