<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241370</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
N her article on Dawson International following publication of the company's
interim results Margaret Vaughan made a number of statements which were not
correct (November 17).
While I have an obvious interest as the previous managing director, invited to
resign along with the previous chairman, I do not wish to comment on the
company and its performance other than to set the record straight.
It is stated that I and the previous chairman, Sir Ronald Miller, both received
a settlement of three years' salary rather than two as recorded.
It is suggested that Philip Kemp was managing director of the US shower curtain
business. He was in fact chief executive of the US businesses with the
president of the shower curtain business reporting to him until he (Mr Kemp)
left the company in April 1994. Details of his settlement were recorded in the
rights issue documentation published in May 1994.
Furthermore, a number of initiatives announced following our departure (in some
cases within a matter of days) were in fact instigated and agreed during the
term of office of Sir Ronald and myself: the sale of the shower curtain
business, Dawson Home Fashions; the sale of the weaving business, Premier
Fabrics; and the rationalisation of manufacturing capacity at Pringle of
Scotland and at Blackwoods carpet yarns.
Nick Kuenssberg,
6 Cleveden Drive,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
