<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Design takes centre stage</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Minty Donald</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241371</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Minty Donald visits an exhibition which puts            the glorious art of
scenography in the spotlight with
THE notion of an exhibition of design for theatre is, on reflection, curious.
How and why would one present an exhibition of something so dependent on its
context, the live theatre performance, for its appreciation or comprehension?
But then, theatre design - or scenography, as some of us, at the risk of
inviting pseud's corner accusations, prefer to call it - has always occupied a
peculiar position somewhere between visual art and theatre, between fine art
and design.
One need only look around the various institutions where it is taught (none,
regrettably, in Scotland as yet) to see these are frequently Drama Schools as
Art Colleges, fine art faculties as departments of interior and
three-dimensional design.
MAKE SPACE! is an exhibition of design for theatre and alternative spaces
currently in Carlisle (the furthest north it gets, to date), and it tackles
this ambivalence head-on. While unavoidably, and unashamedly, inviting
spectators to be seduced by the skill and intricacy, and the sheer doll's house
dinkieness of the models on display, exhibition organisers Kate Burnett and
Peter Ruthven Hall are at great pains to establish the context of each design.
The exhibition is divided into eight sections, according to category of theatre
or performance space. Thus we have sections devoted to design for
theatre-in-the-round, for thrust and open stages, for proscenium theatres,
touring, converted spaces and so on, including one on ``events and non-theatre
performances''.
Each designer's work is accompanied by a statement of intent, supporting the
drawings, photographs and models. It may sound like hard work, more educational
than inspiration, but the display is engaging and accessible; well deserving of
the special gold medal awarded at the 1995 Prague Scenography Quadriennial.
But what of the work itself? Designers will no doubt quibble, as is their wont,
over the selection of exhibits. Undoubtedly, some weak pieces have found their
way into the show, and the concentration on the North and North West of England
privileges the neo-hippy school of rough-hewn visual theatre. Diehards of the
bamboo-and-willow sculpture, puppet, and bonfire, Welfare State International
and Horse &amp; Bamboo perhaps exclude some more innovative work. Where, for
instance, at risk of waving the nationalist flag, is Glasgow's own Stewart
Laing?
But then, you can't please everyone. All in all, the show provides a
representative overview of British scenography from the past five years,
wheeling out the old stalwarts as well as catching the prevalent trends,
fashions, and flavours-of-the-month.
In the grunge corner, we have Hildegard Bechtler's Wozzeck for Opera North, all
pared-down monochrome, but with a scummy, grimy layering of textures, and
fascination with the qualities of ``real'' and ``poor'' materials on stage.
Vicki Mortimer's Turn of the Screw, at Tramway, brings in the properties of the
building itself, enhancing them with ``honest'' and ``simple'' elements such as
tarpaulin, water and earth in her haunting design for Scottish Opera.
At the other end of the scale, the grand, glossy visual metaphors so beloved by
contemporary opera designers are given vigorous reworkings in Mark Thompson's
stunning design for Sydney Opera House's Hansel and Gretel.
This is just a tiny sample of a show which encompasses work from Christine
Marfleet's minimalist gems to Ian MacNeil's  An Inspector Calls.
Such a richly packed exhibition deserves wider exposure, not least north of the
border.
n MAKE SPACE! is at the Tullie House Museum, Carlisle until December 3.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Indicators in exam results</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241372</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOOKING at the lists of examination results I was disappointed to see that you
have once again failed to publish one of the key indicators (November 21).
The figure for the percentage of pupils in S4 who gain five or more Standard
Grade awards at levels 1-6 actually tells us more about a school than any other
single indicator.
If this figure is low then however impressive its credit or general awards may
be, the school is manifestly not reaching all the parts.
If, on the other hand, the 1-6 figure is high, it tells us that the school is
managing to get all, or nearly all, its children to keep on coming, keep on
working, finish all the work for the internally assessed components, and turn
up on the day to do their best.
Any school which is doing that successfully is almost certainly being very
effective with all its pupils, whatever their backgrounds or abilities.
More seriously, by failing to mention awards gained at foundation level you are
serving to reinforce old prejudices. The implication is that foundation awards
are indeed worthless and that all the hard work, effort, and good attendance of
the children concerned is of no account.
When will we learn to give due value to the education of all our children?
Ian N Valentine,
Head Teacher,
Cleveden Secondary School,
42 Cleveden Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jack Finney</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241373</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Jack Finney (Walter Braden Finney), writer; born Milwaukee, 1911, died November
4, 1995
ONE of the enduring science fiction plots of the American cinema, the aliens
who take over human bodies, was provided by Jack Finney's 1955 novel, The Body
Snatchers. It was filmed three times, the first and most celebrated version
directed by Don Siegel in 1956 was Invasion of the Body Snatchers. It was
remade under the same title in 1978 by Philip Kaufman and as Body Snatchers
last year by Abel Ferrara.
The novel's plot is about alien plant pods which arrive from space and give
birth to perfect replicas of the inhabitants of a small American town who
proceed to take over the world as the pods proliferate. It is a chilling tale,
and Seigel made the most of it in a low-budget film starring Kevin McCarthy as
the one man who realises what is going on, losing his fiancee to the
infiltrators. The remakes changed the location to San Francisco and a US army
base without actually improving things.
The strength of the plot is such that both book and the films can be seen as
allegories interpreted variously as anti-Communist or anti-McCarthy. A prolific
novelist and short story writer, whose influence as a model is admitted by the
likes of Stephen King, Finney had other books adapted for the cinema, including
thrillers like Five Against the House, filmed in 1956 with Kim Novak, and
Assault on a Queen, about a plot to hijack the Queen Mary, filmed in 1966 with
Frank Sinatra.
His time-shift comedy, Marion's Wall, was filmed four years ago as Maxie,
starring Glenn Close. His best novel, Time and Again, published in 1970, was
about a man who thought himself back into turn of the century New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000145</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000145</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>How the `Milk Bar King' rose to the top</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Andrew Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241374</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
As the Forte empire comes under attack from Granada, Andrew Wilson recalls past
battles won and lost
THERE must have been a chuckle in Heaven yesterday. For eight tense and
dramatic years, the late Sir Hugh Wontner as chairman of the Savoy hotels group
resolutely fought off the attempts first by Lord Forte and more latterly
In the glorious and sometimes confused and incomprehensible battles that
ensued, Sir Hugh with a wintry smile said at one point:  ``I always thought
that Italians made good hotel managers.''
But that is what seemingly brash Gerry Robinson of Granada disputes - and he
has a point.
The Forte group's origins are the stuff of legend. These include the story of
the 1880s, when a family member was captured by bandits who demanded a ransom.
They threatened initially to cut off his ears and then his nose. The family
paid the money but decided that was valour enough and most emigrated including
Rocco Forte, grandfather of the now Sir Rocco.
He had ventured as far north as Scotland to set up small cafes - until the late
1940s the eastern part of Scotland seemed to be dotted with Forte ice-cream
shops and cafes.
Charles Forte arrived on the scene on November 26, 1908 in the village of
Montfort, south of Rome. He was brought to Scotland to join his father five
years later and was educated at both Alloa Academy and later at Dumfries
College.
He branched out on his own with his own milk-bar chain which spread rapidly
thoughout Britain although most were in southern England and particularly in
the London area. He was growing ever richer as the local prosperity improved in
the late 1930s until the Second World War brought about the shattering blow of
internment with a host of other Italians on the Isle of Man - albeit for just
three months.
The ``Milk Bar King'' became a British citizen in late 1945 and continued to
expand his business. A major breakthrough was the winning of the catering
contract for the 1951 Festival of Britain.
Other firsts included the award of the first motorway catering contract in 1959
- surely a missed opportunity as motorway feeding of the masses gained a
reputation that lasted a full two decades and only now is beginning to receive
critical praise and approbation.
That was four years after being awarded the right to supply Heathrow. This gave
Forte a major opportunity which proved invaluable in precise mass-catering and
portion control for highly demanding customers, as airlines could not afford
delays. That interest was sold off at the beginning of last year in the form of
Alpha Airports, although Forte still retains a quarter share which it does
intend selling off at the appropriate time - as does Granada if it wins the
takeover battle.
Industrial catering under the Gardner Merchant banner became an increasingly
important part of group activities and gave a stable and expanding base which
insulated the rest of Forte to some extent against the vagaries of the economy
and particularly the hotels business.
That began in 1958 when Charles Forte bought the Waldorf Hotel in London,
ironically as        it turned out just a couple of hundred yards away from the
Savoy. The roadside interests were gradually expanded with the establishment of
the Little Chefs and the Happy Eaters which were acquired as a package much
later.
The years 1970 and '71 were among the most important in his life. He was
knighted and also merged with the Trust Houses group. That was established in
1904 as a chain of temperance hotels catering for commercial travellers who
even then had a reputation.
Then came the bid from Allied Breweries which was one of the most vicious
dogfights ever seen in the City. By the end of the day Allied was seen off but
that left deep scars in the Trust House Forte boardroom.
Then came the purchase of the Travelodge motels business in the US although
that has never performed as well as had been hoped - overall the US experience
has been one of disappointment which culminated at one stage in former British
Steel chairman Sir Ian MacGregor being sent out to improve the business.
The wooing and then assault on the Savoy began in 1981 - a year before his
peerage as Baron Forte of Ripley. That was from the platform of the 35 Strand
Hotels acquired from Allied's Lyons subsidiary in 1978 for about #28m.
There was a clash of temperament.
Lord Forte, a close friend of Margaret Thatcher, is blunt and knows his own
mind but is also good at putting people at ease.
That was not enough for the Savoy's then managing director Giles Shepard who
remarked that ``the stewardship of the Savoy could not be entrusted to a vast
combine which, among other things, runs service stations on the main arterial
roads''.
That was a bit rich considering Forte made more money out of them than did the
Savoy despite its ownership of three of London's five-star hotels. In recent
years, partly due to recession, Forte has been seen to be struggling.
Part of that has been put at the door of Sir Rocco who became chief executive
in 1982 and chairman in 1992. But that is perhaps a little unfair given that
there was the recession of the early 1990s. And whatever people say about
Rocco, he does not lack competitiveness. Not only has he finished the London
marathon several times but he is also a keen golfer - he plays Gerry Robinson
frequently and plays to win.
So while he has been nicknamed Prince Charles by some in the headquarters in an
unprepossessing concrete headquarters in High Holborn, there is going to be
quite a fight before the battle is lost and won.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ten commandments to make the economy work</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELEANOR SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>open forum</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975241375</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UP until the Renaissance it was felt among those in society who held knowledge
that everything had been learned - the origins of life were explained in the
Bible, the natural world and human physiology had all been explained by the
ancients. Scientists who, in the new spirit of inquiry, began making
discoveries and publishing them frequently fell foul of the establishment,
especially the Church.
Modern economics is rather in the position of the fifteenth-century Church
-man-made explanations of how things are and must be assume the status of a
proven truth which cannot, must not be challenged. One can forgive the
economists themselves for this, imprisoned by their training, unable to break
free of the constraints to independent thought that formal training can so
regrettably create, they can no more question their faith than could those
churchmen in previous centuries.
Politicians, however, are drawn from the population generally, and some at
least should be able to take a fresh look at economic practice, if not theory.
Recent debates between the major parties on tax and benefits have highlighted
the fact this is not happening.
The Herald editorial of November 20 noted this, regretting the absence of `` .
. . a presentation of the theory and political ethics of any Labour tax
policy''. Labour is not the only party guilty of this; most politicians' ideas
on tax are completely shaped by what has gone before (so a tax introduced to
fund the Napoleonic Wars remains the mainstay of fiscal policy 200 years on).
Variations in taxation proposals between the major parties resemble a see-saw
more than anything - Income Tax up or down a few pence, VAT up or down a few
percent, depending on which section of the electorate is being particulary
wooed.
To counter the ``faith'' aspect of how people look at this aspect of the
economy, I have written out, as simply as I can, the 10 commandments of
tax/benefit policy.
1. Tax raises revenue.
2. Tax influences behaviour.
3. If you tax work, fewer people will be employed.
4. If you don't tax resources, people will feel free to use them all up.
5. If tax is raised and spent locally, it can respond to local need.
6. Everyone, including every child, is a citizen and citizenship should be
worth having.
7. The quality of life of even the richer members of society is reduced by the
poverty of others.
8. There will never again be nine to five, Monday to Friday jobs for every
adult, if indeed there ever were.
9. Part-time work, voluntary work, full or part-time study are all good for
society and should be encouraged at any age.
10. The ``cake'' cannot keep getting bigger, so fairness means a redistribution
of what we've got, both wealth and work.
Most of these are obvious. Commandment 10 is the only one likely to be
challenged but common sense shows it to be true; for example, 3% economic
growth per year means a doubling of economic activity in approximately 22 years
- twice the pollution, twice the waste produced, twice the consumption of
resources, twice the traffic in less than a generation - and if recent history
is anything to go by, no corresponding increase in employment.
Mr Blair may have abandoned Clause 4 but unless he has also abandoned fair
play, he will have to face up to redistribution of wealth at some point. We
can't rely on the cake getting bigger to solve poverty.
A party like the Scottish Green Party which is unlikely (though perfectly
ready) to form the next Government has the space to stand back and take a
proper look at the whole tax/benefit system with all its complexities and
bureaucracy. We have produced a thoroughly researched and costed system which
would eliminate the poverty trap (commandments six and nine) tax resource
depletion rather than work (three, four), encourage appropriate development and
promote a fair and just society (seven, nine, 10).
This difference would start as soon as a child is born. What is now referred to
as Child Benefit we would regard as the child's Basic Income which he/she would
continue to receive, increasing between the ages of 16 and 18 until it reached
the level of the Adult Basic Income. This would replace all existing benefits
and personal tax allowance, and would not be lost on taking up employment,
thereby eliminating that particular poverty trap.
It would be simple and cheap to administer and would allow for flexible
working, studying and retiral at an age that suits the person and his/her
employer, rather than at some rigid pre-determined age.
The Basic Income would continue throughout life - no need for an ``old age
pension'' - with the only variation being an enhancement in cases of
disability. Unlike the much-vaunted ``minimum wage'' or indeed Gordon Brown's
low starting rate for income tax, the Basic Income would benefit everyone, not
just those in full-time work.
As commandments one to four make clear, we need to move away from taxing jobs,
as National Insurance and VAT do now, to taxing resource use. We need to
encourage development by replacing taxes like Council Tax which are levied on
buildings and therefore discourage development, to a Land Value Tax which would
encourage development and discourge land speculation.
We need to sweep away the present cumbersome, inefficient and often degrading
benefits system with a simple, cheap and fair alternative and to integrate this
with the tax system. As The Herald editorial referred to earlier pointed out,
it is the benefits system rather than the tax system which is responsible for
the poverty trap.
Above all, we need the debate on tax, benefits and the economy generally to be
enriched by some new ideas.
I began by saying that 500 years ago it was generally held that the ancients
had found all the answers. They hadn't, of course, but they still hit upon some
essential truths from time to time; I believe it was Solomon who said: ``Where
there is no vision the people perish.''
Dr Eleanor Scott  is social affairs speaker for the Scottish Green Party.
</TEXT>
