<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A fragile peace Bosnia's future rests with two men</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241376</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DESPITE European pique and the pettiness of the French government it remains a
fact that only the United States had the muscle and the determination to
persuade Balkan leaders to agree to a peace plan for Bosnia. That said, the
peace plan is a frail creature, much in need of sustenance and support before
it can grow into something worthy of the name. Whether this will happen depends
for the most part on two men. The first is President Clinton who encouraged
that talented bully, US negotiator Richard Holbrooke, to bluster, threaten, and
twist Balkan arms. He did this with enthusiasm and the result is an agreement
which has achieved a reasonable degree of support in former Yugoslavia despite
its apparent rejection by the Bosnian Serbs. President Clinton must take the
peace process a crucial step further by ensuring that the United States honours
its promise to supply one-third of the required 60,000 Nato peacekeepers. His
problem lies in the attitude of his Republican Party opponents in the United
States who have shown a breathtaking ability to take political
bloody-mindedness to new heights of irresponsibility. British involvement is
dependent on US involvement, and although President Clinton will probably win
his peacekeepers it is sad that he should have to argue such an obvious case.
Within former Yugoslavia much depends on President Slobodan Milosevic of
Serbia. It is distressing to see this man, who carries much of the guilt for
the inception of the Balkan war, feted and courted as a peacemaker. He may make
peace, but only because he wants to remove sanctions from his own country. If
the Bosnian Serbs persist in their opposition to the peace agreement Milosevic
will bully them, although not as gently as Ambassador Holbrooke. Even this may
not be enough to ensure a lasting peace, but it is the best chance the
suffering people of the region have had.
</TEXT>
