<DOCNO>GH951123-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Alan Hull</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ADAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241378</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Alan Hull, singer, songwriter and poet; born February 20, 1945, died November
17, 1995
YES - Fog on the Tyne, Lady Eleanor, Clear White Light, We Can Swing Together -
few were the rock festivals and parties in the early 1970s which didn't sway
along to these songs. They were, of course, all sung by the same band,
Lindisfarne; all written by the same man, Alan Hull; and all, remarkably,
written in the same week while Hull was working as a nurse in a mental hospital.
A strict working class Newcastle upbringing gave Hull's writing the common
touch, his experiences as a nurse bringing a sense of realism which sustained
him when Lindisfarne's brief taste of rock stardom came to an end and he turned
his energies towards more overtly political writing.
He began singing as a teenager with a local rock band called the Chosen Few.
They made a few records but failed to make much impact.
In 1967 he formed the Downtown Faction, who a year later became Lindisfarne.
Their first album, Nicely Out Of Tune, initially caused a only few ripples but
when the follow-up, Fog on the Tyne, reached No.1 in 1971, it charged up the
charts.
By the following year, Lindisfarne were vying with Slade as the UK's biggest
selling band. An attempt to repeat that success in America backfired, however,
and ultimately led to three of the band - drummer Ray Laidlaw, guitarist Simon
Cowe, and bass guitarist Rod Clements - leaving to form Jack the Lad.
In 1973 Hull had released a solo album, Pipedream, many of whose songs related
to his nursing experiences, and he followed this up with a book of poetry on
similar concerns, The Mocking Horse, which became a best seller. He continued
to work as a solo artist, releasing the albums Squire (1975), Phantoms (1979),
and On the Other Side (1983).
Lindisfarne re-formed in 1978, scoring a Top Ten single with Run For Home, and
in 1990 joined footballer Paul Gascoigne on his ``Gazza rap'' hit version of
Fog on the Tyne.
Their concerts, particularly their incredible run of 150 Christmas sell-outs at
Newcastle City Hall, retained the 1970s care-free folk-rock party spirit, but
Hull could also still hit the political bullseye with songs such as Mother
Russia from their 1993 album Elvis Lives On the Moon. He was working on a new
solo album when he died following a heart attack last Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
