<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000151</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000151</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Idol falls to dearth</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Belcher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241380</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
David Bowie has released a new album, but    David Belcher hears a hero  crash
landing
ONCE upon a time, long ago and far away, I would have been thrilled to be able
to say I played a part in making a David Bowie album. Woweee, me and Boweee!
Chameleon of rock. Pilot of an inter-galactic ark, the Glam Warrior, upon which
I used to be a willing space-cadet. My hero! He was. Once upon a time, long ago
and far away . . .
Well, we all grow up and grow out of things, don't we? What was that Bowie
song? Ch-ch-changes . . . time may change me, but you can't trace time. A
ringing statement. Although what it meant, I never knew.
As for the current Bowie-Belcher interface? No big deal, really. So what part
did I play in making a disc Bowie has described as ``a non-linear gothic drama
hyper-cycle''? It was by default that I became involved, actually. It's what I
didn't do during the making of his current album Outside that made all the
difference. Kinda Zen, that. Kinda ambient. Kinda Bowie.
But hey, I'm not being a tease when I say that the true story of me and Bowie
must start at the start - in the summer of 1972, with teen-laddie me at home in
Manchester listening to John Peel on Radio 1.
John Lennon might have had his head turned by hearing Chuck Berry. For me it
was Ziggy Stardust, leper messiah, fuzzy guitars and rock'n'roll zip. The birth
of glam rock! Glam: cheap, gaudy, and a two-fingered, two-pronged affront.
For as well as thumbing its cute button-nose at the staid scruffiness of
hippiedom and heavy, lasting bands like Wishbone Ash and Budgie, glam blew a
raspberry at grey-suited Straightsville. Glam was purple lip-gloss;
navel-baring jumpers from Miss Selfridge; teetering tri-coloured platform
clogs, and long feather-cut hair with red and blonde streaks in it. But enough
of me. You should have seen what the girls were wearing.
I went to see Bowie play live that summer, just prior to the Ziggy phenomenon
taking nationwide effect. He wore a blue nylon bomber jacket with a fake-fur
collar, his jeans rolled up to knee-level, baseball boots, plus red and white
football socks. Bowie's hair stood up in a vermilion cockade. Gallus. The
perfect synthesis of soccer hooliganism and rock 'n' roll. And I was there:
ascloseasthis.
What did Bowie and his on-stage gang, the Spiders From Mars, sound like? Crisp,
punchy, fizzing.
I saw Bowie again in the same venue at Christmas. Not as good. The place was
more packed. I was further away from him. Stardom meant Bowie was literally
more distant.
What else? Mick Ronson performed execrable guitar solos; Bowie wore a
skintight, snake-print suit that would have made him the target of a terracing
ruckus rather than the leader of one. Over the next couple of years, I came to
see that mincing around pretending to be a hairdresser was much less fun than
going out with hairdressers - female ones.
A few months after that Bowie gig, I bade farewell to my own brief rock 'n'
roll career as Vincebus Eruptum's deeply-unconvincing leper-messiah vocalist.
We were playing a local school's under-14s disco. I sang Suffragette City.
``Put the records back on!'' the more discerning punters cried. Afterwards, one
lumpy young herbert wearing blue eye-shadow approached and said our Suffragette
City was chuffing great, loads better than Bowie's.
He was incorrect. In a similar way, I came to see Bowie as more flawed as time
passed. Nevertheless, I still bought the albums, still went to see him. Glasgow
Apollo, 1978, in his funky matelot outfit. 1983, Birmingham NEC; All I truly
remember is being several miles from the stage.
Later the same year Bowie played Murrayfield. Heading stagewards, his grey Ford
Granada, surrounded by a flying phalanx of security men, almost ran me over in
the car park. The perfect way to go, I thought. Then it rained a lot, and the
feeling receded. It didn't stop me going to Sunderland in 1987: the Glass
Spider tour. What is a glass spider? One of Bowie's concepts, and therefore not
worthy of rational explanation. The show was awful, with swarms of interpretive
dancers and Peter pigging Frampton on guitar, a rocker whose palpable
uselessness - show me a worse No 1 than Show Me The Way - helped spark the
great punk war in 1976.
Returning to Glasgow by car, my party traded ever-more indecipherable Bowie
lyrics through the night. Lyrics we had once hungrily absorbed, believing them
to be an expression of universal truths. The only truth was that Bowie had
become nostalgia, and empty nostalgia to boot.
Tin Machine? Tinny and mechanical. In 1991, the nadir: Bowie officially
flushing his old hits down the dumper on a tour which visited Ingliston's cold,
insulting concrete wastes.
And now he's back. Supported next week in Scotland by Morrissey. Shouldn't it
be the other way round? Why, Morrissey, why? I can but salute your undying
Mancunian glam-rock loyalty, sirrah. Maybe you and I flounced shoulder to
shoulder all those years ago. Boys keep swinging. I wonder what would you have
looked like as a 13-year-old in blue eye-shadow.
But back to the point: me and Bowie and Outside, the big deal. About a year
ago, I was dining in a swish Islington restaurant when David Bowie grandly
swept in, feet from my table, accompanied by a female aide. Was I excited? No.
Another 20 minutes passed. Holy guacamole! Here's Brian Eno heading towards
Bowie's table. Eno is one of Bowie's ex-collaborators; Eno ends up producing
Outside. Hindsight plainly identifies Outside as the project under discussion
that night in Islington.
Then, after another 15 minutes, in lopes U2 guitar-slinger the Edge. My dinner
companion and I are by now in a state of giggly ecstasy, taking bets on the
identity of Bowie's next guest. Aprs Eno, Bono? Or Ringo? Van Morrison? Jim
Morrison? Ten minutes later it's U2's manager, Paul McGuinness, who's joining
the Bowie table.
So how did I get more closely involved in the process of creative exchange
which ultimately led to Outside? Well, visiting the lavvy, I had to pass
Bowie's table. Asclosesasthis. I wanted to speak to him, but I couldn't. I
don't think he would have heard anyway. Yarking away in blokeish sarf Landan
tones, he was.
I wanted to tell Bowie that in order to re-kindle his muse-sort-of-thing, he
had to re-immerse himself in happening music - other peoples'. I could have
given him a long list. But I didn't. So that's why, without my advice, Outside
turned out the way it did - not very good.
Eh up, Davie Belch and D. Bowie. We've come a long way together over the past
23 years, but maybe not as far as either of us would admit.
n David Bowie, accompanied by Morrissey, visits Aberdeen's Exhibition Centre on
Wednesday, November 29, and Glasgow's SECC the following day.
</TEXT>
