<DOCNO>GH951123-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Oh Ma'am, look what a state we're in</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241381</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN may not be at ease with itself, but it is not a nation in despair and
fears that the nation's public institutions may be about to collapse under the
weight of criticism or social division appear misplaced, according to a new
report on British Social Attitudes by Social Community Planning &amp; Research
published today.
It reveals growing distrust in, and greater apathy about politics and
politicians, increased fear of crime, highest among those least at risk, and a
growing tendency to back punitive rather than libertarian attitudes. There has
been a marked decline in support over the past decade for the belief that it is
better to risk letting a guilty person go free than convict someone who is
innocent, one of the cornerstones of the British legal system.
As far as the Welfare State is concerned, the report warns politicians who
tamper with it to do so at their peril because the foundations of popular
support have ``never been more solid''. It admits this support is coloured by
self-interest, rather than altruism, but it is none the less real and no
evidence for social divisions threatening the Welfare State's stability was
found. There was also little support for moving away from the mass provision to
the flexible provision of services.
On Europe the report offers cold comfort for the Eurosceptics. Only 17% of the
population, compared with 42% 10 years ago, think we should withdraw, and the
closer links with Europe as compared with the United States, are favoured by a
two to one majority.
What must worry the Eurosceptics most is their failure         to attract
support among the young. They are overwhelmingly pro-integration, although the
fact that more Eurosceptics are Conservative supporters means that the
Eurosceptics will continue to get a sympathetic hearing within that party. On
the other hand, many ``natural'' Conservatives among the middle classes, put
off by an anti-integration stance, could be tempted by Labour's more
pro-European outlook, the report suggests.
Scottish devolution:
THE report found that one           in five Scots, and one in three people in
the UK were opposed to any reform at all. Among     the remainder the most
popular option was a devolved assembly.
q-Asked in 1992 about independence outside the UK and the EU, only 4% were in
favour, compared with 5% in 1994.
q-Asked about independence inside the EU, 9% were in favour in 1992 compared
with 10% in 1994.
q-Asked about Scotland remaining part of the UK with an assembly with some tax
and spending powers 52% were in favour in 1992, compared with 47% in 1994.
Taxation and paying for the Welfare State:
THE report notes the arguments about the need to change the Welfare State, but
it finds that the British public does not wish to either abandon or recast it
into ``new welfare''. People remain firmly wedded to the traditional Welfare
State, the bulk of whose resources are sunk into health, education, and
pensions. Asked if the Government should increase taxes and spend more on
health, education, and social benefits, 32% said yes in 1983 compared with 58%
in 1994.
Although health as a priority for spending started to decline over the 10 years
the report covers, dissatisfaction with the NHS resulted in the trend
reversing. In 1983 74% saw it as top priority, compared with 60% in 1993, and
72% in 1994.
The report found that people were unconvinced by official claims that the poor
are benefiting from rising living standards and is aware of the growth in
inequality over the past decade. Only 25% of those polled thought the poor
lived in need as the result of ``laziness or lack of willpower'', whereas one
in three endorsed the notion that it was due to ``injustice in our society''.
Fear of Crime:
FOR young women their fears about personal safety are linked to the
availability of pornography, while for elderly women fear of crime is most
strongly associated with unease about change in society in general. For elderly
men it is linked to other worries, such      as about their health. What
emerged was that fear of crime was a problem in itself, as           opposed to
being part and         parcel of problems about crime in general.
This casts doubt on whether reducing the fear of crime is something a
government can realistically aim to do. The   only appropriate way to reduce
fear is to cut crime itself by tackling the problem head on and adopting even
more vigorous measures.
Libertarianism in retreat?
ONE of the cornerstones of the British legal system is that the accused is
innocent until proved guilty. Asked whether it was worse to convict an innocent
person, or let a guilty one go free 20% chose the second option in 1985, 24% in
1994, while the don't knows rose from 12% to 18%. While libertarians may be
reassured, the report says the signs are that the cornerstone is beginning to
crumble.
Public support for the reintroduction of the death penalty also remains solid,
with three in five wanting it for all murders. In their eighth report,
following a series of miscarriages of justice, SCPR reckoned this support would
be dented, but they admit they were wrong. ``It seems that public support for
the death penalty is already at an irreducible minimum,'' they conclude.
People are more ready to cede powers to the police, resistance to the use of
surveillance cameras, for instance, having fallen.
q-In 1990 55% said they should be used to detect speeding drivers, in 1994 it
was 70% and there was a similar rise in favour of their use on housing estates
to detect vandals.
q-In 1990 37% were in favour of the introduction of identity cards, 40%
against. The balance is now two to one in favour, 53% as against 26%.
q-Public lack of confidence in the courts has risen from 79% who felt criminals
were getting off too lightly in 1990 to 86% in 1994, and the evidence emerging
is that the more hawkish stance taken by both the Government and Opposition
towards crime is in tune with public sentiment.
q-People have changed their minds about the right of peaceful protest. Asked in
1985 about holding meetings, 59% said they should be allowed. That has fallen
to 48% in 1994, and this is considered ``hardly reassuring'' from a libertarian
point of view.
q-Asked in 1994 if a rich person was more likely to be found guilty of a crime
only 2% agreed, whereas 66% thought if the person was poor they would be found
guilty, 10% up on 1990.
q-It found there was still a good deal of public sympathy for righting wrongs
on behalf of ethnic minorities, with 39% feeling we had not gone far enough in
giving equal opportunities to Asians and others of different ethnic origins.
Travelling people also fared well, with 44% thinking there should be more sites
provided, but homosexuals and lesbians get a raw deal, with 46% thinking things
have gone too far, 18% not far enough.
Growing distrust of, and public apathy about, politics and politicians:
THE sceptical electorate is alive and well. It seems that the British public is
losing whatever confidence it had in its politicians, and fewer than one in
four voters believe British governments of any party place the national
interest above their party's interest.
The monarchy:
WHEN they last asked the question in 1983 the results showed such overwhelming
support the SCPR thought there was little point in including questions again.
But it now finds that in the intervening 11 years there has been a change in
attitudes. Two-thirds still want to retain a monarchy, but in 1983 two in three
people believed it was important to keep the monarchy, now only one in three
take this view.
``The public's long-standing passion for its royal family has distinctly
cooled,'' the report concludes. ``While it is still regarded by the public as
comfortably the safest constitutional option available, it is perhaps no longer
seen as indispensable.''
n-British Social Attitudes, the 12th report, Dartmouth Publishing Company, #25.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
