<HEADLINE>Macbeth, Greenwich Theatre, London</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nicola Dillon</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241382</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Macbeth, Greenwich Theatre, London
MARK Rylance's production of Macbeth is his first staging of a Shakespeare play
since The Globe announced his appointment as their artistic director. Rylance
is also artistic director of Thoebus Cart which is producing his current vision
of Macbeth. He and his company have taken the non-traditional approach but in
this case their interpretation is misguided.
Duncan and his thanes are presented as a Hare Krishna-type sect and their power
struggles are set in that context. As a result the characters struggle. Only
Tim Barlow, as an excellent Porter, and Albie Woodington as Macduff, appear
comfortable. The weird sisters, played as dysfunctional youths, add nothing to
the play. Mark Rylance plays Macbeth as a hesistant and gauche American
introvert. Jane Horrocks's Lady Macbeth lacks the steely quality necessary to
convince us that she could persuade her husband to kill Duncan.
While it could be interesting to explore why religion can inspire murder, and
sects can be riven by power politics, Shakespeare does not provide the words to
enable Macbeth to be the vehicle for that exploration. Mark Rylance is an
exceptionally fine actor and only this quality keeps the audience in their
seats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Professor James McGilvray</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241383</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Professor James W McGilvray, economist and academic; born February 21, 1938,
died November 19, 1995
JAMES McGilvray was born in Glasgow in 1938, and educated at Kelvinside Academy
and later at St Columba's College near Dublin. He grew up at Huntershill House
in Bishopbriggs, earlier the home of Thomas Muir, the exiled reformer; much of
his childhood was spent in the company of his mother's family in Ireland.
In 1960 he graduated with honours in economics from Edinburgh University and
took up a lectureship at Trinity College, Dublin, where he remained for nine
years. Following a year spent at Harvard on a research fellowship, where he
worked with the Nobel Laureate Wassilly Leontief, he was appointed as senior
lecturer in economics at Stirling University.
In 1975 he and I were appointed to the foundation posts of research director
and director respectively, at the newly established Fraser and Allander
Institute at Strathclyde University. His first major assignment there was to
lead the tripartite team, drawn from IBM, the Scottish Council (Development &amp;
Industry), and the Fraser of Allander Institute itself, which in 1979 completed
the compilation of the first ever set of input/output tables for Scotland.
Responsibility for the production of these tables on a regular basis has now
been adopted by the Government. He was also the founder and first editor of the
Institute's Quarterly Economic Commentary, and established the
subscription-based Business Forecasting Service.
At the same time he led the institute's team in a development project in
Morocco, the first of many such projects he was to lead over the next 15 years
in countries ranging from Egypt and Jordan to Angola and Albania. These
projects were typically funded by the World Bank, the United Nations
Development Programme, and the European Commission.
In 1985 to 1988 he took leave of absence to direct the economics division of a
London-based international consulting company, thereby deepening and widening
his experience of the practical application of economics to the problems of
developing countries.
Being responsible for the management as well as the technical content of a wide
range of collaborative projects stood him in good stead when he returned to
Strathclyde University. He became joint director of the university's Overseas
Development Services Office, which acts as a link between the university and
international development agencies in the provision of research. consultancy,
and training services.
From August 1991 to July 1994 he was head of the Department of Economics, and
in August 1993 was appointed vice-dean for Research of the Strathclyde Business
School Faculty.
A recent assignment from the European Commission to survey the functioning of
the official statistical offices in several Eastern European countries, led him
to throw his weight behind the proposal to establish a Centre for European
Economies in Transition.
As well as all these activities, he found the time to write a number of books
on economics and statistics. Only a few days before he died, he completed the
preface of a book jointly written with two colleagues on Natural Resources and
Environmental Economics.
He leaves behind his wife, Alison, his son and daughter, and his mother, who
lives in Dublin, and very many friends throughout the world.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000155</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000155</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Car workers prepare to turn screw</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Roy Rogers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241384</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Roy Rogers explains why motor manufacturing employees are ready
again to flex their industrial muscle
FORD and Vauxhall car workers threatening industrial action after rejecting
inflation-busting pay offers against a background of recurring strikes by
Scottish posties and Merseyside firefighters may give the impression that
another ``winter of discontent'' is in the offing.
In fact, Ford and Vauxhall workers are most unlikely to embark on strike
action, the post and fire disputes remain localised even though they involve
national issues, and the overall rate of days lost through strike action
remains at a historical low.
Scottish postal workers are incensed at what they see as Post Office attempts
to undermine second deliveries prior to axing jobs. There is nothing new in
Communications Workers Union members fighting for services and jobs, but on
this occasion they have jumped the gun by walking out before a strike ballot
has been completed.
What is new is that the resurgence of the British motor industry has meant that
car workers feel more confident in their futures and therefore better able to
challenge what they see as the inequities in their sector.
Union officials have decided that the time is ripe to win concessions on hours
for Ford and Vauxhall employees who still work a 39-hour week when their Ford
and General Motors counterparts get paid more for working a 35-hour week in
Germany, workers at Ford's Jaguar subsidiary receive higher wages for operating
a 37-hour week as do employees of Rover Group and Rolls-Royce Motors.
Nissan and Toyota have let it be known that they will follow any Ford-Vauxhall
concessions on hours and Peugeot Talbot would have little choice but to follow
suit.
The unions therefore are keen to bring the rest of the motor manufacturing
industry into line with the bulk of the engineering industry which is already
on a 37-hour week as a result of the highly successful shorter working week
campaign waged by the Confederation of Shipbuilding and Engineering Unions five
years ago.
The CSEU, which has a #10m ``war chest'' left over from the confrontation, is
poised to reopen that campaign in order to mop up any remaining areas of
resistance to 37 hours before seeking to press for further reductions.
So, after years of being in the doldrums during which the UK car industry has
become highly competitive, mainly through having to compete with new
Japanese-owned UK plants, British car workers who had the reputation for
walking out at the drop of a hat in the 70s, feel that once again they can at
least flex their industrial muscles.
Even so, Vauxhall workers are only talking about banning overtime and leaving
two hours early on Fridays and union negotiators are by no means confident of
winning a strike mandate from Ford workers even though several thousands walked
out on unofficial stoppages last week.
National officials including Scottish AEEU councillor Jimmy Airlie and TGWU
national secretary Tony Woodley are expected to tour the Ford plants before an
industrial action ballot is called.
It remains to be seen whether their powers of persuasion can produce a strike
mandate sufficent to convince Ford of the need to concede reduced hours. It
appears most unlikely but, even if thwarted this time round, the unions will
certainly be back pressing for shorter hours when negotiations become due again
in two years' time. The issue will not go away and at some stage the company
will have to face up to conceding shorter hours or facing a dispute.
A winter of discontent therefore appears most unlikely this time round although
one may not be far off as dissatisfaction builds among Britain's 1.5 million
local government workers who have seen their pay restricted by Government
ruling for the past five years and who can expect no respite under this
Government.
The local authority unions, which bore most of the blame for the 1978-9
``winter of discontent'' which was seen as ushering in the ``Thatcher years'',
have yet to be convinced that things would be any better under Labour however.
Labour leader Tony Blair has been told of the likelihood of a dust up over
local authority pay either in the run in to the next General Election or soon
after it. Either way it could spell deep embarrassment for Labour, although
according to union sources Labour has no policy on public sector pay as yet.
A substantial claim is due       to be lodged soon on behalf of the 1.5 million
blue and white-collar local authority staff who come together this year for the
first common claim for a common April 1 pay date.
With a total pay bill of #7.3 billion, some 85% of which comes from central
government, the local authority negotiations are by far the largest and
therefore most significant.
About 350,000 currently earn less than the #4.15 an hour minimum expected to
figure in the unions' demand - with many cleaners and catering staff on just
#3.71 an hour which would require increases of up to 11.8%. It is estimated
that it would cost some 3% on the total pay bill just to bring everybody up to
the #4.15 minimum.
A ``winter of discontent'' is forecast - but probably not this winter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
