<HEADLINE>Runner, CCA Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241386</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IMAGES of restriction, images of endurance - and ultimately the image of an
inner resilience than can transcend the rigours that beset the physical self.
These are the core themes of Runner, a new project which Marisa Zanotti is
currently showing as a work-in-progress at the CCA.
The ideas started forming a couple of years back, while she was reading Brian
Keenan's autobiography, An Evil Cradling. Zanotti found herself translating his
description of the conditions he endured as a hostage into her own imagined
actuality - what kind of space, for instance, would give her small frame the
same sense of cooped-up oppression as his 6ft ; 4ft cell? What kind of
movements could you achieve to try to keep your body from packing up through
lack of exercise? And how would you keep your spirits from simply crumbling
into terminal despair?
Just over three weeks ago, she started putting together her material - solo
movement, selected music, a snatch of text, some video projections (by Bert
Ross), and, latterly, atmospheric lighting by Bob Pringle. Karen Grant sat in
as an ``outside eye'' to help shape a running order for the piece so far.
Results so far are both promising and effective.
Ross's projections add a stunning extra dimension, not least when a moving map
floods the floor while Zanotti strives to keep her balance - it's as if none of
us knows where we are, even as she tries to find her own place.
The after-show discussion was a useful, informal exchange which probably
encouraged her even as it gave the audience valuable insights into the process
of devising. Running is already worth seeing in its beginning form - repeated
tonight, with hopes of the complete work showing next May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
