<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975241387</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sergei Grinkov, skater; born February 4, 1967, died November 20, 1995
RUSSIAN Olympic champion figure skater Sergei Grinkov suffered from severe
heart disease that led to his fatal heart attack on the ice-rink at Lake
Placid, New York on Monday.
Grinkov, 28, had a history of high blood pressure and the twice Olympic
champion suffered from severe arteriosclerosis, according to Dr Francis Varga.
``In an athletic, vigorous young person who is asymptomatic, it is hard to
detect these problems,'' said Dr Varga. ``Sudden death is often the first sign
of heart disease. Unless there is an abnormality that causes pain, there is no
way to detect this.''
He was practising with his wife, Ekaterina Gordeeva, 24, for a figure skating
exhibition on Saturday in the professional Stars On Ice tour.
The two had skated together since he was 15 and she was 11 years old. In the
early years the disparity in their sizes (she was then under 5ft and weighed
less than six stones) produced a certain incongruity in their appearance. But
there were compensations. Katya could easily be lifted overhead with one hand
or thrown into spectacular jumps.
Grinkov and Gordeeva were Olympic pairs champions in 1988 and 1994. They also
won four world championships, two European titles, and the Soviet national
championships as amateurs. Having turned professional in 1990 and subsequently
married, they had competed in professional championships, but then - like
Britain's Torvill and Dean - took advantage of the decision of the
International Olympic Committee to allow professionals to skate in the 1994
Winter Olympic Games.
The Grinkovs brought pairs figure skating to new artistic and athletic heights
with powerful lifts and stunning throws executed to music as varied as Mozart,
Beethoven, and honkey-tonk.
They lived with their three-year-old daughter Daria in Simsbury, Connecticut,
and in Moscow.
</TEXT>
