<HEADLINE>Traffic decline at airport</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241388</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COULD I make one or two observations on your editorial, Traffic-island airport
(November 14). The decline in this summer's traffic at Glasgow Airport is now
well researched and known.
The withdrawal of United and Northwest Airlines would, all other things being
equal, have reduced the passenger growth at Glasgow Airport by 1% to 2%. That
was our forecast last year and was achieved in April to June.
Since then two other factors have come into play. Detailed passenger surveys
show that some passengers have transferred from Glasgow Airport to Edinburgh
Airport because of road congestion. By far the most important influence has
been the decline in the holiday traffic. Your newspaper has accurately reported
the tribulations of the tour operators this summer - and these certainly have
not been leaves on the line.
As well as Glasgow Airport the other main holiday charter airports in the UK
have shown identical decline in passengers - for example Manchester Airport's
international traffic was down 4.2% last month. In fact the last two weeks of
October were level pegging and the first two weeks of November have seen
Glasgow Airport back into growth.
But the key issue of your editorial must not go unanswered. There are no
grounds for complacency over the surface transport problems in Glasgow and we
welcome your support.
V.L Murphy,
Managing Director,
Scottish Airports Ltd,
St Andrew's Drive,
Glasgow Airport,
Paisley.
</TEXT>
