<HEADLINE>Penetrator, Tron Theatre, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sara Villiers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241390</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Theatre
MEG RYAN eat your heart out; Paul Blair's opening orgasm scene might not be as
pretty as the Hollywood starlet's number in the deli but it's certainly more
convincing. Despite the graphic content of the play there's no on-stage nudity
but nineties lads are laid bare none the less. Anthony Neilson's superbly
crafted play thrusts into the male psyche with a rigour and insight which is by
turns hilarious and horrific but always compulsive.
As an exploration of the point when the bonds of male friendship turn into
manacles, either corporeal ones through physical intimidation or spiritual ones
through emotional betrayal, it's a devastating account. An evening of banter
between Max (Blair) and his flatmate Alan (Joel Strachan) is transformed when
Max's childhood friend, the squaddie Tadge, turns up with a maniacal account of
persecution, paranoia, and rape at the hands of the so-called ``penetrators''.
The quick-witted humour, flecked with masculine defensiveness of the opening
scenes - which includes an excellent description of dance music as being ``a
three-hour record which sounded like a mixture of international dialling
codes'' - slowly dissolves into an atmosphere of intimidation, as Tadge imposes
a threatening presence. But the real weapon he brings is not the terrifying
machete he carelessly brandishes but the candour of a ravaged mind - forcing
the others into an unwanted exploration of their homosexual and homophobic
desires.
John Kazek delivers an outstanding performance, physically and mentally adroit
at portraying the febrile tension and occasional vulnerability of a psychotic,
while Blair and Strachan offer stolid support in a production directed and
designed by Peter Mackie Bruns which speaks directly, if brutally, to a young
generation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
