<HEADLINE>university status</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241391</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
University status
IT was interesting to read the excellent article by Barclay McBain on the story
of Strathclyde University (November 18).
However, I would like to correct a statement about the actual process of
acquiring university status.
The mistake in his article is made by members of staff of the university and as
the person involved from start to finish I would like to put the record
straight in The Herald as this might finally correct the error.
The University Grants Committee, represented by Sir Keith Murray, took the view
in 1960 that there was no need to make us a university. I fought my case
strenuously and early in 1961 Sir Keith (now Lord Murray) said his committee
had unanimously agreed the Royal College in Glasgow should proceed to request
formally university status.
His committee could virtually guarantee the Privy Council would give us a royal
charter and statutes and he asked me to start writing them. Early in 1962 an
official announcement was made that government had accepted the case for
university status for the Royal College.
It should be noted Glasgow was the first British city to win the privilege of
having a second university. Murray urged me to continue to build strength in
arts and social sciences, where we were making rapid progress.
There was never any condition about ``merging'' with the Scottish College of
Commerce. However the director of that college, Dr Eric Thomson, asked me to
absorb the Scottish College in the Royal College if I could.
So it was a case of absorbing into the Royal College, already sure in its own
right of university status. There was, in fact, a need to persuade the
University Grants Committee, representing the Government, that the Scottish
College of Commerce could be successfully swallowed.
The point I am anxious to make is that the Royal College as such was already
simply waiting for its charter and statutes to be blessed by Privy Council and
the absorption of the Scottish College was a separate step in its process of
growth.
The process of swallowing was difficult but achieved by the Royal College as
Strathclyde over some years.
Privy Council was slow in passing the charter because it hoped to take into
account some ideas of Lord Robbins but no reference to Robbins was asked of the
Royal College.
Robbins advocated others should do what the Royal had done and intended to do.
So Strathclyde became a university on its own and after some time, and partly
with help from Robbins, a number of colleges of advanced technology and science
were given university status.
Sir Sam Curran,
First Principal of
Strathclyde University,
93 Kelvin Court,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Society that will not see Much to be learned from West case</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241392</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE can hardly be a person in the land who
A senior official in a children's charity reminded us yesterday that adults
must learn to listen to children, especially when they give out signals which
may suggest problems within their family. Paedophiles, she said with utter
truth, are very plausible people. We should remember that the West murders were
discovered only when an alert social worker took seriously a remark made by a
child and reported the ensuing suspicions to police. Thankfully that was one
social worker who refused to be intimidated into silence by the habitual abuse
meted out to that most beleaguered of professions by the tabloid media and
certain politicians. Nevertheless, the lessons which must be learned from the
West case are of particular relevance to health and care agencies who must
always be willing to accept that procedures and practices require constant
updating in the light of experience.
In the particular case of the West family it is clear that school, health, and
social services officials were involved on several occasions with a variety of
the West children. These included incidents of some seriousness, such as
grossly inappropriate health problems for young children, evidence of assault,
and the removal from school of a child still of school age. A criminal court
merely fined the Wests for the serious indecent assault of a teenage lodger and
nobody in the legal system saw the need to pass the results to those who would
investigate further. In retrospect there is an abundance of evidence that much
was wrong in the West household, but that the procedures at the time were
insufficient to ensure that information was circulated between the relevant
agencies.
It is by no means clear that this is a problem which has been solved. It is
true that child protection procedures in the early 1970s were rudimentary
compared with those of today; it is also the fact that the various health and
care agencies and the police were only instructed to work together after the
Cleveland report in 1988, by which time the dreadful events in the West
household had already taken place. Yet it remains the case that few care
professionals today would express complete satisfaction with existing liaison
procedures between relevant agencies. Nor is there yet a sufficient recognition
of the fact that children must be listened to and taken seriously when they
give hints of dark areas in their lives.
What, then, must we make of our society in the light of the West case? It is
the job of government to craft and mould the legislation and practices and to
provide the resources for the various agencies which try to protect society.
There are many areas in which government social legislation can be criticised
over the past two decades; from the notorious assertion that there is no such
thing as society (meant sincerely, whether quoted in or out of context) to the
modern fixation for blaming single mothers, foreigners, and benefits cheats for
the manifest failure of social policy.
Yet in the West case government stands innocent: there are limits to what a
government can do and it is one of the silliest mistakes to blame a few
disparate individuals in Westminster for evils which are hardly capable of
being prevented by the passage of legislation. There is a responsibility which
must be borne by all of us; it rests in the growing lack of community feeling
which separates the sinews and bones of society, one from the other. The West
case reminds us that there are countless missing persons in this small country,
many of them vulnerable youngsters; how can this be? Neighbours turn a blind
eye to the abuse of children and old folk in their own street, whether it be
physical abuse or cold neglect, and the harshness and self-seeking aspects of
our society become daily more evident. Of course we must keep these criticisms
in balance, but will anyone deny their truth? The West case can indeed be a
learning experience for all of us, but only if we are willing to learn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951123-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951123-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>951123</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Payments to workers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975241393</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE compensation payments to four Glasgow University animal laboratory workers
who contracted asthma raises several questions (November 21).
If conditions in the animal house adversely affected the staff how can we know
that those conditions did not affect the animals and the results of the
experiments in which they were used?
Was this situation unique to Glasgow University or are we about to see a flood
of compensation claims from workers in other laboratories, poultry farms, and
the like?
If, as claimed by one of the injured workers, Government officials carried out
regular welfare checks on the animals, why was their welfare compromised by
allowing researchers to experiment on them and then kill them? The answer to
these questions is fairly simple. If the animals were affected by dusty
conditions it is likely that would affect the results of experiments they were
used in. At #50,000 a shot it is very likely that more claims will follow.
Government inspectors from the Home Office only ensure animals are used within
the boundaries of the 1986 Animals (Scientific Procedures) Act which allows
animals to suffer pain, stress, and death.
John F Robins,
Organising Secretary,
Animal Concern,
62 Old Dumbarton Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
